module.exports={"dreams-vista-cancun-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Vista Cancun and Secrets Puerto Los Cabos match on overall rating (8.9) and value (8.7), but diverge sharply in audience and amenity depth. Dreams Vista is a family resort in Cancun with a flowrider, waterpark for little kids, kids club for under-4s, teen club, arcade, diving, windsurfing, and rooms for 5+, supported by a strong service score (9.0) and cleanliness (9.2). Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is adults-only in San Jose del Cabo with a quieter, more refined atmosphere (8.0 vs 7.1), slightly better food (8.1 vs 7.6), cleaner rooms (9.4 vs 9.2), and a location score of 8.6 vs 8.3. Secrets trades the family infrastructure for a calmer environment with archery, fishing, and a swim-up bar, but its beach scores lower (3.5 vs 4.0) and sleep quality lags (8.1 vs 8.8), likely reflecting a livelier bar scene. Dreams Vista wins on activity breadth; Secrets wins on food, atmosphere, and adult-focused refinement.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a high-energy Cancun all-inclusive with a flowrider, waterpark, kids club from infancy, teen club, arcade, diving, and windsurfing — all without reservation hassles and with rooms large enough for five or more.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a quieter, design-forward Los Cabos all-inclusive with better food, a refined atmosphere, swim-up bar, golf, fishing, and archery, without the noise and activity of a family resort.","whenToVisit":"Cancun's peak season runs December through April when weather is dry and settled; hurricane season (June–October) brings lower prices but real storm risk. Los Cabos is drier year-round with very low hurricane exposure, making it a more reliable late-summer or fall option. Both resorts sit at the $$$$ price tier, so shoulder months — May and November — offer the best balance of value and conditions at either property.","activities":"Dreams Vista guests can dive, windsurf, rent watersports equipment, ride the flowrider, or play golf on-site, with Cancun's Hotel Zone offering nearby cenote tours, Chichen Itza day trips, and Isla Mujeres ferry excursions. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos guests can fish, play archery, golf, or explore San Jose del Cabo's art district and galleries, with Land's End rock formations and whale-watching tours (December–April) easily accessible from the marina."},"dreams-jade-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Jade Resort & Spa is a large family all-inclusive on Mexico's Caribbean coast near Puerto Morelos, with a kids club for under-4s, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, diving, bicycles, tennis, and rooms for five or more guests. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Pacific side in San Jose del Cabo, with a golf course, yoga, mini golf, and notably higher ratings for rooms (9.1 vs 8.6), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.9), service (9.1 vs 8.8), food (8.1 vs 7.4), pool (7.8 vs 6.9), and atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.8). Dreams Jade edges ahead only on beach score (4.8 vs 3.5), though both beaches rate poorly. Dreams Jade is the family-focused Caribbean option with broader activity programming for kids; Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is the more polished, quieter adults-only Pacific resort where room quality, dining, and service meaningfully outperform.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Caribbean all-inclusive near Puerto Morelos, with a lazy river, kids club from infancy, teen programming, babysitting, diving, and large rooms accommodating five or more guests.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a refined, adults-only all-inclusive in Los Cabos with standout room quality, cleanliness, and service scores, plus golf course access and a more relaxed, intimate atmosphere on the Pacific coast.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Jade on the Caribbean coast benefits from November through April when hurricane risk drops and humidity eases, though summers can bring tropical weather. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos on the Pacific enjoys sunshine nearly year-round, with October and November occasionally seeing late-season Pacific storms. Los Cabos's desert climate means drier, more predictable conditions across most of the year compared to the Yucatan's humid Caribbean side.","activities":"Dreams Jade guests can explore the Puerto Morelos reef—one of Mexico's few protected national marine parks—snorkel, dive, fish, cycle into the quiet town, or take excursions to Tulum and Chichen Itza. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos guests can golf on-site, take sport-fishing charters into the Sea of Cortez, visit the famous El Arco rock formation by boat, explore San Jose del Cabo's art district, or ATV through the Baja desert."},"dreams-estrella-del-mar-mazatlan-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Estrella del Mar Mazatlán is a family all-inclusive on Mexico's Pacific coast in Mazatlán, built around a waterpark, lazy river, kids clubs for all ages, babysitting, and a full beach setup. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only all-inclusive in San José del Cabo with a nightclub, archery, fishing, and mini golf, aimed squarely at couples and solo travelers. The most striking gap is in beach ratings: Dreams scores 6.8 versus Secrets' 3.5, reflecting the notoriously rough, swim-unfriendly surf at Los Cabos. Dreams edges ahead on overall score (9.0 vs 8.9), rooms (9.5 vs 9.1), value (8.9 vs 8.7), and sleep quality (9.1 vs 8.1). Secrets counters with better food (8.1 vs 7.6), a stronger pool rating (7.8 vs 7.3), and a livelier adults-only atmosphere (8.0 vs 7.5). Both share the same price tier, cleanliness score, and service ratings. Dreams is the family-oriented Pacific beach resort; Secrets is the couple-focused Baja escape where the pool replaces the ocean.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of any age who want a Pacific Mexico all-inclusive with a waterpark, lazy river, dedicated kids clubs including under-4s, babysitting, and genuine beach access at strong value for the price tier.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adults-only travelers who want a polished Baja California all-inclusive with better dining, a nightclub, fishing, archery, and a golf course, and who are comfortable with a pool-focused holiday given Los Cabos' limited swimming beach.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit on Mexico's Pacific side and share broadly similar seasonality. December through April is dry season for both, offering the most reliable sunshine. Mazatlán's hurricane season runs June through October, with peak risk in September. Los Cabos faces similar tropical storm risk in late summer, with September the most active month. Shoulder months of November and May offer good value and thinner crowds at both properties.","activities":"At Dreams Mazatlán, guests can explore Mazatlán's historic centro, ride the malecón, and visit the Angela Peralta Theater, with on-site golf, spa, and waterpark rounding out the program. At Secrets Los Cabos, guests can arrange whale-watching excursions from November to March, sport fishing in the Sea of Cortez, and day trips to the famous Arch at Cabo San Lucas, complemented by on-site archery, mini golf, golf, and spa facilities."},"dreams-vallarta-bay-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Vallarta Bay Resort & Spa is a family-focused all-inclusive on Mexico's Pacific Coast in Puerto Vallarta, with a kids club, teen club, pool slide, heated pool, diving, babysitting, and swim-up bar at a lively beach resort. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos Golf & Spa Resort is an adults-only all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo with a golf course, archery, yoga, and notably higher ratings for food (8.1 vs 7.5), rooms (9.1 vs 8.8), pool (7.8 vs 6.9), cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.0), atmosphere (8.0 vs 7.1), and service (9.1 vs 9.0). The trade-off is the beach: Dreams rates 6.0 against Secrets' very weak 3.5, while Dreams also offers more water-based activities including diving and fishing. Both resorts share the same overall score of 8.9 and price tier. Dreams is the clear pick for families wanting an active, beach-adjacent Puerto Vallarta holiday, while Secrets suits couples prioritizing refined dining, polished rooms, and golf over swimming in the ocean.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-service Puerto Vallarta all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, pool slide, diving, babysitting, and swim-up bar in a lively Pacific Coast setting where beach access, however modest, is part of the package.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and golfers who want a polished, adults-only San Jose del Cabo all-inclusive with superior food, immaculate rooms, yoga, archery, and an on-site golf course, and who can accept that the beach is essentially not a draw at this property.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Vallarta's dry season runs November through April, making those months ideal for Dreams Vallarta Bay. Los Cabos enjoys year-round sunshine with low humidity, but September and October carry hurricane risk at both destinations. Winter and early spring offer the most reliable weather across both resorts, with December through February being peak season and commanding premium pricing.","activities":"Dreams Vallarta Bay guests can dive, fish, play tennis, and access Puerto Vallarta's vibrant Malecon boardwalk, old town, and whale-watching excursions from November to March. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos guests can play golf, practice archery, take yoga classes, and explore nearby San Jose del Cabo's art district and gallery walks on Thursdays, with Cabo San Lucas's sportfishing and sea-lion snorkeling a short drive away."},"dreams-macao-beach-punta-cana-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Macao Beach Punta Cana is a large Dominican Republic family all-inclusive on a strong beach (7.8) with a waterpark, lazy river, kids club, teen club, diving, snorkelling, and watersports, scoring a standout 9.2 for cleanliness and 8.9 for location. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only Mexican resort in San Jose del Cabo with a golf course, spa, and polished rooms (9.1), but its beach rating is a striking 3.5 versus Dreams' 7.8, and sleep quality trails at 8.1. Food is a meaningful gap too: Secrets scores 8.1 versus Dreams' 7.6, giving the Mexican resort an edge at the table. Dreams wins on beach, family infrastructure, and watersports breadth; Secrets wins on food, room quality, spa, golf, and the adults-only atmosphere. Both are priced at the same level and share identical value scores of 8.7, so the choice comes down to beach versus golf, families versus couples, and the Caribbean versus the Pacific coast of Mexico.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a strong Caribbean beach, a waterpark, lazy river, kids and teen clubs, babysitting, diving, and snorkelling in a consistently clean, well-serviced Dominican Republic resort with rooms that can accommodate five or more guests.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and golfers who want a refined, adults-only Mexican resort with a spa, golf course, strong food program, and elegant rooms near San Jose del Cabo, and who can accept that the beach here is one of the weakest-rated in the category.","whenToVisit":"Punta Cana is driest and busiest December through April; hurricane season peaks August through October but storms are manageable. San Jose del Cabo enjoys near-year-round sunshine, with September being the most active hurricane month on the Pacific side. Both resorts are popular over the winter holidays, so booking early is essential for either destination during peak season.","activities":"At Dreams Macao, guests can dive, snorkel, rent watersports equipment, play tennis, practice archery and yoga, and use the waterparks and lazy river, all within a lively Punta Cana beach setting. At Secrets Los Cabos, guests can golf, fish, use the spa, play mini golf, practice archery and yoga, and explore San Jose del Cabo's art district and restaurants nearby. Neither resort lacks for evening entertainment or a swim-up bar."},"dreams-karibana-cartagena-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Karibana Cartagena and Secrets Puerto Los Cabos share an identical overall rating of 8.9 and the same price tier, but diverge sharply in audience and amenities. Dreams Karibana is a family-friendly Colombian all-inclusive on the Caribbean coast of Cartagena, with a kids club for infants and up, babysitting, pets allowed, and an on-site golf course. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only Mexican resort in San Jose del Cabo with a swim-up bar, nightclub, archery, yoga, fishing, and mini golf. On food, Secrets leads by a meaningful 1.1 points (8.1 vs 7.0), and its pool rating is notably higher (7.8 vs 6.9). Both resorts score poorly on beach — Secrets at 3.5, Dreams at 4.5 — reflecting that neither offers a classic swimming beach. Secrets edges Dreams on cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.1), service (9.1 vs 8.9), and atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.8), while Dreams holds a slight advantage on location (8.2 vs 8.6 goes to Secrets). Dreams is the clear choice for families; Secrets is built entirely around adult escapes.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of any age, including infants, who want a well-rated Colombian all-inclusive in historic Cartagena with a kids club, babysitting, on-site golf, and high marks for rooms, cleanliness, and service — and who do not need a strong beach or dining experience.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults-only couples and solo travelers who want a polished Baja California Sur resort with strong food ratings, a swim-up bar, nightclub, yoga, archery, fishing, and one of the highest cleanliness and service scores in its category, without the presence of children.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Karibana in Cartagena is best visited December through April during Colombia's dry season, avoiding the heavier rains of October and November. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos in San Jose del Cabo benefits from Baja's near year-round sunshine, though hurricane season runs June through October; November through May offers the most reliable, comfortable conditions for both resorts.","activities":"At Dreams Karibana, guests can explore UNESCO-listed Cartagena's walled old city, take boat trips to the Rosario Islands, and play the on-site golf course. At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, guests can fish the Sea of Cortez, take yoga classes, try archery, play mini golf, and access the San Jose del Cabo art district, with whale watching available December through April."},"dreams-riviera-cancun-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Riviera Cancun and Secrets Puerto Los Cabos share the same overall rating tier (8.8 vs 8.9) and price level, but differ sharply in audience and setting. Dreams is a family resort in Puerto Morelos on the Caribbean side, with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, pool slide, babysitting, and diving — a full infrastructure for families. Secrets Los Cabos is an adults-only resort on the Pacific side in San Jose del Cabo, built around golf, archery, yoga, and fishing, with a notably higher food score (8.1 vs 7.5), better room rating (9.1 vs 8.7), and cleaner facilities (9.4 vs 9.1). The beach scores are weak at both properties, but Secrets scores even lower (3.5 vs 4.8), reflecting the rugged Pacific coastline typical of Los Cabos. Dreams compensates with its lazy river and water features. If you want a Caribbean family all-inclusive with water park elements, kids programming, and solid service near Cancun, go to Dreams Riviera Cancun. If you want a polished adults-only Pacific Mexico retreat with superior dining, golf, and refined rooms, go to Secrets Puerto Los Cabos.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a Caribbean-side Mexican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, pool slide, babysitting, and diving, all within easy reach of Cancun airport in the quieter Puerto Morelos corridor.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want a refined, adults-only Pacific Mexico resort with a golf course, yoga, archery, fishing, superior dining, and elegantly rated rooms in the upscale San Jose del Cabo area.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Riviera Cancun is best November through April, avoiding the Caribbean hurricane season that peaks August through October. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos enjoys year-round sunshine on the Pacific side, though July and August bring higher humidity and occasional tropical storms. Both resorts are busiest over US holiday periods; January through March offers the best balance of weather and manageable crowds at both properties.","activities":"At Dreams Riviera Cancun, guests can dive the nearby Mesoamerican Reef, snorkel Puerto Morelos's protected marine park, or explore the town's low-key artisan market. At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, guests can golf the on-site course, arrange deep-sea fishing charters, visit the historic San Jose del Cabo art district, or take day trips to the iconic Land's End arch at Cabo San Lucas, about 30 minutes away."},"breathless-riviera-cancun-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Riviera Cancun and Secrets Puerto Los Cabos are both adults-only Mexican all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they differ meaningfully in setting, beach quality, and activity range. Breathless sits on the Caribbean coast near Cancun with an actual beach, though its beach rating of 4.8 signals it is far from a standout stretch of sand. Secrets is in San Jose del Cabo on the Pacific, where the beach scores an even lower 3.5, making swimming conditions genuinely limited at both properties. Secrets edges Breathless on nearly every service metric: food (8.1 vs 7.6), rooms (9.1 vs 8.9), cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.1), service (9.1 vs 8.9), and value (8.7 vs 8.4). Breathless counters with a heated pool and a livelier, nightclub-forward atmosphere (7.4) that leans into its younger, party-adjacent brand identity. Secrets adds golf, archery, fishing, yoga, and mini golf, giving it a broader activity roster for guests who want structured daytime pursuits beyond the pool. Both carry the same overall rating gap of just 0.1 (8.9 vs 8.8).","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a lively Caribbean adults-only resort near Cancun with a heated pool, swim-up bar, and a nightclub-driven atmosphere. Best for couples or groups prioritizing evening entertainment and a more energetic social scene over daytime activity variety.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults seeking a polished, service-oriented Los Cabos resort with top-tier rooms, consistently strong food ratings, and a broad activity menu including golf, fishing, archery, and yoga. Ideal for couples who want refined comfort and structured daytime pursuits over a party atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Breathless Riviera Cancun is best visited November through April to avoid Caribbean hurricane season and peak humidity. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos benefits from Los Cabos' more stable, desert-dry climate, making it viable nearly year-round, though July and August bring higher humidity and occasional tropical moisture. Both resorts command peak pricing over US holiday weeks.","activities":"At Breathless, guests focus on the pool, swim-up bar, beach access, and evening entertainment and nightclub programming. Secrets offers a considerably wider daytime activity range with an on-site golf course, fishing excursions, archery, yoga classes, and mini golf alongside its pool and spa. Both properties include spa facilities, gyms, and no-reservation dining across multiple restaurants."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-riviera-cancun-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos Golf & Spa Resort is an adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Baja Peninsula in San Jose del Cabo, with a golf course, fishing, archery, mini golf, and yoga, earning stronger scores across overall (8.9 vs 8.6), food (8.1 vs 7.7), pool (7.8 vs 7.1), atmosphere (8.0 vs 7.5), location (8.6 vs 8.2), and rooms (9.1 vs 9.0). Its beach rating of 3.5 is notably weak, reflecting the Pacific-facing coast's rougher surf. Secrets Riviera Cancun sits on the Caribbean side near Cancun with a meaningfully better beach rating (4.8 vs 3.5) and a higher sleep quality score (9.0 vs 8.1), but a thinner amenity roster with no golf, fishing, archery, or yoga on offer. Los Cabos wins on activities, food, and atmosphere; Riviera Cancun wins on beachfront quality and quieter nights. Both share the same premium price tier and near-identical service scores of 9.1.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who prioritize a full activity slate — golf, fishing, archery, yoga — over beach swimming, and want the dramatic desert-meets-ocean landscape of Los Cabos with stronger food ratings and a livelier atmosphere at a luxury adults-only all-inclusive.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want a calmer, more sleep-friendly Caribbean beach experience near Cancun, with a genuinely swimmable shoreline and a pared-back, relaxation-focused stay at a luxury adults-only price point.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos is best October through June, avoiding peak summer humidity and occasional late-summer hurricanes. Riviera Cancun's Caribbean side shares a similar hurricane window, with December through April offering the driest, most reliable weather. Both resorts sit in the same premium-season window of mid-winter through spring, when demand and prices peak.","activities":"Los Cabos guests can play on-site golf and go sport fishing in one of the world's top billfish destinations, plus explore San Jose del Cabo's art district and the famous El Arco rock formation. Riviera Cancun guests are close to Cancun's hotel zone, Isla Mujeres ferry, and the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef for snorkelling and diving, with cenote tours accessible inland."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall is a family-friendly Jamaican all-inclusive in Montego Bay with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, lazy river, and rooms for five or more guests, rated 8.5 overall with a beach score of 6.0 and food at 7.4. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only Mexican resort in San Jose del Cabo rated 8.9 overall, with standout scores in cleanliness (9.4), rooms (9.1), and service (9.1), but a notably low beach score of 3.5 reflecting the rugged Pacific coastline. Food climbs to 8.1 at Secrets versus 7.4 at Dreams, and rooms rate 9.1 against 8.2. The price gap is significant: Dreams sits at mid-market while Secrets commands a premium. Dreams is the clear choice for families who need kids programming and a functioning beach; Secrets suits couples prioritizing refined rooms, polished service, and golf over swimming in the ocean.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a Montego Bay all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, lazy river, and large rooms sleeping five or more, at a mid-market price point with reliable service scores and a usable beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples who prioritize exceptionally clean, high-quality rooms and top-tier service over beach quality, and who want yoga, archery, fishing, golf, and a polished adults-only atmosphere in Baja California Sur at a premium price.","whenToVisit":"Jamaica's peak season runs December through April when rainfall is lowest and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable; hurricane season runs June through November with August and September carrying the highest risk. Los Cabos enjoys dry, sunny weather most of the year, with peak season also December through April; late summer brings occasional tropical moisture but far less hurricane exposure than the Caribbean.","activities":"Dreams Rose Hall offers tennis, a lazy river, swim-up bar, evening entertainment, and a nightclub on the Montego Bay strip, with golf nearby. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos adds archery, yoga, fishing charters, and mini golf alongside its on-site golf course, with the art galleries and restaurants of San Jose del Cabo's historic town center a short drive away."},"dreams-aventuras-riviera-maya-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Aventuras Riviera Maya and Secrets Puerto Los Cabos share identical overall scores (8.9) and value scores (8.7), but diverge sharply on several fronts. Dreams Aventuras is a family resort on the Caribbean coast near Puerto Aventuras with a waterpark, kids clubs, babysitting, diving, and snorkelling, while Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only resort on Baja California's Pacific coast with a golf course, archery, fishing, and a nightclub. The beach gap is significant: Dreams Aventuras scores 5.3 versus Secrets' already-modest 3.5, meaning neither excels on sand but Secrets trails considerably. Secrets compensates with a much stronger room score (9.1 vs 8.6), better food ratings (8.1 vs 7.0), higher cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.9), and a superior pool score (7.8 vs 6.6). Atmosphere also favors Secrets at 8.0 versus Dreams' 6.9. If you want a family-oriented Caribbean all-inclusive with water slides and kids programming, Dreams Aventuras wins. If you want a polished adults-only Pacific-coast resort with better food, rooms, and upscale amenities like golf and fishing, Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is the stronger pick.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a Caribbean Riviera Maya all-inclusive with a waterpark, dedicated kids clubs including programming for under-4s, babysitting, diving, snorkelling, and large group rooms accommodating five or more, without worrying about restaurant reservations.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who prioritize refined rooms, better food, and a cleaner, more atmospheric resort experience on the Baja Peninsula, with access to golf, fishing, archery, and a nightclub in a well-located San Jose del Cabo setting.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Aventuras benefits from the Riviera Maya's dry season, November through April, when Caribbean humidity and hurricane risk drop significantly. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos enjoys Baja California's year-round arid climate, though summer brings occasional tropical moisture. Both resorts sit at the same price tier, so shoulder seasons in late April or early November offer the best value at either property.","activities":"Dreams Aventuras guests can dive and snorkel directly from the resort, visit the Puerto Aventuras marina, or day-trip to Tulum ruins and cenotes nearby. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos guests can play golf on-site, arrange sport fishing excursions, try archery, or explore San Jose del Cabo's art district and the corridor to Cabo San Lucas, a short drive away."},"secrets-baby-beach-aruba-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Baby Beach Aruba and Secrets Puerto Los Cabos are both adults-only Secrets properties, but they diverge sharply on beach quality and amenity breadth. Baby Beach Aruba earns an 8.5 beach rating, benefiting from Aruba's calm, sheltered southern coast with consistent sun and minimal hurricane risk. Los Cabos scores a stark 3.5 on beach, reflecting the Pacific-facing shore's rough surf and swimming restrictions that are typical for this stretch of Baja. Where Los Cabos compensates is activity volume: it offers a golf course, archery, fishing, mini golf, a nightclub, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment versus Aruba's leaner lineup of gym, spa, and buffet. Room quality slightly favors Aruba at 9.4 versus 9.1, and Aruba's sleep quality rating of 9.3 beats Los Cabos's 8.1 noticeably. Overall, Los Cabos edges Aruba on overall score (8.9 vs 8.6) and location (8.6 vs 8.4), but Aruba wins decisively on beach, sleep quality, and rooms. Los Cabos is a resort you visit for land activities and desert scenery; Baby Beach Aruba is one you visit to actually swim and beach-lounge.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults-only couples or solo travelers who want a genuine beach holiday with calm, swimmable water, exceptional room quality, and a quiet, restorative atmosphere. Aruba's near-constant trade winds, low storm risk, and that 9.5 cleanliness rating make it ideal for those prioritizing relaxation over a packed activity schedule.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults-only couples who want a high-amenity Baja experience anchored by golf, fishing, archery, a nightclub, and evening entertainment rather than beach swimming. If the Sea of Cortez desert landscape, world-class golf access, and a diverse on-resort activity program matter more than sand and surf, Los Cabos delivers.","whenToVisit":"Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and enjoys reliable sunshine year-round, making any month viable, though December through April sees peak pricing. Los Cabos is best visited October through June, avoiding the summer hurricane season that runs July through September. Both resorts command higher rates over the Christmas and New Year holiday period.","activities":"At Baby Beach Aruba, guests can explore Arikok National Park, rent ATVs along the rugged eastern coast, visit the California Lighthouse, or snorkel the calm southern bay just outside the resort. At Los Cabos, the surrounding area offers world-class deep-sea fishing, whale watching from January to March, ATV desert tours, visits to the famous El Arco rock arch, and proximity to San Jose del Cabo's art gallery district."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only Mexican resort in San Jose del Cabo with a broader amenity set including a golf course, archery, yoga, nightclub, mini golf, and evening entertainment, scoring higher on food (8.1 vs 8.6 edge to Zoëtry), pool (7.8 vs 7.4), and rooms (9.1 vs 8.8), while posting a stronger overall score (8.9 vs 8.6). Zoëtry Marigot Bay is a family-friendly St. Lucia boutique resort tucked into a dramatic rainforest bay, with a notably better atmosphere rating (8.6 vs 8.0), superior sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.1), and a more refined, intimate feel, though it allows children at up to three per room. Both resorts score poorly on beach (3.5 and 2.5 respectively), reflecting rocky or limited shorelines. Secrets offers more programming and activity variety; Zoëtry trades that breadth for a quieter, more enveloping natural setting. Both sit at the same price tier, making the choice fundamentally about lively Mexican resort amenities versus serene St. Lucian rainforest intimacy.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples or groups who want a well-appointed Mexican all-inclusive with golf, archery, a nightclub, and evening entertainment in the polished San Jose del Cabo corridor, and who prioritize strong room quality and a full activity roster over a tranquil atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples seeking a quiet, character-rich boutique all-inclusive in St. Lucia's scenic Marigot Bay, where lush rainforest surroundings, exceptional sleep quality, and an intimate atmosphere matter more than a packed activity schedule or a wide beach.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos is driest and most reliably sunny from November through May, with hurricane-adjacent humidity possible in late summer. St. Lucia's dry season runs January through April, offering the clearest skies and calmest seas; the wetter months of June through November bring lush green scenery but occasional heavy showers. Both destinations are pleasant outside peak summer months.","activities":"At Secrets Los Cabos, guests can golf on-site, try archery, join yoga classes, fish offshore, and explore the boutique art galleries and restaurants of San Jose del Cabo nearby. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, the picturesque bay itself is the draw, with fishing, spa treatments, and easy access to St. Lucia's hiking trails, the Piton peaks, sulphur springs, and the lively waterfront bars of Marigot Bay village just steps away."},"breathless-montego-bay-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Montego Bay is an adults-only Jamaican all-inclusive in Montego Bay with a beach, nightclub, tennis, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment, leaning into a lively party-oriented atmosphere. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo with golf, archery, yoga, fishing, mini golf, a spa, and a notably broader activity roster in a more polished setting. Secrets outscores Breathless on nearly every measurable: overall (8.9 vs 8.5), food (8.1 vs 7.5), pool (7.8 vs 7.2), rooms (9.1 vs 8.7), value (8.7 vs 8.3), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.9), and service (9.1 vs 8.7). Breathless has a meaningful beach advantage (5.5 vs 3.5), though neither resort excels on this metric. Secrets delivers a quieter, more refined Baja California experience with stronger across-the-board scores, while Breathless offers Caribbean energy with a nightclub focus at a slightly lower quality ceiling. If you want a lively Jamaican adults-only beach resort with nightlife and Caribbean atmosphere, choose Breathless. If you want a polished, activity-rich Mexican adults-only resort with superior rooms, food, and service, choose Secrets.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults seeking a high-energy Caribbean adults-only experience in Jamaica, with a nightclub, swim-up bar, evening entertainment, and a real beach presence, who prioritize atmosphere and location in Montego Bay over top-tier food and room quality.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want a refined, well-appointed Baja California all-inclusive with exceptional rooms, strong service, and diverse land-based activities including golf, fishing, archery, and yoga, and who are not reliant on a quality beach.","whenToVisit":"Breathless Montego Bay is best visited November through mid-December or late January through April to avoid Jamaica's hurricane season peak and summer heat. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos suits travel from October through May, when Baja California is dry and mild. Both resorts sit at the same price tier, so shoulder months offer better availability and rates at each.","activities":"At Breathless Montego Bay, guests can use the beach, tennis courts, swim-up bar, spa, gym, and nightly entertainment and nightclub. Nearby Montego Bay offers hip strip dining, Dunn's River Falls day trips, and airport-adjacent convenience. At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, guests can golf, fish, practice archery, take yoga classes, and visit the spa. San Jose del Cabo's art district, whale watching in season, and Cabo San Lucas excursions are all within easy reach."},"dreams-playa-esmeralda-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Playa Esmeralda and Secrets Puerto Los Cabos both sit at the same overall rating of 8.9 and price level, but diverge sharply in guest profile and setting. Dreams is a family all-inclusive on the Dominican Republic's northeastern coast with a kids club for under-4s, teen club, and babysitting, built around a beach that rates 8.3. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only resort in San Jose del Cabo with a golf course, archery, fishing, swim-up bar, and nightclub, but its beach rates a striking 3.5, reflecting the notoriously rough Pacific surf of Los Cabos. Dreams edges ahead on room quality (9.2 vs 9.1) and sleep quality (9.1 vs 8.1), while Secrets leads on food (8.1 vs 7.6), pool (7.8 vs 7.1), and atmosphere (8.0 vs 7.5). Dreams suits families wanting a genuine Caribbean beach holiday; Secrets suits adults drawn to Baja golf, activities, and nightlife who can accept a non-swimmable beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a genuine Caribbean beach holiday in the Dominican Republic, with dedicated kids and teen programming, babysitting, strong room comfort ratings, and a swimmable beach as the focal point of the trip.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a polished, activity-rich Baja California escape with golf, fishing, archery, a nightclub, and strong food and atmosphere ratings, and who understand that Los Cabos's Pacific coastline means pool time replaces beach swimming.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Playa Esmeralda is best visited December through April when Dominican Republic hurricane risk is lowest and the northeast coast is driest. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos suits travel from October through May, when Baja temperatures are comfortable and the desert landscape is at its most striking; summer months bring heat and occasional tropical storms to both destinations.","activities":"At Dreams, guests stay focused on the Caribbean beach, kids club programming, and the spa. At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, the activity roster is broader and more land-oriented: an on-site golf course, archery range, mini golf, sport fishing excursions, and evening entertainment fill the days, while the spa and swim-up bar anchor resort downtime. San Jose del Cabo's art district and the Corridor to Cabo San Lucas add strong off-property options."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-wild-orchid-montego-bay":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos and Secrets Wild Orchid Montego Bay are both adults-only, upper-upscale all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they diverge sharply on beach access and atmosphere. Puerto Los Cabos scores a very low 3.5 for beach — the Pacific-facing San Jose del Cabo coastline is notoriously rough for swimming — while Wild Orchid scores 6.8, offering a genuine sandy beach on the calmer Caribbean. Pool ratings also favor Los Cabos (7.8 vs 7.2), though Wild Orchid counters with a lazy river. Atmosphere leans toward Los Cabos (8.0 vs 7.7), while Wild Orchid edges it on sleep quality (8.8 vs 8.1) and location (8.9 vs 8.6). Los Cabos adds a golf course, archery, fishing, and mini golf, making it far more activity-driven on land. Wild Orchid offers diving, tennis, a casino, and a lazy river. On the core metrics that matter most — overall (8.9 vs 8.6), rooms (9.1 vs 8.9), and cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.0) — Los Cabos holds a consistent, if modest, edge.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a polished, activity-rich Mexican resort with a golf course, fishing, archery, and spa, and who are content without strong beach swimming. Best for couples or golfers drawn to the dramatic Baja landscape and a slightly higher overall rating.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want a genuine Caribbean beach all-inclusive in Jamaica with diving, a casino, lazy river, and tennis. Ideal for couples who prioritize Caribbean sea access, strong sleep quality, and the lively Montego Bay setting over a Mexican land-activity lineup.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos is best from October through May, when humidity is low and the Pacific weather is stable; summer brings heat and hurricane-season risk. Montego Bay suits winter visits from December through April for dry, breezy Caribbean conditions. Both resorts see premium pricing around the Christmas–New Year holiday window regardless of weather.","activities":"At Los Cabos, guests can play the on-site golf course, try archery, fish the Pacific, or explore the artisan markets of San Jose del Cabo. At Wild Orchid, the focus shifts to water: certified diving, snorkelling, and watersports off the Caribbean beach, plus a casino on-site and the shopping and dining of Montego Bay's Hip Strip close by."},"breathless-cancun-soul-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Cancun Soul Resort & Spa is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Caribbean side of Mexico near Puerto Morelos, with a beach rating of 7.8, a nightclub, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment in a lively atmosphere. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos Golf & Spa Resort is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Pacific side in San Jose del Cabo, with a dramatically lower beach rating of 3.5 reflecting the rough, non-swimmable surf typical of Los Cabos, but it compensates with a golf course, archery, fishing, yoga, and a notably higher service score of 9.1 versus Breathless's 8.8. Secrets edges out Breathless on overall rating (8.9 vs 8.4), food (8.1 vs 7.6), value (8.7 vs 8.3), and service, while Breathless wins decisively on beach. If a swimmable Caribbean beach is central to your holiday, Breathless Cancun is the clear choice. If you want a polished Pacific Mexico adults-only resort with golf, fishing, and superior dining and service and can live without a beach, Secrets Los Cabos delivers.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a lively Caribbean all-inclusive where beach time is central, with a nightclub, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment in the calmer waters near Puerto Morelos. Best for couples and groups who prioritize beach access and a social atmosphere over activity variety.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want a refined, activity-rich Pacific Mexico all-inclusive with golf, fishing, archery, and yoga, and who are not dependent on a swimmable beach. Ideal for couples or golf-focused travelers who value exceptional service and dining over beach quality.","whenToVisit":"Breathless Cancun is best visited November through April to avoid Caribbean hurricane season and peak humidity. Secrets Los Cabos benefits from the same winter window, as Los Cabos summers bring heat and the occasional Pacific storm. Both resorts sit in the same broad high season, making December through March the safest bet for reliably good weather at either property.","activities":"Breathless Cancun guests can snorkel the nearby Puerto Morelos reef, explore the town's low-key village strip, or day-trip to Tulum and Playa del Carmen. Secrets Los Cabos guests can play the on-site golf course, arrange sport fishing charters, visit the famous El Arco rock formation in Cabo San Lucas, or explore the art galleries and restaurants of San Jose del Cabo's historic town center."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-st-james-montego-bay":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos and Secrets St. James Montego Bay are both adults-only Mexican and Jamaican all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they diverge sharply on beach and pool experience. Puerto Los Cabos scores a striking 3.5 for beach versus St. James's 6.8, reflecting the Pacific-side surf conditions at San Jose del Cabo that make swimming difficult — pool time dominates here, though the pool itself rates only 7.8 against St. James's 7.2. Puerto Los Cabos compensates with a golf course, archery, mini golf, and fishing that St. James lacks entirely, while St. James counters with a casino, tennis, and diving unavailable in Los Cabos. Room quality is closer than it looks — Puerto Los Cabos edges ahead at 9.1 versus 8.8 — but St. James leads on location (8.9 vs 8.6), sleep quality (8.8 vs 8.1), and beach access. Puerto Los Cabos scores higher overall at 8.9 versus 8.5, driven by cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.0) and service (9.1 vs 8.9). Choose Los Cabos for land-based amenities and superior rooms; choose St. James for actual beach access and watersports.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a premium Los Cabos all-inclusive with a golf course, fishing, archery, and spa, and who are comfortable trading true beach swimming for dramatic Pacific scenery and a strong overall resort experience with top-rated rooms and service.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who prioritize genuine beach access, diving, tennis, and a casino in a well-located Montego Bay setting, and who value reliable sleep quality and service in a classic Jamaican adults-only resort without needing golf or land-based activity variety.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos peaks October through May when Pacific storms subside and temperatures are comfortable; summer brings heat and occasional hurricane-season humidity. Montego Bay sits in the Caribbean hurricane belt, with peak season running mid-December through April. Both resorts command premium pricing during North American winter holidays, so shoulder months like November or early May offer better value at either property.","activities":"At Puerto Los Cabos, guests can golf the attached course, fish the Sea of Cortez, take archery lessons, and explore San Jose del Cabo's art district nearby. At St. James Montego Bay, guests can dive Caribbean reefs, play tennis, try the casino, and access Montego Bay's Hip Strip and Rose Hall historic great house. Both offer spa, swim-up bar, nightclub, and evening entertainment on property."},"dreams-sands-cancun-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Sands Cancun is a family-oriented all-inclusive on the Cancun hotel zone with a lazy river, kids club for under-4s, and a genuine Caribbean beach, though that beach scores a modest 6.5 and the pool rates just 6.0. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only resort in San Jose del Cabo with dramatically stronger scores across rooms (9.1 vs 7.8), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.5), food (8.1 vs 6.9), and overall (8.9 vs 8.5), but its beach is effectively unusable at 3.5, making the swim-up bar and golf course the primary draws. Dreams Sands wins on family infrastructure and a functional beach setting in Cancun, while Secrets Los Cabos delivers a noticeably higher-quality product in rooms, dining, and service for couples willing to forgo ocean swimming. If you want a family Cancun all-inclusive with kids programming and a swimmable beach, choose Dreams Sands. If you want a polished adults-only experience in Baja with superior rooms, food, and amenities despite a non-swimmable coastline, choose Secrets Puerto Los Cabos.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children, including toddlers, who prioritize a swimmable Cancun beach, a lazy river, and no-reservation dining in a lively hotel zone setting. Parents who want structured kids programming and easy access to Cancun's wider restaurant and nightlife scene will find Dreams Sands a practical, well-located base.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a refined, high-cleanliness all-inclusive in Baja California with excellent food, spacious rooms scoring 9.1, golf, spa, archery, and evening entertainment. Guests who won't miss ocean swimming and prefer a quieter, more polished atmosphere over a family resort environment will find Secrets Los Cabos worth the premium.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Sands Cancun is best visited November through April, when Caribbean humidity drops and hurricane risk is minimal. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos benefits from Los Cabos' year-round desert climate, with peak comfort also falling between November and May. Both resorts see higher rates during US holiday weeks and spring break; Cabos in particular draws crowds during major American holidays given its direct flight connections.","activities":"Dreams Sands guests have Cancun's hotel zone on their doorstep, with Mayan ruins at Tulum and Chichen Itza accessible as day trips, plus watersports along the Caribbean coast. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos offers on-site golf, fishing charters, archery, yoga, and a spa, with the historic town of San Jose del Cabo, the Los Cabos art district, whale watching seasonally, and the famous El Arco rock formation a short transfer away."},"secrets-mirabel-cancun-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Both are adults-only Mexican all-inclusives at the same price tier with near-identical room (9.1), service (9.1), and cleanliness scores, but they diverge sharply on beach and activity profile. Secrets Mirabel Cancún sits on the Caribbean coast with a genuine beach rated 7.3, while Secrets Puerto Los Cabos scores a striking 3.5 for beach — the Pacific surf and rocky shoreline near San José del Cabo make swimming impractical, and guests rely heavily on the pool (7.8 vs 7.5). Cancún edges ahead on location (9.0 vs 8.6) and sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.1), suggesting a quieter, more restful setting. Los Cabos counters with a richer activity roster: golf course, fishing, archery, yoga, mini golf, and a nightclub, versus Cancún's leaner lineup of spa, snorkelling, gym, and evening entertainment. If a swimmable beach is your anchor, Cancún is the clear choice. If you want desert-meets-ocean scenery, golf, fishing, and more on-property programming, Los Cabos delivers despite its unusable shoreline.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults-only couples and solo travellers who want a genuine Caribbean beach experience in Cancún, prioritising a swimmable shore, excellent sleep quality (9.2), a relaxed atmosphere, and strong location scores with easy access to Cancún's Hotel Zone and nearby attractions.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults-only couples who prioritise activities over beach access — golfers, anglers, yoga enthusiasts, and nightlife seekers who are drawn to the dramatic Baja landscape around San José del Cabo and won't miss a swimmable shoreline as long as the pool, spa, and programming are strong.","whenToVisit":"Cancún peaks December through April when Caribbean weather is dry and calm; hurricane season runs June through October with some risk. Los Cabos enjoys its best weather October through June — summer brings humidity and occasional tropical storms to Baja. Both resorts command premium pricing during Christmas and spring break regardless of season.","activities":"Secrets Mirabel Cancún guests can snorkel the Caribbean reefs, explore the Hotel Zone, visit Isla Mujeres, or day-trip to Chichén Itzá. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos guests can golf on-site, charter fishing boats for marlin and dorado, practise archery and yoga, take the short drive to San José del Cabo's art district, or arrange whale-watching excursions between January and March."},"dreams-sapphire-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Sapphire Resort & Spa is a large family all-inclusive on Mexico's Caribbean coast in Puerto Morelos, with a kids club, teen club, infant programming, diving, snorkelling, babysitting, adult pool, tennis, and a beach setup, rated 8.7 overall with strong service (9.0) and cleanliness (8.8) but a notably weak beach score (5.0) and modest food rating (7.2). Secrets Puerto Los Cabos Golf & Spa Resort is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Pacific side in San Jose del Cabo, with golf, archery, mini golf, and a nightclub, rated 8.9 overall with superior food (8.1 vs 7.2), rooms (9.1 vs 8.5), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.8), and pool (7.8 vs 6.7), though its beach score is even lower at 3.5, typical of Los Cabos. Dreams Sapphire suits families wanting Caribbean water activities and structured kids programming; Secrets Puerto Los Cabos suits adults prioritizing refined rooms, better dining, and golf over beach quality.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a Caribbean all-inclusive with structured kids and teen programming, water activities including diving and snorkelling, babysitting, and a dedicated adult pool, all on Mexico's Riviera Maya coast near Puerto Morelos.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who prioritize exceptional room quality (9.1), superior food (8.1), golf, and a polished atmosphere over beach access, and who prefer the desert-meets-Pacific setting of San Jose del Cabo to a traditional Caribbean beach resort.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Sapphire benefits from the Riviera Maya's dry season, November through April, when humidity drops and hurricane risk fades. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos sits on the Pacific side of Baja, where September brings the highest hurricane risk; November through May offers the most stable, sunny conditions. Both resorts are at their best mid-November through March.","activities":"Dreams Sapphire guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef nearby, explore the Crococun Zoo, or visit Cancun and Playa del Carmen. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos guests can play golf on-site, charter fishing boats for world-class sportfishing, visit the Arch at Land's End, explore San Jose del Cabo's art district, or take an ATV excursion into the Baja desert."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-sunscape-dorado-pacifico-ixtapa":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo with a full amenity stack: golf course, spa, archery, yoga, nightclub, swim-up bar, fishing, mini golf, gym, and multiple restaurants requiring no reservations. Sunscape Dorado Pacifico Ixtapa is a family all-inclusive on the Pacific coast of Ixtapa with beach access as its primary listed amenity and a more stripped-back offering at a lower price tier. The ratings tell a clear story: Secrets leads on room quality (9.1 vs 8.2), food (8.1 vs 6.4), pool (7.8 vs 6.2), atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.3), and cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.6). Sunscape edges ahead only on beach (6.8 vs 3.5) and location (8.8 vs 8.6), though Secrets' beach score of 3.5 reflects the rocky marina setting at Puerto Los Cabos rather than a swimming beach. If you want an upscale adults-only resort with serious amenities and polished service in Los Cabos, choose Secrets. If you want an affordable family beach resort in Ixtapa, choose Sunscape.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples and solo travelers who want a high-end Los Cabos all-inclusive with a golf course, spa, excellent rooms, and a full entertainment program, and who are not prioritizing a classic swim-in beach experience.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families on a mid-range budget who want a straightforward Pacific Mexico beach all-inclusive in Ixtapa with decent rooms, solid service, and direct beach access without paying luxury prices.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos is best November through May when the desert climate is dry and pleasant; summer brings heat and hurricane risk. Ixtapa sits on Mexico's Pacific coast with a dry season running November through April. Both destinations peak over Christmas and Easter, so booking well in advance is essential for either resort during those windows.","activities":"At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, guests can play the onsite golf course, book fishing charters, take archery and yoga classes, use the spa, and explore San Jose del Cabo's art district and galleries nearby. At Sunscape Dorado Pacifico Ixtapa, guests can use the beach, and the broader Ixtapa-Zihuatanejo area offers sport fishing, snorkeling at Ixtapa Island, and exploring the charming fishing village of Zihuatanejo a short drive away."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-tulum-resort-and-beach-club":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos and Secrets Tulum are both adults-only Mexican all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they differ meaningfully across key ratings and amenity sets. Puerto Los Cabos scores higher on overall satisfaction (8.9 vs 8.3), location (8.6 vs 7.8), and value (8.7 vs 7.9), while Tulum edges ahead on atmosphere (8.5 vs 8.0), sleep quality (9.1 vs 8.1), beach (5.5 vs a notably weak 3.5), and service (8.8 vs 9.1). Puerto Los Cabos is the more amenity-rich property, offering a golf course, archery, fishing, nightclub, spa, gym, mini golf, yoga, and a swim-up bar — a full activity roster for guests who want structured programming. Tulum's listed amenities are sparse by comparison, with its appeal resting more on atmosphere and the surrounding Riviera Maya jungle-and-beach setting. Neither resort is a standout beach destination, but Tulum's 5.5 beach rating is considerably less damaging than Puerto Los Cabos's 3.5. If you want a well-equipped adults-only resort in Los Cabos with strong overall scores and a full amenity lineup, choose Puerto Los Cabos. If a bohemian Tulum atmosphere and better sleep quality matter more than structured activities, choose Tulum.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a well-rounded Los Cabos resort with a wide activity menu — golf, fishing, archery, a spa, nightclub, and swim-up bar — and who prioritize strong overall value (8.7), exceptional rooms (9.1), and cleanliness (9.4) over beach quality.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults drawn to the Tulum aesthetic — jungle surroundings, a more intimate atmosphere (8.5), and quieter nights (sleep quality 9.1) — who are less focused on structured resort amenities and more interested in the Riviera Maya's cultural and natural surroundings nearby.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season, roughly November through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity manageable. Los Cabos can see occasional hurricane-season disruption from August through October, though it sits at the edge of the Pacific storm track. Tulum, on the Yucatán Peninsula, is more directly in the Caribbean hurricane corridor, making November through May the safer and more comfortable window for visits.","activities":"Puerto Los Cabos guests can fish the Sea of Cortez, play golf on-site, take archery and yoga classes, and explore San Jose del Cabo's art district and galleries nearby. Tulum guests are positioned near the UNESCO-listed Tulum ruins, the Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve, cenotes throughout the Yucatán Peninsula, and the emerging Tulum town dining and nightlife scene — a richer off-resort excursion menu than Los Cabos offers."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-sunscape-dominicus-la-romana":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive on Mexico's Baja Peninsula in San Jose del Cabo, with a golf course, spa, archery, yoga, nightclub, fishing, swim-up bar, and multiple restaurants requiring no reservations. Sunscape Dominicus La Romana is a family all-inclusive on the Dominican Republic's south coast near La Romana, with a beach, kids club, teen club, and waterparks for both age groups. The ratings tell a clear story: Secrets scores significantly higher on food (8.1 vs 6.2), pool (7.8 vs 6.2), atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.2), and rooms (9.1 vs 8.0), while Sunscape edges ahead on beach (8.0 vs 3.5) — a meaningful gap given Cabo's rockier Pacific coastline. Both sit at the same price tier, but Secrets delivers markedly higher overall satisfaction at 8.9 versus Sunscape's 8.1. Secrets is the clear choice for couples and adults wanting a polished, amenity-rich Mexican resort experience; Sunscape suits families prioritizing a genuine Caribbean beach and age-specific kids programming over dining and atmosphere quality.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples and solo travelers who want a high-rated, amenity-packed Mexican resort with golf, spa, archery, fishing, and strong room and service scores, and can accept a limited beach in exchange for a refined, upscale Cabo atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of varying ages who prioritize a proper Caribbean beach and dedicated kids and teen programming over food quality and atmosphere, and want a straightforward Dominican Republic beach holiday at a mid-to-upper price point.","whenToVisit":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos benefits from Cabo's dry, sunny climate from November through May, avoiding late-summer hurricane risk. Sunscape Dominicus sits in the Dominican Republic's south, which is drier than the north coast but still carries some hurricane exposure from August through October. Both resorts are most reliably pleasant from December through April.","activities":"At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, guests can play golf, fish the Pacific, take archery and yoga classes, visit the spa, and explore the galleries and restaurants of San Jose del Cabo town nearby. At Sunscape Dominicus, the focus shifts to the beach and water, with the onsite waterparks, kids club, and proximity to Altos de Chavón, a replica Mediterranean village, and Casa de Campo's world-class golf and polo just minutes away."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-zoetry-montego-bay-jamaica":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos and Zoëtry Montego Bay are both adults-only luxury all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they diverge sharply on amenities, scale, and setting. Secrets edges ahead on overall rating (8.9 vs 8.2), rooms (9.1 vs 8.7), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.9), and value (8.7 vs 7.9), while Zoëtry scores slightly better on beach (4 vs 3.5), sleep quality (8.9 vs 8.1), and service (8.8 vs 9.1 is close). Secrets is the larger, more activity-rich property with a golf course, archery, nightclub, mini golf, fishing, and a swim-up bar — a genuine resort campus on the Los Cabos Pacific coast. Zoëtry is a quieter, more intimate boutique property in Jamaica with a slower, wellness-oriented pace and notably better sleep scores. Neither beach rates impressively, but Zoëtry's marginal edge there is worth noting. If you want an active, amenity-loaded Mexican adults-only resort with golf and nightlife, choose Secrets. If you want a tranquil, intimate Jamaican retreat prioritizing rest and service, choose Zoëtry.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who want a large, activity-rich Los Cabos all-inclusive with golf, fishing, archery, a nightclub, and a swim-up bar. Well-suited to those who want plenty to do on-site and don't mind a weaker beach in exchange for strong overall ratings and excellent room quality.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults and couples seeking a quieter, boutique Jamaican all-inclusive where the emphasis is on rest, service, and atmosphere rather than a packed activity roster. Ideal for those who prize sleep quality, a more intimate setting, and a relaxed Caribbean pace over nightlife and sprawling amenities.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos is driest and most reliably sunny from November through May, with summer bringing heat and occasional hurricane-season risk. Montego Bay is warm year-round but also sits in the Caribbean hurricane belt, making December through April the safest and most comfortable window. Both resorts offer better value pricing in the May–June shoulder season before peak summer demand.","activities":"At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, guests can play golf on-site, fish the Pacific, take archery or yoga classes, and explore San José del Cabo's art district and local markets nearby. At Zoëtry Montego Bay, guests can snorkel the Jamaican coast, visit the famous Hip Strip, or take excursions to Dunn's River Falls and the Blue Mountains, with watersports typically available through the resort."},"dreams-bahia-mita-surf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Bahia Mita is a family-friendly all-inclusive on Mexico's Pacific Riviera Nayarit coast near Punta de Mita, with a kids club, babysitting, evening entertainment, and a spa set against a surf-influenced beach backdrop. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo with a notably stronger food rating (8.1 vs 7.3), swim-up bar, golf course, archery, yoga, nightclub, and fishing. Both sit at the same price tier and score similarly on rooms (9.0 vs 9.1) and service (9.0 vs 9.1), but Secrets edges ahead on overall rating (8.9 vs 8.6) and cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.2). Neither property excels on beach, with Dreams scoring a low 4.8 and Secrets even lower at 3.5, so pool and surroundings matter more than shoreline at both. Dreams wins on atmosphere for families and surf-coast setting; Secrets wins on dining variety, adults-only sophistication, and activity breadth including golf and fishing. Choose Dreams for a family Pacific Mexico escape; choose Secrets for a polished, amenity-rich adults-only Los Cabos experience.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want a Pacific Mexico all-inclusive near Punta de Mita with a kids club, babysitting, and a surf-coastal atmosphere. The strong room (9.0), service (9.0), and value (8.5) ratings make it a reliable choice for parents who want comfort without sacrificing family programming.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a polished, amenity-heavy Los Cabos all-inclusive with superior dining (8.1), a golf course, swim-up bar, nightclub, yoga, archery, and fishing. The higher overall rating (8.9) and adults-only atmosphere make it ideal for those prioritising quality food and varied activities over family facilities.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Bahia Mita benefits from Riviera Nayarit's dry season between November and April, when surf conditions and outdoor dining are at their best. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos sits in Baja California Sur, where the desert climate keeps things sunny and dry from October through June. Both resorts see peak pricing over the winter holiday period; shoulder months of October–November and April–May offer better value at each property.","activities":"Dreams Bahia Mita guests can surf the nearby breaks of Punta de Mita, take day trips to Sayulita village, or explore the Marieta Islands by boat. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos guests can play the on-site golf course, book fishing charters directly from the resort, try archery and yoga, or day-trip to the historic art galleries and restaurants of San Jose del Cabo's town centre, just minutes away."},"dreams-los-cabos-suites-golf-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Both resorts sit in San Jose del Cabo at the same price tier, but they serve fundamentally different guests. Dreams Los Cabos is a family all-inclusive with a kids club for under-4s, while Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is strictly adults-only. Secrets outperforms Dreams across nearly every measured category: overall (8.9 vs 8.6), food (8.1 vs 7.5, a meaningful 0.6-point gap), pool (7.8 vs 6.9), atmosphere (8.0 vs 7.2), room (9.1 vs 8.7), value (8.7 vs 8.3), and cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.9). Dreams edges ahead only in sleep quality (8.6 vs 8.1), which may reflect the quieter, family-paced environment. Both resorts share the Cabo reality of a poor beach score (3.5 vs 3.3), typical for this rocky Pacific coastline. Secrets carries a significantly richer amenity set — archery, swim-up bar, golf course, fishing, nightclub, mini golf, and a full spa — while Dreams' listed amenities are comparatively sparse. For the same price, adults consistently rate Secrets the stronger experience.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with very young children who want a well-maintained, high-cleanliness all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo. Dreams' kids club for under-4s and relaxed dining policy suit parents who need flexibility and a forgiving, family-oriented atmosphere without sacrificing room quality.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults and couples who want the stronger-rated, amenity-rich all-inclusive experience in San Jose del Cabo. Secrets delivers notably better food, pool, atmosphere, and room scores, plus a swim-up bar, golf course, fishing, nightclub, and spa — all without children on property.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Los Cabos' best weather between November and May, when rainfall is minimal and temperatures are warm without extreme humidity. Peak winter months (December through February) bring the most reliable conditions but highest prices. Summer visits (June through September) carry some hurricane-season risk and intense heat, though rates drop considerably.","activities":"Both resorts are near the San Jose del Cabo art district and the famous Land's End arch at Cabo San Lucas, reachable by taxi or tour. Secrets adds on-site archery, mini golf, fishing charters, and a golf course. Shared draws include spa treatments, snorkeling excursions, whale watching (December through April), and ATV tours into the desert landscape surrounding the Baja peninsula."},"dreams-natura-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Natura is a family all-inclusive on the Caribbean side of Mexico in Puerto Morelos, sitting on a natural beach backed by jungle with a kids club for under-4s, a cleanliness score of 9.0, and a standout room rating of 8.8. Its beach score of 4.5 reflects a reef-protected shoreline that limits swimming, and its food rating of 7.3 is a notable weak spot. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Pacific side in San Jose del Cabo with a richer amenity set — golf, archery, fishing, nightclub, swim-up bar, spa, and mini golf — and it outscores Dreams Natura on food (8.1 vs 7.3), rooms (9.1 vs 8.8), service (9.1 vs 8.7), cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.0), and overall (8.9 vs 8.5). Its beach score of 3.5 is even lower than Dreams Natura's, reflecting Los Cabos' characteristically rough Pacific surf. If you want a family-oriented Mexican Caribbean retreat near a coral reef at a strong value, go to Dreams Natura. If you want a polished adults-only Baja all-inclusive with superior food, service, and activity variety, go to Secrets Puerto Los Cabos.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children, including infants, who want a Caribbean Mexico all-inclusive near Puerto Morelos with jungle surroundings, a reef-protected beach, excellent cleanliness, and relaxed restaurant access without reservations — and who can overlook a food rating that lags the competition.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and groups who want a high-performing Baja all-inclusive with top-tier service (9.1), excellent rooms (9.1), golf, fishing, archery, and a nightclub in San Jose del Cabo — and who won't rely on the Pacific beach for swimming.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Natura in Puerto Morelos is best November through April, avoiding the Caribbean hurricane season that peaks August through October. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos in San Jose del Cabo benefits from Baja's drier, more stable climate and is pleasant year-round, though summer months bring heat and occasional tropical moisture. Both resorts sit at the same $$$$ price tier, so timing around demand rather than budget is the main lever.","activities":"Dreams Natura guests are steps from the Puerto Morelos coral reef, one of the best snorkelling sites on the Mexican Caribbean, with the charming Puerto Morelos village a short distance away. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos offers golf, fishing, archery, mini golf, and spa on-site, and guests are well-positioned for whale watching (winter), ATV tours, and the restaurants and galleries of San Jose del Cabo's art district nearby."},"dreams-tulum-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Tulum is a family all-inclusive on Mexico's Caribbean coast in Tulum, with a beach, kids club for under-4s, and no-reservation dining, rated overall 8.2 with solid scores for cleanliness (8.6), service (8.5), and sleep quality (8.3), but notably weaker on food (7.0), pool (6.7), and beach (6.3). Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo on the Pacific side, rated overall 8.9, with standout scores for rooms (9.1), cleanliness (9.4), service (9.1), and food (8.1), but a near-unusable beach score of 3.5 — typical of Los Cabos's rough Pacific surf. Secrets offers a substantially richer amenity set including golf, spa, swim-up bar, archery, yoga, nightclub, and room service, while Dreams focuses on family accessibility. The food gap is meaningful — a full 1.1 points separates them. If beach access and traveling with young children are priorities, Dreams Tulum edges ahead despite its lower food and pool scores. Secrets wins on almost every quality metric, but guests must accept that ocean swimming is effectively off the table.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children, including toddlers under 4, who want a Caribbean beach all-inclusive in Tulum with a relaxed no-reservation dining setup and strong service and cleanliness scores, and for whom beach swimming in calm Caribbean waters is a meaningful part of the holiday.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who prioritize room quality, food, and service over beach swimming, and want a premium adults-only experience in Los Cabos with golf, spa, archery, yoga, and a nightclub — accepting that the Pacific surf here makes ocean swimming impractical.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Tulum is best visited November through April to avoid Caribbean hurricane season and peak humidity; the Tulum area can be very hot and wet from June through October. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos benefits from Los Cabos's desert climate and is largely rain-free year-round, though August and September carry some hurricane risk. Both resorts are at their most pleasant and least crowded in the shoulder months of November and early December.","activities":"At Dreams Tulum, guests are well-placed to visit the iconic Tulum ruins, cenotes, and the Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve. At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, the resort itself offers golf, fishing, archery, and yoga, and guests can easily reach the famous El Arco rock formation at Land's End, whale-watching excursions from November to March, and the galleries and restaurants of San Jose del Cabo's historic art district."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-secrets-st-lucia-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos and Secrets St. Lucia are both adults-only, upper-upscale all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they diverge sharply on setting, amenities, and key ratings. Puerto Los Cabos scores notably higher on rooms (9.1 vs 8.6), overall (8.9 vs 8.6), and atmosphere (8.0 vs 7.8), while St. Lucia edges it on sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.1), service (9.2 vs 9.1), and beach (6.8 vs a striking 3.5). That beach gap is the defining split: Puerto Los Cabos sits on a rocky Pacific cove where swimming is limited, while St. Lucia offers a proper sandy beach. On amenities, Puerto Los Cabos is far more loaded, with a golf course, archery, fishing, nightclub, mini golf, yoga, swim-up bar, spa, and gym. Secrets St. Lucia lists only no-reservation dining, suggesting a more intimate, pared-back property. Both deliver excellent cleanliness and comparable food scores. Puerto Los Cabos wins on activity variety and room quality; St. Lucia wins on beach, sleep, and Caribbean landscape drama.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a well-appointed Mexican Pacific resort with exceptional rooms, a golf course, fishing, archery, nightclub, and a full activity slate in a polished Los Cabos setting, and who are comfortable with a rocky shoreline rather than a classic swim-ready beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who prioritize a genuine sandy Caribbean beach, outstanding sleep quality, and a quieter, more intimate atmosphere amid St. Lucia's volcanic scenery, and who are less focused on a wide amenity roster than on relaxation and natural surroundings.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Los Cabos is best visited October through June, avoiding the late-summer hurricane fringe and peak heat of July and August. St. Lucia's dry season runs January through April, offering the most reliable sunshine; the wetter months of June through November bring lush landscapes but increased rain. Both resorts sit outside the primary hurricane belt's worst-affected zones but St. Lucia sees more tropical weather risk in late summer.","activities":"Puerto Los Cabos guests can play the on-site golf course, fish the Sea of Cortez, try archery, take yoga classes, and visit the town of San Jose del Cabo for galleries and markets. Whale watching runs December through April. St. Lucia guests can explore the UNESCO-listed Pitons, hike to a drive-in volcano, snorkel coral reefs, tour banana plantations, and take boat trips along the island's lush west coast, with Castries and Soufrière both reachable for cultural and culinary excursions."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-sunscape-coco-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is a premium adults-only all-inclusive on Mexico's Baja Peninsula in San Jose del Cabo, rated 8.9 overall, with standout scores for rooms (9.1), cleanliness (9.4), and service (9.1), and a broad amenity set including a golf course, spa, archery, fishing, nightclub, and swim-up bar. Sunscape Coco Punta Cana is a budget-friendlier family all-inclusive on the Dominican Republic's Punta Cana coast, rated 8.2 overall, with a more modest offering anchored by a kids club and teen club. The rating gaps are telling: Secrets leads on food by 1.9 points (8.1 vs. 6.2), pool by 1.6 (7.8 vs. 6.2), and atmosphere by 1.8 (8.0 vs. 6.2). Sunscape edges ahead only on beach (6.8 vs. 3.5), a significant practical difference. Secrets costs more but delivers meaningfully higher quality across nearly every measurable category. Sunscape trades on price and family infrastructure in a classic Caribbean beach setting. If you want a polished, activity-rich adults-only Mexican resort with exceptional service and rooms, choose Secrets. If you want an affordable family Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a proper beach and kids programming, choose Sunscape.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples or solo travelers who want a high-end, well-rounded Mexican all-inclusive with a golf course, spa, fishing, archery, and consistently strong service and room quality in a Baja Peninsula setting where nightlife and dining variety matter.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children and teenagers seeking an affordable Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a real Caribbean beach, a kids club, and teen programming in Punta Cana, where value and family infrastructure outweigh premium amenities.","whenToVisit":"San Jose del Cabo is best from November through May, avoiding summer hurricane risk and heat. Punta Cana's peak season runs December through April for dry, reliable weather. Both destinations see higher prices and crowds over the Christmas-New Year window. Shoulder months like November and late April offer better rates at both properties.","activities":"At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, guests can golf an on-site course, fish the Sea of Cortez, practice archery, take yoga classes, and explore San Jose del Cabo's art district and galleries nearby. At Sunscape Coco Punta Cana, the focus shifts to the beach and pool for families, with Punta Cana's wider resort strip offering water parks, dune buggy excursions, zip-lining, and catamaran snorkelling trips close by."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-zoetry-curacao-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos and Zoëtry Curaçao are both adults-only, top-tier all-inclusives, but Secrets pulls ahead on nearly every measurable dimension. Secrets scores 8.9 overall versus Zoëtry's 7.6, a significant 1.3-point gap, and leads on pool (7.8 vs 6.9), value (8.7 vs 7.4), and service (9.1 vs 8.2). Both resorts share weak beach scores — Secrets at 3.5, Zoëtry at 3.3 — so neither delivers a classic Caribbean beach experience. Secrets compensates with a far broader amenity list: golf course, nightclub, archery, mini golf, fishing, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment. Zoëtry, by contrast, operates as a more intimate, wellness-leaning boutique property near Willemstad with fewer programmatic amenities but comparable food scores (8.1 each) and a slightly quieter atmosphere. Secrets is the stronger all-around resort for the price; Zoëtry suits guests drawn specifically to Curaçao's Dutch-Caribbean culture and a quieter, less activity-driven stay.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a high-performing, amenity-rich Mexican all-inclusive with golf, a nightclub, fishing, archery, and evening entertainment in Los Cabos. Strong service scores (9.1) and outstanding cleanliness (9.4) make it ideal for couples and solo travelers who want a full program without sacrificing comfort.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults drawn to Curaçao's unique Dutch-Caribbean culture and proximity to Willemstad who prefer a quieter, boutique atmosphere over a packed activity schedule. Best suited to couples prioritizing sleep quality (8.8), room comfort (8.8), and a more intimate, low-key retreat over nightlife and resort-wide programming.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos is best visited October through June, avoiding hurricane season and peak summer heat; March and April offer ideal weather. Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and is a reliable year-round destination, though January through April delivers the driest, most comfortable conditions. Both resorts command premium pricing in winter high season.","activities":"Secrets Los Cabos guests can golf on-site, fish the Pacific, take archery or yoga classes, and explore San Jose del Cabo's art district and historic town center. Zoëtry Curaçao guests are well-placed for Willemstad sightseeing, UNESCO-listed colonial architecture, world-class wreck and reef diving, and snorkeling in the island's clear southern waters."},"dreams-puerto-morelos-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Puerto Morelos is a family-oriented all-inclusive on the Caribbean coast near Puerto Morelos, with a waterpark for both young and older kids, a beach, and a kids club at a mid-to-upper price point. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only all-inclusive on the Pacific side of Baja California in San Jose del Cabo, with a golf course, spa, nightclub, swim-up bar, archery, fishing, and evening entertainment. Secrets outscores Dreams on nearly every measurable dimension: overall (8.9 vs 7.8), food (8.1 vs 7.0), pool (7.8 vs 6.7), atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.9), location (8.6 vs 7.5), room (9.1 vs 8.5), value (8.7 vs 7.8), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.6), and service (9.1 vs 8.5). The one area where Dreams holds a structural advantage is family infrastructure — waterparks and a kids club that Secrets simply doesn't offer as an adults-only property. Beach ratings are poor at both resorts (5.0 vs 3.5), though Dreams edges ahead on that metric. Secrets is the stronger resort by the numbers across the board for couples and adult travelers.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children who want a Caribbean Mexico all-inclusive with a kids club and waterparks for all ages. If keeping younger guests entertained is the primary trip driver and the lower food, pool, and atmosphere scores are an acceptable trade-off, Dreams Puerto Morelos delivers the family infrastructure.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a polished, high-scoring adults-only all-inclusive in Los Cabos with golf, spa, nightclub, fishing, and archery. Guests who prioritize room quality, cleanliness, service, and food over beach access will find Secrets Puerto Los Cabos consistently outperforms on the metrics that matter most.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Puerto Morelos benefits from the Yucatan's dry season between December and April, avoiding Caribbean hurricane season which peaks August through October. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos sits on the Baja Pacific side where Los Cabos enjoys sunshine most of the year, though September and October carry some hurricane risk. Both resorts sit in the same price tier, making shoulder seasons like May or November worth considering for better availability.","activities":"At Dreams Puerto Morelos, the focus is on family water activities, beach access, and the dual waterparks alongside the Caribbean reef nearby at Puerto Morelos National Park. At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, the activity range is broader for adults: on-site golf, fishing charters, archery, yoga, spa treatments, a nightclub, and evening entertainment, with the historic art galleries and restaurants of San Jose del Cabo town easily accessible from the resort."},"dreams-playa-bonita-panama-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Playa Bonita Panama is a family all-inclusive on the Pacific coast near Panama City, with a kids club for under-4s and no-reservation dining, but it underperforms on several key metrics: food rates at just 6.7, pool at 6.6, and beach at a low 4.0, reflecting its urban-adjacent, non-traditional beach setting. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo, Mexico, with a golf course, spa, archery, swim-up bar, and nightclub, and it substantially outrates Dreams across almost every category — overall 8.9 vs 7.4, food 8.1 vs 6.7, rooms 9.1 vs 7.6, cleanliness 9.4 vs 8.0, and value 8.7 vs 7.2. Beach scores are poor at both properties (3.5 vs 4.0), so neither delivers a classic powdery-sand experience. Secrets wins on atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.5) and location (8.6 vs 7.6). Dreams' primary advantage is its family-friendly programming and proximity to Panama City for travelers combining a resort stay with urban exploration.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with very young children who are combining a Panama City city visit with a resort stay and want a no-reservation all-inclusive with a kids club nearby. Those for whom cultural access and convenience to Panama City outweigh resort quality metrics should consider Dreams Playa Bonita.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults-only couples or solo travelers who want a high-performing Mexican all-inclusive with strong food, immaculate rooms rated 9.1, and a full amenity suite including golf, spa, archery, and a nightclub. Guests prioritizing comfort, service, and value for money at a Cabo-area resort will find Secrets consistently delivers.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Playa Bonita is best visited December through April, Panama's dry season, when humidity and rainfall are lowest. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos suits visits from October through June to avoid peak summer heat in Los Cabos; March and April offer ideal weather before holiday crowds arrive. Both resorts carry premium pricing during Christmas and New Year holiday weeks.","activities":"Dreams Playa Bonita guests can explore Panama City's historic Casco Viejo neighborhood, the Panama Canal, and nearby rainforest reserves. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos offers on-site golf, spa treatments, archery, fishing charters, and mini golf, with San Jose del Cabo's art gallery district, downtown dining, and East Cape sportfishing excursions a short drive away."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-sunscape-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo with a golf course, spa, archery, fishing, nightclub, and swim-up bar, priced at the upper end of the market. Sunscape Puerto Vallarta is a mid-market family all-inclusive on the Pacific coast of Jalisco, pitched at a lower price tier. The rating gaps are substantial: Secrets leads on overall score (8.9 vs 8.0), rooms (9.1 vs 7.7), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.2), food (8.1 vs 6.2), pool (7.8 vs 6.0), and atmosphere (8.0 vs 6.2). Beach scores are low at both properties, though Sunscape edges ahead slightly (5.3 vs 3.5), reflecting Cabo's rockier Pacific shoreline versus Puerto Vallarta's more swimmable bay beach. Secrets commands a meaningfully higher room rate but delivers noticeably stronger performance across nearly every measurable category. Sunscape's value proposition is its family-friendly positioning and lower price point in a lively destination, not amenity depth or ratings parity with Secrets.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples or groups who want a high-end, amenity-rich Mexican Pacific resort with golf, spa, archery, fishing, and a nightclub in Los Cabos, and are willing to pay a premium for significantly better rooms, food, and overall polish.","whoShouldChooseB":"Budget-conscious families who want a straightforward, affordable all-inclusive base in Puerto Vallarta with decent service and a swimmable beach, and do not need extensive amenities or top-tier food ratings.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season, roughly November through April, when rainfall is minimal and temperatures are comfortable. Los Cabos summers bring heat and occasional hurricane risk; Puerto Vallarta's rainy season runs June through October with heavier, more frequent rainfall. Either destination is at its most reliable between December and March.","activities":"At Secrets Los Cabos guests can play golf, fish, take yoga classes, practice archery, and visit the spa on-site, with whale watching tours, ATV excursions, and glass-bottom boat trips available nearby in the Cabo corridor. Sunscape Puerto Vallarta guests have access to the Malecon boardwalk, zip-lining in the Sierra Madre foothills, snorkeling at Los Arcos, and day trips to the Marieta Islands within easy reach of the resort."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-sunscape-sabor-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos Golf & Spa Resort is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo with an overall rating of 8.9, exceptional room scores (9.1), cleanliness (9.4), and service (9.1), plus a golf course, spa, archery, nightclub, yoga, and fishing. Sunscape Sabor Cozumel is a budget-friendly family all-inclusive on Cozumel with a notably lower overall rating of 7.6, weaker food (6.1 vs 8.1), pool (5.8 vs 7.8), and atmosphere (6.2 vs 8.0) scores, and minimal listed amenities beyond beach access. Secrets Los Cabos commands a significant price premium for its polished adults-only experience, while Sunscape Sabor offers a no-frills family entry point into Cozumel at a fraction of the cost. Beach ratings tell their own story: Cozumel edges San Jose del Cabo 5.8 vs 3.5, reflecting Los Cabos's Pacific surf conditions versus Cozumel's calmer Caribbean waters. If refined adults-only luxury with strong room quality and resort amenities matters most, choose Secrets. If budget and Caribbean beach access for families are the priority, choose Sunscape.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples and solo travelers who want a high-end, amenity-rich Mexican Pacific resort with a golf course, spa, archery, and nightclub, and are willing to pay a premium for consistently strong rooms, service, and cleanliness scores in San Jose del Cabo.","whoShouldChooseB":"Budget-conscious families who want a straightforward, affordable all-inclusive base on Cozumel's Caribbean coast, particularly those prioritizing the island's world-class diving and snorkeling over on-resort amenities and dining quality.","whenToVisit":"San Jose del Cabo is best from November through May, avoiding summer hurricane season and peak humidity. Cozumel's peak season runs December through April with calm, clear Caribbean waters ideal for diving. Both destinations share a shoulder-season sweet spot in late November and early December when prices dip slightly before the holiday surge and weather remains reliable.","activities":"Secrets Los Cabos guests can fish the Pacific, play golf, take archery lessons, and explore San Jose del Cabo's art district and marina. Sunscape Sabor guests are positioned for Cozumel's famous coral reef diving and snorkeling, with the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef minutes offshore. Day trips to Mayan ruins at Tulum or San Gervasio add cultural depth to either trip."},"dreams-cozumel-cape-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Cozumel is a family-friendly Mexican all-inclusive on the island of Cozumel, with a kids club for under-4s and a strong location score of 8.3, but it underperforms on food (6.8), pool (6.7), and especially beach (5.3). Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only resort in San Jose del Cabo with a dramatically higher overall rating (8.9 vs 7.3), superior rooms (9.1 vs 8.2), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.5), and service (9.1 vs 8.3), plus a full amenity stack including golf, archery, spa, nightclub, and swim-up bar. The beach gap is notable: both score poorly, but Secrets sits lower at 3.5 vs Dreams' already weak 5.3, reflecting Los Cabos' rocky Pacific shoreline. Where Dreams leans on Cozumel's Caribbean island setting and family infrastructure, Secrets wins on nearly every quality metric. If the priority is family travel with young children in an island Caribbean setting, Dreams Cozumel delivers. If maximizing resort quality, room comfort, and adult atmosphere in Baja California matters more than beach access, Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is the clear choice.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children, including toddlers, who want a Caribbean island base in Cozumel with easy access to world-class diving and snorkelling reefs, a kids club for under-4s, and a relaxed atmosphere without requiring dining reservations.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who prioritize resort quality above all else and want high-rated rooms, spotless facilities, golf, spa, archery, and a nightclub in a refined Los Cabos adults-only setting, and who are comfortable trading beach quality for overall excellence.","whenToVisit":"Cozumel is best visited November through April when Caribbean humidity drops and hurricane risk fades, though Cozumel sits outside the main hurricane belt. San Jose del Cabo enjoys a desert climate with minimal rain year-round, making Secrets Puerto Los Cabos viable in any season, though summer months bring higher humidity and occasional tropical moisture from the Pacific side.","activities":"Dreams Cozumel guests can access Cozumel's renowned coral reef system for snorkelling and scuba diving, plus ferry connections to the Yucatan mainland. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos guests have an on-site golf course, archery, fishing charters, spa, and mini golf, with San Jose del Cabo's art district, whale watching tours between January and March, and the iconic Land's End rock arch accessible nearby."},"dreams-acapulco-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Acapulco Resort & Spa is a family-oriented all-inclusive on Mexico's Pacific coast in Acapulco, rated a modest 7.4 overall, with notably lower scores across food (6.5), beach (6.0), pool (6.2), and atmosphere (6.3), though it posts solid numbers for cleanliness (7.9), sleep quality (7.9), and service (7.7). Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo rated 8.9 overall, outperforming Dreams Acapulco across virtually every category: rooms (9.1 vs 7.4), cleanliness (9.4 vs 7.9), service (9.1 vs 7.7), food (8.1 vs 6.5), and value (8.7 vs 6.8). The one area where Secrets stumbles is beach, rating a stark 3.5 versus Dreams' already-low 6.0, reflecting Los Cabos' notoriously rough, swim-unfeasible shoreline. Dreams brings a kids club for under-4s and a no-reservation dining policy; Secrets adds a gym, golf course, archery, spa, nightclub, and swim-up bar for adult guests only. These are two very different propositions: a budget-leaning family resort in Acapulco versus a premium adults-only escape in Cabo.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children, including toddlers, who want a no-frills Pacific Mexico all-inclusive in Acapulco at a lower price point. Best suited to guests who prioritize easy dining access and solid service over polished amenities or a standout beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or solo travelers who want a premium, well-appointed all-inclusive in Los Cabos with excellent rooms, top-tier service, golf, spa, and a full evening entertainment program. Those who can forgo swimming in the ocean in exchange for pool-focused relaxation and a refined atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Acapulco's peak season runs November through April when humidity drops and rainfall is minimal; summers are hot and wet. Los Cabos is drier and sunnier year-round, with peak season similarly November through April. Hurricane risk affects both Pacific destinations from June through October, though Los Cabos sees more direct tropical storm exposure in late summer and early fall.","activities":"Dreams Acapulco guests are close to Acapulco's famous cliff divers at La Quebrada and the city's historic malecón. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos sits near San Jose del Cabo's art district and gallery walks, with the resort itself offering golf, archery, fishing, mini golf, and a spa on property. Both destinations offer sportfishing charters and snorkeling excursions, though Cabo's marine environment is considerably richer."},"secrets-aura-cozumel-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Aura Cozumel and Secrets Puerto Los Cabos are both adults-only Mexican all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they differ significantly in quality ratings and setting. Puerto Los Cabos scores substantially higher overall (8.9 vs 7.4), with particularly striking gaps in rooms (9.1 vs 7.6), cleanliness (9.4 vs 8.1), value (8.7 vs 7.2), and service (9.1 vs 8.3). Neither resort excels at beach — Cozumel scores a mediocre 5.5 while Los Cabos scores a poor 3.5, reflecting the rocky, Pacific-facing Baja coastline — but Los Cabos compensates with a far broader amenity set including a golf course, spa, nightclub, archery, swim-up bar, fishing, and mini golf. Cozumel's strongest cards are its location (8.3) and the world-class diving and snorkelling accessible from the island. If you want a premium, amenity-rich Baja adults-only resort with exceptional rooms and service, Los Cabos wins clearly. If you want a diving-focused Cozumel getaway with a more relaxed pace, Aura makes its case on location alone.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who prioritise Cozumel's legendary reef diving and snorkelling over resort amenities, and are willing to accept middling food and pool ratings in exchange for one of Mexico's best underwater destinations on their doorstep. Best suited to divers and marine life enthusiasts.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults seeking a high-quality, well-appointed Baja all-inclusive with standout rooms, exceptional cleanliness, and a full amenity roster including golf, spa, fishing, and nightclub entertainment. Well suited to couples and golfers who want polished service and strong overall value in Los Cabos.","whenToVisit":"Cozumel is best visited November through April when Caribbean waters are calm and visibility for diving peaks. Avoid hurricane season, particularly September and October. Los Cabos enjoys a drier, more consistent Baja climate year-round, though summer months bring higher humidity and occasional tropical storms; November through May offers the most reliably pleasant conditions.","activities":"Cozumel guests can dive or snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, the second largest barrier reef in the world, explore the island by scooter, or take day trips to Tulum and Chichen Itza from the mainland. Los Cabos guests have on-site golf, archery, fishing charters, spa treatments, and easy access to Land's End, whale watching tours, and the downtown San Jose del Cabo art district."},"secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort-vs-sunscape-curacao-resort-spa-and-casino":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only luxury all-inclusive on Mexico's Baja Peninsula in San Jose del Cabo, with a golf course, spa, archery, fishing, nightclub, and swim-up bar, rated 8.9 overall with standout scores for cleanliness (9.4), rooms (9.1), and service (9.1). Sunscape Curacao is a family all-inclusive near Willemstad, Curaçao, rated 7.3 overall, with noticeably weaker scores across food (6.2), pool (6.0), and atmosphere (6.2), though its location rating (8.1) reflects the appeal of Willemstad's proximity. The gap between the two properties is substantial across nearly every category: Secrets leads on food by 1.9 points, pool by 1.8, atmosphere by 1.8, and rooms by 1.7. Secrets is a premium adults retreat with a polished resort experience; Sunscape is a mid-tier family option in a genuinely interesting destination. If you want a refined adults-only Mexican all-inclusive with golf, spa, and excellent service in Los Cabos, choose Secrets. If you want a family-friendly base near Willemstad's colonial city and Curaçao's diving, choose Sunscape.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples and solo travelers who want a high-end, well-serviced Mexican all-inclusive with golf, a spa, archery, and fishing in Los Cabos. Those who prioritize immaculate rooms and attentive service over a standout beach will find Secrets delivers consistently across almost every measure.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families drawn to Curaçao's Dutch-Caribbean culture and world-class diving who can tolerate average food and pool offerings in exchange for a convenient base near Willemstad. Best suited to guests who plan to spend significant time off-resort exploring the island rather than staying anchored to amenities.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos is best visited October through June, avoiding the late-summer hurricane-adjacent heat and humidity of July and August. Curaçao sits outside the main hurricane belt and is visitable year-round, though its driest and most reliably sunny months run from January through September, making it a strong winter or spring option.","activities":"At Secrets Los Cabos, guests can golf the on-site course, fish offshore, take archery and yoga classes, and explore San Jose del Cabo's art district. At Sunscape Curaçao, the draw is off-property: Willemstad's UNESCO-listed colonial waterfront, some of the Caribbean's best shore diving and snorkeling, and cave tours and flamingo sanctuaries across the island's rugged interior."},"dreams-curacao-resort-spa-and-casino-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Curaçao and Secrets Puerto Los Cabos are both priced at the same tier, but their ratings tell starkly different stories. Secrets scores an 8.9 overall versus Dreams Curaçao's 6.4, with Secrets outperforming on nearly every metric: cleanliness (9.4 vs. 7.8), rooms (9.1 vs. 7.3), service (9.1 vs. 7.3), and food (8.1 vs. 7.0). The one area Dreams Curaçao genuinely wins is beach, though neither scores well — Dreams edges out at 5.3 versus Secrets' rocky 3.5, reflecting Los Cabos' notoriously rough Pacific surf. Dreams is a family property near Willemstad with a kids club for toddlers and a casino; Secrets is an adults-only retreat in San Jose del Cabo loaded with amenities including golf, archery, a spa, nightclub, and swim-up bar. For the same price point, Secrets delivers a significantly more polished experience across the board. Dreams Curaçao's strongest suit is its location score (7.9) and sleep quality (8.2), suggesting the property is quiet and well-situated for exploring the island.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want a Caribbean base near Willemstad's colorful Dutch architecture and are willing to accept middling resort ratings in exchange for a genuine family setup with a toddler-friendly kids club, a casino, and easy access to Curaçao's distinctive culture and dive sites.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and solo travelers who want a high-performing Mexican all-inclusive in Los Cabos with exceptional rooms, service, and cleanliness, plus a full activity slate including golf, archery, spa, and nightclub — and who won't miss a swimmable beach.","whenToVisit":"Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt, making it a reliable year-round destination; the dry season from January to September offers the most sunshine. Los Cabos is best visited October through June, avoiding the summer humidity and the occasional late-season hurricane risk. Both destinations are busiest over US holiday periods, when prices peak and crowds thicken.","activities":"Dreams Curaçao guests can explore Willemstad's UNESCO-listed waterfront, snorkel the island's renowned reefs, and visit the Curaçao Liqueur distillery nearby. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos keeps guests busy on-site with golf, fishing charters, archery, yoga, and a spa, while the broader Los Cabos corridor offers whale watching, ATV tours, and the famous El Arco rock formation at Land's End."},"breathless-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Puerto Vallarta and Secrets Puerto Los Cabos are both adults-only Mexican all-inclusives at the same price tier, but they sit in very different settings with meaningfully different strengths. Breathless scores higher on beach (6.5 vs 3.5), atmosphere (7.5 vs 8.0 is close), and location (8.7 vs 8.6), reflecting Puerto Vallarta's more established beach resort culture. Secrets Cabos pulls ahead on food (8.1 vs 7.7), pool (7.8 vs 7.0), and value (8.7 vs 8.4), and adds a golf course, archery, fishing, and mini golf that Breathless lacks. The beach gap is the starkest number here: Cabos scores a 3.5 versus Breathless's 6.5, a direct reflection of the Sea of Cortez's rougher, non-swimmable surf. If your priority is a proper beachfront experience with a livelier atmosphere, Puerto Vallarta wins. If you want broader land-based amenities, better food scores, and a golf course in a Baja setting where the beach is more of a backdrop, Secrets Cabos delivers.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a genuine beach holiday on Mexico's Pacific coast, prioritizing a swimmable shoreline, a lively resort atmosphere, and strong service and room quality at a competitive price. Best for couples and friend groups who want a classic Puerto Vallarta all-inclusive experience.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults who want a polished Baja California all-inclusive with strong food scores, a golf course, fishing, archery, and a well-rounded amenity set, and who are happy to treat the beach as scenery rather than a swimming destination. Ideal for golfers and active couples.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Vallarta is best November through April when the rainy season has ended and humidity drops. July and August bring heat and afternoon storms. Los Cabos enjoys more consistent year-round sunshine with very little rain, making it a reliable destination any month, though peak season runs November through April and prices reflect that.","activities":"Breathless guests have Puerto Vallarta's Old Town, the Malecón, whale watching (December to March), and jungle zip-lining close by. Secrets Cabos guests can access Land's End and the famous arch at Cabo San Lucas, world-class sport fishing, ATV desert tours, and the Baja wine country. Both resorts offer on-site spa facilities, pools, and evening entertainment programs."},"dreams-grand-island-cancun-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Grand Island Cancun is a family all-inclusive on Costa Mujeres with a kids club for under-4s, strong service (9.1) and sleep quality (9.0) ratings, and a solid location score (8.5), but its beach rates a notably weak 6.1 and food comes in at just 7.2. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos is an adults-only resort in San Jose del Cabo with a more comprehensive amenity set — golf, archery, spa, nightclub, fishing, swim-up bar — and significantly stronger ratings across food (8.1), rooms (9.1), value (8.7), and atmosphere (8.0). Secrets also scores higher on cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.0). The critical trade-off is beach: Secrets scores a very low 3.5, reflecting Los Cabos's rough Pacific surf, while Dreams scores a modest 6.1 on the calmer Caribbean side. Dreams wins on family infrastructure and beachfront usability; Secrets wins on dining, room quality, amenity breadth, and overall polish for adult travelers. Both sit at the same price level, making the adults-only upgrade at Secrets genuinely good value given its rating advantages.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with very young children who want a polished, low-stress Caribbean all-inclusive in Costa Mujeres with a kids club for under-4s, reservation-free dining, and excellent service and sleep quality scores — and who prioritize a swimmable beach over resort amenity variety.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a well-rounded, high-performing all-inclusive in Los Cabos with golf, spa, archery, fishing, a nightclub, and strong food and room ratings — and who are comfortable with Los Cabos's rocky Pacific coastline and primarily pool-focused beach experience.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Grand Island Cancun is best visited November through April to avoid Caribbean hurricane season and summer humidity. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos suits travel October through June, when the Pacific side of Baja is dry and mild. Both resorts are at the same $$$$ price tier, though Los Cabos tends to peak around winter holidays and Cancun during spring break, so booking early matters for both.","activities":"Dreams Grand Island Cancun keeps families occupied on a calm Caribbean stretch near Isla Mujeres, with ferry access to the island as a natural day trip. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos offers on-site golf, archery, fishing charters, spa, and mini golf, with downtown San Jose del Cabo's art galleries and restaurants a short drive away. Los Cabos also offers whale watching seasonally and ATV excursions into the desert landscape."},"secrets-macao-beach-punta-cana-vs-secrets-puerto-los-cabos-golf-and-spa-resort":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Macao Beach Punta Cana is an adults-only Dominican Republic all-inclusive set on Macao Beach, one of the more secluded and scenic stretches of coastline in Punta Cana, with a beach rating of 8.2 that reflects a genuinely strong seaside experience. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos Golf & Spa Resort is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive in San Jose del Cabo with a golf course, archery, fishing, and a spa, but its beach rating of 3.5 signals that the Pacific-side waters are largely unsuitable for swimming. Secrets Macao edges out on atmosphere (8.1 vs 8.0), sleep quality (9.1 vs 8.1), and location (9.0 vs 8.6), while Puerto Los Cabos wins on overall score (8.9 vs 8.5), value (8.7 vs 8.4), and cleanliness (9.4 vs 9.3). If you want an adults-only Dominican all-inclusive where a genuine swimmable beach is central to the experience, go to Secrets Macao. If you want a Los Cabos adults-only resort with golf, spa, fishing, and upscale amenities where the pool rather than the ocean is your focal point, go to Secrets Puerto Los Cabos.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who want a genuinely swimmable, secluded beach as the centerpiece of their Dominican Republic all-inclusive stay. Strong sleep quality and service ratings (9.1 and 9.2) make it ideal for those prioritizing rest and attentive hospitality over a broad activity roster.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults and couples drawn to the Baja California lifestyle — golf, sport fishing, spa treatments, and dramatic desert-meets-sea scenery — who are happy to swim in pools rather than the ocean. The strong value rating (8.7) makes it an appealing higher-end option for those who want Los Cabos without a punishing price premium.","whenToVisit":"Secrets Macao is best visited November through April, avoiding the Dominican Republic's Atlantic hurricane season which peaks August through October. Secrets Puerto Los Cabos suits year-round travel given Baja California's dry, sunny climate, though July and August bring higher humidity and occasional tropical storms. Los Cabos winter months (November through March) offer the most reliably pleasant conditions and are ideal for golf.","activities":"At Secrets Macao, the beach, pool, and ocean are the primary draws, with watersports accessible from the shore. At Secrets Puerto Los Cabos, guests can play golf on the on-site course, try archery, book sport fishing charters, take yoga classes, and use the full spa. Both resorts offer evening entertainment and nightclubs. The Los Cabos corridor adds nearby art galleries, the historic San Jose del Cabo town center, and ATV excursions into the desert."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a Cuban family all-inclusive on the Holguin coast with a waterpark for little kids, archery, yoga, nightclub, and a strong overall rating of 9.0, backed by standout room (9.0) and cleanliness (9.0) scores. Iberostar Waves Cozumel is a Mexican family all-inclusive on Cozumel island where diving and snorkelling in the Mesoamerican Reef are the headline draw, with rooms for 5+ guests and a higher food score (6.6 vs 6.1). Holguin scores meaningfully higher on beach (8.0 vs 5.3), room (9.0 vs 7.8), overall (9.0 vs 8.8), and cleanliness (9.0 vs 8.7), while Cozumel edges ahead on atmosphere (6.8 vs 6.4) and food. Holguin suits families who want a polished Cuban beach resort with broad land-based activities; Cozumel suits families and divers drawn specifically to world-class reef diving and snorkelling. If you want a high-rated Cuban beach resort with excellent rooms, a waterpark for young kids, and a nightclub, choose Holguin. If you want Cozumel's legendary reef diving and snorkelling in a family-friendly Mexican all-inclusive with large-group room capacity, choose Waves Cozumel.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want a highly rated Cuban beach resort with a waterpark, archery, yoga, and evening entertainment, and who prioritise excellent rooms and cleanliness over diving or reef access.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and diving enthusiasts who want direct access to Cozumel's world-renowned Mesoamerican Reef, with rooms that accommodate groups of five or more and a Mexican island atmosphere, even at a premium price point.","whenToVisit":"Holguin is best from November through April when Cuba's dry season delivers reliable sunshine and low humidity. Cozumel peaks December through April for calm seas, optimal dive visibility, and dry weather. Both destinations become hot and humid in summer; hurricane season runs June through November for both Cuba and Mexico's Caribbean coast, with Cozumel generally more exposed to storm tracks.","activities":"Holguin guests can explore Guardalavaca's beach, visit the nearby Banes archaeological museum, or take excursions to colonial Holguin city. Cozumel guests can dive or snorkel the Palancar and Columbia reefs, explore the island by scooter or jeep, visit the San Gervasio Mayan ruins, or take a ferry to Playa del Carmen for shopping and cenote trips."},"iberostar-selection-playa-mita-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Playa Mita and Iberostar Waves Cozumel share an identical overall rating of 8.8 and price tier, but diverge meaningfully across most subcategories. Playa Mita scores higher on food (7.1 vs 6.6), beach (6.3 vs 5.3), pool (7.3 vs 6.3), room (8.8 vs 7.8), cleanliness (9.2 vs 8.7), and service (9.0 vs 8.8). Cozumel's weaker beach score reflects its rocky, reef-fronted shoreline, which prioritizes diving and snorkelling over swimming. Playa Mita, on the Pacific coast near Punta de Mita, adds a waterpark for little kids, a teen club, a nightclub, a golf course, and rooms accommodating five or more guests, making it the fuller family amenity package. Cozumel counters with world-class reef diving and snorkelling directly off the resort. If you want a polished Pacific Mexico family resort with superior rooms, stronger food ratings, a waterpark, teen club, and golf, go to Playa Mita. If you want a dive-focused Caribbean family resort on a legendary reef island where the underwater experience is the main draw, go to Cozumel.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with kids of all ages who want a well-rounded Pacific Mexico all-inclusive with a waterpark for little ones, a dedicated teen club, a golf course, and stronger across-the-board ratings for rooms, food, and cleanliness.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and diving enthusiasts who want direct access to Cozumel's world-renowned reef system, with snorkelling and diving as the centerpiece of the trip rather than beach lounging or resort amenities.","whenToVisit":"Playa Mita's Pacific coast sees its driest, calmest conditions from November through April; the summer rainy season brings humidity and occasional Pacific swells. Cozumel's Caribbean side is at its clearest for diving from March through June before hurricane season peaks between August and October. Both resorts are busiest over Christmas, New Year, and spring break, with shoulder months like November and early December offering better availability and rates.","activities":"At Playa Mita, guests can play golf on-site, dive, take tennis lessons, and use the waterpark and teen club, with Sayulita's surf town and the Marieta Islands day trip close by. At Cozumel, the Mesoamerican Reef draws divers and snorkellers to some of the best visibility in the Caribbean, and the island's town, San Miguel, offers local restaurants, shops, and ruins excursions to the nearby mainland at Tulum or Chichen Itza."},"iberostar-selection-coral-bavaro-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Coral Bávaro and Iberostar Waves Cozumel are both family-oriented, upper-tier all-inclusives from the same brand, but they diverge sharply on beach and pool quality. Coral Bávaro's beach scores an 8.0 against Cozumel's 5.3, and its pool rating of 7.4 still beats Cozumel's 6.3, reflecting the difference between a wide Bavaro sand strip and Cozumel's famously rocky, ironshore coastline. Food also separates them: Coral Bávaro rates 7.6 versus Cozumel's 6.6, a full point gap. Coral Bávaro adds a casino, nightclub, and waterpark for little kids — amenities Cozumel lacks — while Cozumel counters with a swim-up bar and world-class diving access on the Mesoamerican Reef. Both share an identical 8.6 value score and 8.8 service rating. If a premium beach experience and broader on-property entertainment define your holiday, Coral Bávaro wins. If world-renowned reef diving matters more than sand, Cozumel is the call.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who prioritize a strong beach, a wider amenity set — casino, nightclub, waterpark for toddlers — and better-rated food in a lively Dominican Republic resort corridor. Particularly well-suited to those travelling with a mix of young children and adults who want evening entertainment options.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples where at least one person is a serious diver or snorkeller who wants direct access to some of the Caribbean's best reef diving. Best suited to guests who can accept a limited beach and lower food ratings in exchange for Cozumel's exceptional underwater environment.","whenToVisit":"Coral Bávaro's peak is December through April when the Dominican Republic is dry and breezy; May through August offers lower rates with manageable heat. Cozumel shares a similar dry season window of December to April, with calmer seas ideal for diving and snorkelling. Both sit in the hurricane belt, so late August through October carries elevated risk at either destination.","activities":"At Coral Bávaro, guests have snorkelling, tennis, a waterpark, casino, nightclub, and a spa on a long Bavaro beach with nearby Punta Cana excursions including dune buggies and cenotes. At Cozumel, the focus shifts underwater: the Palancar and Columbia reefs offer world-class scuba diving and snorkelling, while the island also has jungle ATV tours, glass-bottom boat trips, and the San Gervasio Mayan ruins."},"iberostar-selection-rose-hall-suites-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Both Iberostar properties sit at the same overall rating (8.8) and price tier ($$$$), but diverge meaningfully across several categories. Rose Hall Suites scores higher on rooms (8.8 vs 7.8), atmosphere (7.3 vs 6.8), pool (7.3 vs 6.3), sleep quality (8.6 vs 8.1), and food (7.1 vs 6.6), suggesting a more polished, comfortable on-property experience in Montego Bay. Cozumel edges ahead slightly on value (8.6 vs 8.5) despite fewer amenities. Rose Hall Suites adds a lazy river, casino, nightclub, fishing, and a waterpark for little kids — a significantly deeper amenity stack. Cozumel's differentiator is its reef access: snorkelling and diving off one of the world's premier dive destinations. Beach scores are low at both properties (6.0 and 5.3 respectively), so neither should be chosen primarily for sand. Rose Hall Suites is the stronger on-property resort; Cozumel is the better base for underwater exploration.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want a well-appointed Jamaican all-inclusive with a waterpark, lazy river, casino, nightclub, and babysitting — and who prioritise comfortable rooms and a lively on-property atmosphere over access to world-class diving.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and couples who want a solid Cozumel base for snorkelling and scuba diving on one of the Caribbean's best reef systems, and are happy trading a thinner on-property amenity list and lower room scores for unmatched underwater access.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April when rainfall and hurricanes are least likely. Cozumel's underwater visibility is excellent year-round but peaks November to April. Jamaica's summer months bring more rain but lower rates. Both properties sit in the Atlantic hurricane belt, so July through October carries elevated weather risk at either resort.","activities":"Rose Hall Suites guests can fish, play tennis, dive, and visit the historic Rose Hall Great House nearby, with Montego Bay's Hip Strip shopping and dining a short transfer away. Cozumel guests are minutes from Palancar Reef and the island's dive shops, with San Miguel's waterfront town offering local restaurants, ferry connections to Playa del Carmen, and snorkel tours easily arranged."},"iberostar-waves-cozumel-vs-iberostar-waves-paraiso-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Both properties are same-brand, same-price-tier Mexican family all-inclusives with nearly identical overall scores (Cozumel 8.8 vs Paraíso Beach 8.9) and matching ratings for cleanliness (8.7 each) and location (8.3 each). The sharpest gap is in beach quality: Paraíso Beach scores 6.5 versus Cozumel's 5.3, a meaningful 1.2-point difference. Rooms also favor Paraíso Beach (8.2 vs 7.8). Where Cozumel pulls ahead is in diving access — the island's reef system is among the world's best — and in service (8.8 vs 8.6). Amenity breadth clearly favors Paraíso Beach, which adds a lazy river, archery, yoga, bicycles, a nightclub, golf, and free Wi-Fi that Cozumel lacks. Cozumel compensates with snorkelling directly off the property and large family rooms. For guests where the dive and snorkel experience is the primary draw, Cozumel's island setting is irreplaceable. For those wanting a fuller land-based amenity set and a better-rated beach, Paraíso Beach wins on almost every measurable dimension.","whoShouldChooseA":"Divers, snorkellers, and families whose holiday revolves around Cozumel's world-class reef system. Also suits larger groups needing rooms for five or more who want a well-serviced, clean island base and are willing to trade a weaker beach and fewer land amenities for unmatched underwater access.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a broader on-property experience — lazy river, yoga, archery, nightclub, golf, bicycles — with a better-rated beach and roomier accommodations. Ideal for those who want more to do on land and prefer the Riviera Maya mainland over the logistics of a Cozumel island stay.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season, roughly December through April, with low humidity, minimal rain, and calm seas. Cozumel's diving visibility peaks between March and June. Both destinations share hurricane-season risk from August through October. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower prices with generally acceptable weather at both properties.","activities":"Cozumel guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef — one of the world's top dive sites — plus explore the island's small city center and Mayan ruins nearby. Paraíso Beach guests have direct Riviera Maya access for Tulum ruins, Xcaret eco-parks, cenote swimming, and zip-lining, with golf on-site and the full Playa del Carmen dining and nightlife scene a short drive away."},"iberostar-waves-cozumel-vs-iberostar-waves-paraiso-del-mar":{"keyDifferences":"Both Iberostar Waves properties sit at the same overall rating (8.8) and price tier ($$$$), but they serve meaningfully different Mexican Caribbean experiences. Paraíso del Mar is on the Riviera Maya mainland near Playa Paraíso and scores noticeably better on beach (6.5 vs 5.3) and rooms (8.2 vs 7.8), while Cozumel edges ahead on service (8.8 vs 8.6) and value (8.6 vs 8.5). The amenity gap is significant: Paraíso del Mar adds a teen club, nightclub, archery, yoga, mini golf, bicycles, and access to a golf course, making it the fuller-featured resort. Cozumel's defining draw is its island setting and world-class diving and snorkelling on the Mesoamerican Reef, which attracts guests specifically for underwater access rather than resort breadth. If you want a bigger beach, more varied land activities, a nightclub, and a teen program on the Riviera Maya mainland, Paraíso del Mar wins. If the island itself and exceptional reef diving and snorkelling are the point of the trip, Cozumel is the clear choice.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who want to base themselves on Cozumel specifically for its legendary reef diving and snorkelling, and who value strong service and good overall value over a broad amenity list or a wide sandy beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with teenagers or mixed-age groups who want a Riviera Maya mainland resort with a better beach, a teen club, nightclub, yoga, archery, mini golf, and golf access alongside the standard all-inclusive family programming.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Yucatán Peninsula's dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is low and humidity manageable. Cozumel can see stronger winds and choppier ferry crossings in winter months but diving visibility is generally excellent year-round. Paraíso del Mar and the broader Riviera Maya see peak crowds over Christmas, New Year, and spring break, so shoulder months of November or May offer better availability and rates.","activities":"Cozumel guests have immediate access to the Mesoamerican Reef for diving and snorkelling, plus the island's town of San Miguel for shopping and local food. Paraíso del Mar guests can explore Tulum's ruins, Xel-Há, Xcaret, and a string of cenotes within easy driving distance. Both resorts offer on-site diving, snorkelling, swim-up bars, spa facilities, kids clubs, and evening entertainment, though Paraíso del Mar extends the list with archery, yoga, mini golf, bicycles, and golf."},"iberostar-selection-cancun-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Both resorts share an identical overall rating of 8.8 and sit in the same Iberostar family, but the gap between them on beach and pool is striking. Iberostar Selection Cancun scores 8.3 on beach and 7.3 on pool, while Iberostar Waves Cozumel scores just 5.3 on beach and 6.3 on pool — a full three-point deficit on beach alone. Cancun also pulls ahead on food (7.5 vs 6.6), atmosphere (7.4 vs 6.8), and room quality (8.4 vs 7.8). What Cozumel offers in return is proximity to one of the world's top dive and snorkel destinations, plus a marginally better value rating (8.6 vs 8.5). Cancun adds a waterpark for little kids, a lazy river, a teen club, a golf course, and rooms for five or more people, making it the more amenity-rich property. Cozumel is a leaner resort where the real draw sits offshore in the reef, not on the beach or at the pool. If the beach and on-property facilities matter, Cancun wins clearly. If world-class diving and snorkelling are the point, Cozumel makes sense despite weaker scores on nearly every comfort metric.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a polished Cancun beach holiday with strong on-property amenities — a lazy river, waterpark for young children, teen club, golf, and evening entertainment — and who rate beach quality, food, and room comfort as non-negotiables. The consistently high cleanliness and service scores make it a reliable choice.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples where at least one guest is a serious diver or snorkeler willing to trade a weaker beach (5.3) and pool experience (6.3) for direct access to Cozumel's world-renowned reef. Best suited to those who plan to spend the majority of their time in the water offshore rather than on the sand.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is lowest and seas are calmest. Cozumel's diving visibility peaks during this window. Both destinations sit in the Atlantic hurricane belt, so July through October carries elevated weather risk. Shoulder months of May, June, and November offer lower rates with generally manageable conditions at either property.","activities":"At Cancun guests can use the on-site golf course, tennis courts, spa, lazy river, and kids waterpark, with Cancun's hotel zone bars, shopping, and day trips to Chichén Itzá or Isla Mujeres nearby. At Cozumel the focus shifts offshore — the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef offers some of the Caribbean's best diving and snorkelling, and the island's small downtown San Miguel has local restaurants, shops, and ferry connections to Playa del Carmen on the mainland."},"iberostar-selection-riviera-cancun-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Riviera Cancun and Iberostar Waves Cozumel are both four-dollar-sign Iberostar family all-inclusives in Mexico with kids clubs, diving, babysitting, swim-up bars, and buffets, but they differ meaningfully in setting and amenities. Riviera Cancun sits on the mainland near Puerto Morelos on the Riviera Maya, while Cozumel is on the island of Cozumel, famous for some of the world's best reef diving and snorkelling. Riviera Cancun scores higher on rooms (8.8 vs 7.8), cleanliness (9.1 vs 8.7), food (7.1 vs 6.6), and pool (6.9 vs 6.3), and adds yoga, archery, a waterpark for little kids, an adult pool, and free Wi-Fi as distinct extras. Cozumel edges ahead on location (8.3 vs 7.8), value (8.6 vs 8.3), and overall score (8.8 vs 8.7), and includes snorkelling as a dedicated amenity, fitting its reef-rich surroundings. Riviera Cancun is the stronger choice for families wanting more on-site programming and better rooms; Cozumel suits those whose priority is the island's exceptional underwater environment.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a well-appointed mainland Riviera Maya all-inclusive with superior rooms, a waterpark for young kids, an adult pool, yoga, and archery, and who value cleanliness and on-site programming over proximity to world-class reef diving.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and diving or snorkelling enthusiasts who want a solid island base on Cozumel, with easy access to some of the Caribbean's best reefs, at a slightly better value, and who are happy to trade a thinner amenity list for an exceptional underwater location.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is low and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Cozumel's diving and snorkelling visibility peaks in the dry season but remains strong year-round. Both areas see higher prices and crowds over Christmas, New Year, and spring break. Hurricane season runs June through November, with September being the highest-risk month for both locations.","activities":"At Riviera Cancun, guests can dive the nearby Mesoamerican Reef, visit Puerto Morelos village, take day trips to Tulum or Chichen Itza, and use the on-site archery and tennis facilities. At Cozumel, the draw is the Palancar and Columbia reef systems, among the world's top dive and snorkel sites, alongside the resort's own snorkelling amenity. San Miguel de Cozumel offers shopping, local restaurants, and ferry connections to the mainland."},"iberostar-waves-cozumel-vs-iberostar-waves-dominicana":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Cozumel and Iberostar Waves Dominicana are both large family all-inclusives in the same brand family at the same price tier, but they differ significantly in setting and amenity mix. Cozumel's beach scores a weak 5.3 versus Dominicana's 7.8, reflecting the difference between Cozumel's rocky, reef-fronted shore and Bavaro's wide sandy strip. Dominicana also edges ahead on rooms (8.2 vs 7.8) and sleep quality (8.3 vs 8.1), while Cozumel leads on overall score (8.8 vs 8.6) and service (8.8 vs 8.6). The activity mix diverges sharply: Cozumel offers diving and snorkelling in some of the world's best reef waters, while Dominicana counters with a waterpark for little kids, a teen club, nightclub, and casino. Food ratings are nearly identical and unremarkable at both (6.6 vs 6.8). Choose Cozumel if world-class reef diving and snorkelling matter more than a sandy beach; choose Dominicana if beach quality, a waterpark, nightclub, and broader teen programming are the priority.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who prioritise world-class diving and snorkelling over a sandy beach, and want the highest service scores in the Iberostar Waves lineup. Ideal for underwater enthusiasts who will spend more time on the reef than on the shore.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with a wide age range who want a proper sandy Bavaro beach, a waterpark for younger kids, a teen club, a nightclub, and a casino, all in a large Dominican Republic resort that scores slightly better on rooms and sleep quality.","whenToVisit":"Cozumel is best from December through April when seas are calm and reef visibility peaks; hurricane season runs June through November. Dominicana in Bavaro shares a similar Caribbean calendar, with December through April offering the driest, most reliable weather. Both resorts see higher prices and fuller occupancy over the Christmas and New Year period.","activities":"Cozumel guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, one of the world's largest coral systems, and explore the island by scooter or jeep. Dominicana guests have Bavaro beach for watersports, a nearby golf course, and easy access to Punta Cana excursions including zip-lining, cenote visits, and dune-buggy tours. Both resorts offer tennis, spa treatments, and evening entertainment on-site."},"iberostar-origin-daiquiri-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Daiquiri is a Cuban family all-inclusive on Cayo Guillermo, a remote island accessed by causeway, with a standout beach rating of 8.5 and a broad amenity set including horseback riding, watersports equipment rentals, a nightclub, and a kids club. Iberostar Waves Cozumel is a Mexican family all-inclusive on the island of Cozumel, rated significantly higher overall (8.8 vs 8.4), with notably better service (8.8 vs 8.1), cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.0), sleep quality (8.1 vs 7.4), and food (6.6 vs 5.6), but a much weaker beach score (5.3 vs 8.5). Daiquiri wins decisively on beach and adds horseback riding and a nightclub not found at Cozumel. Cozumel compensates with superior rooms (7.8 vs 7.3), atmosphere (6.8 vs 6.0), and large-family room configurations. Both have comparable location scores. Daiquiri suits beach-first families in a remote Cuban setting; Cozumel suits families prioritizing service quality and world-class diving over sand.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who put a pristine, uncrowded Caribbean beach above all else and want a remote Cuban island escape with horseback riding, a nightclub, and watersports. Those comfortable with Cuba's limited connectivity and willing to trade service polish for natural setting and lower price will find Daiquiri a strong fit.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families, including large groups needing rooms for five or more, who prioritize exceptional service, cleanliness, and sleep quality over a top-tier beach. Divers and snorkellers will appreciate Cozumel's world-renowned reef access, and those wanting a higher-polish Mexican all-inclusive experience at a premium price will be rewarded here.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak in the dry season from December through April. Cayo Guillermo can see Atlantic weather effects June through November, with hurricane risk highest August through October. Cozumel sits in the Caribbean and shares a similar hurricane window, though its dive conditions remain good year-round. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower prices at both properties with generally acceptable weather.","activities":"Daiquiri guests can dive, snorkel, rent watersports equipment, ride horses along the beach, and use the tennis courts, with evening entertainment and a nightclub on-site. Cozumel guests dive and snorkel some of the Caribbean's most celebrated reefs, with the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef system immediately offshore. Both offer kids clubs, spas, swim-up bars, and evening entertainment programs suitable for families."},"iberostar-origin-tainos-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Tainos is a family all-inclusive on Varadero's celebrated beach strip in Cuba, with windsurfing, fishing, yoga, a nightclub, and babysitting on one of the Caribbean's most iconic stretches of sand. Iberostar Waves Cozumel is a family all-inclusive on the Mexican island of Cozumel, built around world-class diving and snorkelling, with a swim-up bar, spa, and rooms sleeping five or more. The beach gap is the starkest contrast: Tainos scores 9.0 versus Cozumel's 5.3, reflecting Varadero's powdery white shoreline against Cozumel's rocky, reef-fronted coast. Cozumel leads on service (8.8 vs 8.2), cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.1), food (6.6 vs 5.8), and sleep quality (8.1 vs 7.5). Tainos offers more watersports variety including windsurfing and fishing, while Cozumel's main draw is diving and snorkelling on the Mesoamerican Reef. If a world-class beach is the priority, Tainos wins clearly. If underwater experiences and sharper overall polish matter more, Cozumel is the stronger choice.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples for whom a stunning beach is non-negotiable, who also want a lively Cuban all-inclusive with windsurfing, fishing, yoga, and a nightclub on Varadero's famous shoreline at a solid value.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families, especially those with older children or diving-enthusiast parents, who want a polished Mexican island all-inclusive with access to the Mesoamerican Reef, a swim-up bar, spa, and large-group rooms, and can accept a modest beach.","whenToVisit":"Varadero is best from December through April when humidity and hurricane risk are lowest, though Cuba's peak season means higher prices. Cozumel shares a similar dry-season window of December through April, avoiding the June–November Atlantic hurricane season. Both destinations see their warmest, calmest conditions in early spring, making February and March the sweet spot for either trip.","activities":"At Tainos, guests can windsurf, fish, play tennis, take yoga classes, and enjoy Varadero's long beach, with the colonial city of Matanzas and Varadero's cave systems nearby. At Cozumel, diving and snorkelling on the Mesoamerican Reef are the headline draws, supplemented by tennis and a spa on-site, plus island-wide dive shops, cenotes, and the San Gervasio Mayan ruins accessible by taxi or rental."},"iberostar-waves-cozumel-vs-iberostar-waves-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Cozumel and Iberostar Waves Punta Cana are both large family all-inclusives from the same brand at the same price tier, but they diverge sharply on beach quality and activity focus. Punta Cana scores a 7.8 for beach versus Cozumel's notably low 5.3, a gap of 2.5 points that reflects Cozumel's rocky, reef-fronted shoreline compared to Punta Cana's wide sandy strip. Punta Cana also edges ahead on rooms (8.2 vs 7.8) and sleep quality (8.3 vs 8.1). Cozumel counters with a swim-up bar that Punta Cana lacks, and its location rating of 8.3 reflects world-class reef diving and snorkelling directly offshore. Punta Cana adds a teen club, nightclub, casino, waterpark for little kids, and a golf course, making it a more entertainment-dense resort for mixed-age families. If you want elite Caribbean diving and snorkelling in Cozumel with a swim-up bar, accept the weak beach. If you want a better beach, a waterpark, nightclub, casino, and teen programming in the Dominican Republic, Punta Cana is the stronger all-round family package.","whoShouldChooseA":"Divers, snorkellers, and families who prioritize direct reef access over a sandy beach. Cozumel's underwater world is the main draw here, and the swim-up bar and strong service ratings (8.8) reward guests who treat the ocean itself as their amenity rather than the shoreline.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with kids and teenagers who want a proper sandy beach alongside a fuller on-resort entertainment program. The teen club, nightclub, casino, waterpark, and golf course give every age group something dedicated, and the 7.8 beach rating means the shoreline actually delivers.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak from December through April when rainfall is minimal and humidity is lower. Cozumel sits in the Caribbean hurricane belt but benefits from the island's positioning, which deflects some storm tracks. Punta Cana's hurricane season runs June through November, with September the highest-risk month. Both resorts offer better rates and thinner crowds in May and early June before the rainy season intensifies.","activities":"Cozumel guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, one of the world's top dive sites, plus explore the island by scooter or visit San Miguel town. Punta Cana guests have on-site golf, a casino, and a waterpark, with excursions to Saona Island, cenotes, and Bavaro's wider resort strip nearby. Both resorts offer tennis, spa, diving, evening entertainment, and kids club programming on property."},"iberostar-selection-bavaro-suites-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Bávaro Suites and Iberostar Waves Cozumel are both upscale family all-inclusives from the same hotel group, but they serve meaningfully different travel priorities. Bávaro Suites scores significantly higher on beach (8.0 vs 5.3) and pool (7.1 vs 6.3), and adds amenities Cozumel lacks entirely — a nightclub, yoga classes, a waterpark for little kids, and a pets policy. Cozumel edges out Bávaro on overall rating (8.8 vs 8.6) and room quality (7.8 vs 8.5 in Bávaro's favour), but its beach score of 5.3 is a serious gap for beach-holiday seekers. Cozumel's strength is its location rating (8.3) and world-class diving and snorkelling on one of the Caribbean's premier reef systems. Bávaro's food rating of 7.5 is notably stronger than Cozumel's 6.6. Both match on value (8.6) and service (8.8). Choose Bávaro for a fuller beach-and-pool family experience in the Dominican Republic; choose Cozumel if underwater activities on a legendary reef matter more than the beach itself.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a strong beach holiday with a proper kids waterpark, nightclub, yoga, and a wide amenity set in the Dominican Republic. Those traveling with pets or needing large group rooms will appreciate the extra flexibility Bávaro Suites offers over Cozumel.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and couples drawn to Cozumel's world-renowned diving and snorkelling who are willing to accept a modest beach in exchange for exceptional reef access. Guests who prioritise underwater experiences over poolside or beach time will find Cozumel's location the real draw.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in the Caribbean's peak dry season from December through April. Cozumel's hurricane exposure is lower than the Dominican Republic's, making it slightly more reliable in the September–October shoulder period. Bávaro's beach is at its calmest and most appealing from January through March, when trade winds are gentler and the Sargassum seaweed risk is lower.","activities":"At Bávaro, guests can dive, play tennis, take yoga classes, and enjoy a kids waterpark and evening entertainment on one of the DR's busiest resort strips, with Punta Cana excursions nearby. At Cozumel, the island's famous reef system is the headline — diving and snorkelling are exceptional — and the charming town of San Miguel offers local restaurants, shops, and ferry connections to the Yucatán mainland."},"iberostar-origin-playa-alameda-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Playa Alameda is an adults-only all-inclusive on Varadero's famed beach strip in Cuba, with a strong beach score of 8.8 but notably weak food and pool ratings of 5.6 each and a modest atmosphere score of 6.1. Iberostar Waves Cozumel is a family all-inclusive on the island of Cozumel, Mexico, rated higher overall at 8.8 versus Alameda's 8.3, with better food at 6.6, stronger service at 8.8 versus 8.0, superior cleanliness at 8.7 versus 7.8, and a location score of 8.3 versus 7.9. The key trade-off is beach versus diving: Alameda delivers one of the Caribbean's best beaches with a score of 8.8, while Cozumel's beach scores only 5.3 but sits atop world-class reef diving and snorkelling. Alameda suits adults who want a quiet Cuban beach escape; Cozumel suits families and divers who prioritise underwater experiences, better service consistency, and rooms that accommodate five or more guests over a premium beach frontage.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults without children who want a quiet Cuban all-inclusive anchored by one of the Caribbean's highest-rated beaches, with yoga, watersports rentals, tennis, and evening entertainment, and who can tolerate below-average food and pool ratings in exchange for a standout shoreline.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and diving enthusiasts who want a well-run Cozumel all-inclusive with world-class reef access, a kids club, babysitting, a swim-up bar, and rooms large enough for five or more, and who prioritise service quality, cleanliness, and value over beach quality.","whenToVisit":"Varadero's dry season runs November through April, making those months ideal for Iberostar Origin Playa Alameda. Cozumel shares a similar dry window from November through April, with calmer seas and optimal diving visibility. Both properties are best avoided during Atlantic hurricane season, which peaks from August through October, though Cozumel carries slightly higher hurricane exposure as a Mexican Caribbean island.","activities":"At Iberostar Origin Playa Alameda guests can enjoy watersports rentals, yoga, tennis, a spa, gym, and evening entertainment along Varadero's long white-sand beach. At Iberostar Waves Cozumel the draw is reef diving and snorkelling on the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, alongside a swim-up bar, spa, gym, tennis, and kids programming. Off-site, Cozumel adds scooter rentals, island exploration, and ferry access to Playa del Carmen on the mainland."},"iberostar-waves-cozumel-vs-iberostar-waves-rose-hall-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Cozumel is a large family all-inclusive on Mexico's Cozumel island, rated 8.8 overall with standout service (8.8) and cleanliness (8.7), and a particularly strong value score (8.6). It edges out Rose Hall Beach on overall rating by 0.3 points, atmosphere (6.8 vs 6.2), and value (8.6 vs 8.3). Its defining advantage is access to Cozumel's world-class diving and snorkelling reefs, plus rooms accommodating five or more guests. Iberostar Waves Rose Hall Beach sits near Montego Bay, Jamaica, scoring slightly higher on beach (5.5 vs 5.3), pool (6.4 vs 6.3), room quality (8.0 vs 7.8), and sleep quality (8.2 vs 8.1), and adds a nightclub Cozumel lacks. Both share identical location scores (8.3) and near-identical food scores (6.5–6.6), which are the weakest marks at both properties. Cozumel suits families who want superior reef access and larger room configurations; Rose Hall Beach suits those who want a Jamaican setting with a nightclub and marginally better rooms.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families, particularly larger groups needing rooms for five or more, who want a high-value Mexican island all-inclusive with world-class diving and snorkelling on Cozumel's reefs, strong service scores, and a clean, well-run property as their base.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and mixed-age groups who want a Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a nightclub, slightly higher-rated rooms, and a beach-and-pool setup, and who are less focused on reef diving as a primary draw.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from a December–April dry season when rainfall is lowest and humidity most manageable. Cozumel's diving visibility peaks in this window. Montego Bay's wet season runs June–November and overlaps with Atlantic hurricane season, which also affects Cozumel; both properties carry similar weather risk in those months. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with generally acceptable conditions at either resort.","activities":"Cozumel guests can dive and snorkel some of the Caribbean's top-rated reefs directly from the resort, with tennis, a spa, and evening entertainment on-site, and downtown Cozumel's shops and ferry to Playa del Carmen close by. Rose Hall Beach guests have diving, tennis, a spa, swim-up bar, and a nightclub on property, with Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls excursions, and river tubing accessible from the area."},"iberostar-origin-playa-pilar-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Playa Pilar in Cayo Guillermo, Cuba and Iberostar Waves Cozumel in Mexico are both family-oriented Iberostar properties, but they diverge sharply on what they do best. Playa Pilar's defining advantage is its beach, rated an exceptional 9.8 versus Cozumel's 5.3 — a 4.5-point gap that reflects one of the finest stretches of sand in the Caribbean. Cozumel counters with stronger service (8.8 vs 8.2), cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.3), sleep quality (8.1 vs 7.7), and food (6.6 vs 6.1). Overall, Cozumel edges ahead 8.8 to 8.5. Playa Pilar's pool rating of 5.9 and atmosphere of 6.5 are both weaker than Cozumel's already modest scores, suggesting guests come purely for the beach. Cozumel's amenity list is more developed, with diving, snorkelling, a kids club, spa, babysitting, and a swim-up bar making it the stronger all-round resort. Playa Pilar is a destination built around one extraordinary beach; Cozumel is a more complete, consistently operated family package with better service and a world-class dive scene offshore.","whoShouldChooseA":"Beach-obsessed families and couples who rate sand and sea above everything else and are comfortable with Cuba's travel logistics and more limited infrastructure. If an extraordinary, near-deserted Caribbean beach is the non-negotiable priority and pool quality, food, and amenity depth can take a back seat, Playa Pilar delivers.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who want a well-rounded Mexican all-inclusive with strong service, a kids club, babysitting, diving, and snorkelling in the world-renowned waters off Cozumel. Those who prioritize consistent operations, cleanliness, and a reliable amenity set over beach quality will find Cozumel the more dependable choice.","whenToVisit":"Cayo Guillermo is best visited November through April, avoiding Cuba's June–October hurricane season and peak humidity. Cozumel shares a similar seasonal pattern — November to April brings drier, cooler weather and calmer seas ideal for diving and snorkelling. Both destinations see higher prices and occupancy over the Christmas and New Year period, so early booking is recommended for peak weeks.","activities":"Playa Pilar guests will spend most of their time on the beach, with watersports available along the Cayo Guillermo coastline. Cozumel's offshore reef system is among the world's top dive sites, and the resort covers it with on-site diving and snorkelling. Back on land, Cozumel offers tennis, a gym, spa, and evening entertainment, while Cozumel town is a short taxi ride away for shopping, local restaurants, and glass-bottom boat excursions."},"iberostar-waves-costa-dorada-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Waves Costa Dorada is a family all-inclusive on Puerto Plata's coast in the Dominican Republic, while Iberostar Waves Cozumel sits on Mexico's reef-rich island of Cozumel. Both share the same value rating (8.6) and nearly identical cleanliness and service scores, but Cozumel edges Costa Dorada in overall rating (8.8 vs 8.5), food (6.6 vs 6.3), atmosphere (6.8 vs 6.2), and location (8.3 vs 8.1). The beach score tells the sharpest story: Costa Dorada scores a meaningfully stronger 6.3 versus Cozumel's 5.3, making it the better pick for beach-focused families. Cozumel compensates with a substantially richer amenity set — kids club, spa, gym, diving, snorkelling, swim-up bar, babysitting, tennis, and rooms for five or more — versus Costa Dorada's beach-only listing. Rooms score slightly higher at Costa Dorada (8.0 vs 7.8). In short, Costa Dorada wins on beach and rooms at a lower price tier; Cozumel wins on activities, atmosphere, and overall experience at a higher price point.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who prioritize a genuine beach holiday over resort amenities and want a solid Dominican Republic all-inclusive at a lower price point. Costa Dorada's stronger beach score and competitive room and service ratings make it the right call for those content with a simpler, beach-forward stay.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a full amenity package — kids club, babysitting, spa, diving, snorkelling, swim-up bar, and tennis — and are drawn to Cozumel's world-class reef. The higher price tier is justified for those who plan to fill their days with structured activities rather than beach time.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak in the dry season. Puerto Plata runs drier from November through April, though its north-coast location makes it wetter than the DR's south. Cozumel's best weather falls between December and April, with calm seas ideal for diving and snorkelling. Both destinations face hurricane-season risk from June through October, with September and October carrying the highest exposure.","activities":"At Costa Dorada, guests have access to Puerto Plata's amber museum, the Ocean World marine park, and the Pico Isabel de Torres cable car. At Cozumel, the resort's own diving and snorkelling programs tap directly into the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, and the island offers cenote excursions, the Punta Sur ecological reserve, and San Miguel's waterfront for local dining and shopping."},"iberostar-origin-laguna-azul-vs-iberostar-waves-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Laguna Azul and Iberostar Waves Cozumel are both family all-inclusives under the same brand, but they diverge sharply in several key areas. Laguna Azul scores significantly higher on beach (9 vs 5.3), reflecting Cozumel's more reef-oriented coastline versus a traditional sandy beach setup. Cozumel flips the advantage everywhere else: overall rating 8.8 vs 8, service 8.8 vs 7.6, cleanliness 8.7 vs 7.7, food 6.6 vs 5.6, value 8.6 vs 7.5, and sleep quality 8.1 vs 7.4. Cozumel also carries a fuller amenity slate including diving, snorkelling, spa, babysitting, kids club, swim-up bar, tennis, and rooms for 5 or more people. Laguna Azul edges ahead on atmosphere (6.1 vs 6.8 favours Cozumel) and beach quality alone. For families who prioritise a classic beach holiday, Laguna Azul delivers on sand and sea. For families who want a more operationally polished Mexican island resort with strong service, better food scores, and world-class reef diving and snorkelling, Cozumel is the clear choice.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and beachgoers who put a top-rated sandy beach at the centre of their holiday and are willing to accept lower food, service, and cleanliness scores in exchange for one of the Caribbean's highest-rated beach experiences.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families seeking a well-rounded Mexican island all-inclusive with strong service, solid food ratings, excellent cleanliness, world-class diving and snorkelling off Cozumel's famous reef, a kids club, babysitting, and rooms that sleep five or more.","whenToVisit":"Cozumel's dry season runs December through April, with calm seas ideal for diving and snorkelling; hurricane season peaks August through October. Laguna Azul follows a similar Caribbean weather pattern. Both resorts are most reliably sunny and calm in winter and early spring, making that the preferred window for either property.","activities":"Iberostar Waves Cozumel sits beside the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, making it a premier base for scuba diving and snorkelling; the resort offers both on-site. Palancar and Colombia reefs are short boat rides away. Laguna Azul guests have a standout beach for swimming and watersports. Both properties offer evening entertainment and pool facilities, while Cozumel adds tennis, a spa, and a gym to its on-site roster."},"marriott-cancun-vs-marriott-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Both are upscale Marriott family all-inclusives in Mexico at the same price level, with nearly identical overall scores (9.0 vs 9.1), pool ratings (both 7.3), atmosphere (both 7.4), and value (both 8.6). The decisive gap is beach: Cancun scores a 9 versus Puerto Vallarta's stark 5, reflecting the difference between the Hotel Zone's wide, calm Caribbean beach and Puerto Vallarta's narrower, rockier Pacific shoreline. Cancun also edges ahead on location (8.8 vs 8.5) and room quality (8.9 vs 8.7). Puerto Vallarta leads slightly on service (9.2 vs 9.1) and adds tennis and bicycles, while Cancun counters with a pool slide, arcade, diving, fishing, and a dedicated waterpark for small children. If you are prioritizing a genuinely excellent beach experience with watersports, diving, and a fuller kids amenity set in the classic Cancun Hotel Zone, Cancun wins clearly. If you prefer the colonial charm of Puerto Vallarta, tennis, and cycling access despite a significantly weaker beach, Puerto Vallarta is the trade-off.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families for whom a world-class Caribbean beach is non-negotiable, particularly those with young children who will benefit from the waterpark, pool slide, arcade, diving, and babysitting services in the well-connected Cancun Hotel Zone.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and couples drawn to Puerto Vallarta's distinct Pacific coast character who are willing to accept a weak beach rating in exchange for the town's colonial atmosphere, with tennis and bicycles adding active options beyond the water.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in prime Mexican sun-belt territory. Cancun's peak season runs December through April, when Caribbean conditions are driest and calmest. Puerto Vallarta shares a similar dry season from November through May. Both locations see a rainy season June through October, with Cancun carrying some hurricane risk August through October. Shoulder months of November and May offer good weather with lighter crowds at both properties.","activities":"At Cancun, guests can dive, fish, rent watersports equipment, and explore the Hotel Zone's shopping and nightlife, with Mayan ruins at Chichen Itza and Tulum within day-trip range. At Puerto Vallarta, guests can cycle into the historic Zona Romantica, play tennis, explore the Malecon boardwalk, take whale-watching tours seasonally, and reach the Sierra Madre foothills for zip-lining and jungle canopy tours."},"delta-hotels-by-marriott-riviera-nayarit-vs-marriott-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Delta Hotels by Marriott Riviera Nayarit is a family all-inclusive in the quieter La Cruz de Huanacaxtle marina village, north of Puerto Vallarta, with a lazy river, adult pool, kids club, spa, and pets-allowed policy. Marriott Puerto Vallarta Resort & Spa sits in the heart of Puerto Vallarta's Hotel Zone and adds a swim-up bar, heated pool, waterpark for young kids, babysitting, tennis, bicycles, and watersports rentals to a broader amenity set. On ratings, Delta edges ahead on rooms (9.0 vs 8.7) and value (8.7 vs 8.6), while Marriott PV scores higher overall (9.1 vs 8.9), on food (7.7 vs 7.1), beach (5 vs 3), pool (7.3 vs 6.9), atmosphere (7.4 vs 6.9), and service (9.2 vs 9.0). Delta's beach rating of 3 versus Marriott PV's 5 is a meaningful gap. Delta also offers free Wi-Fi; Marriott PV charges for it. If you want quieter surroundings, a lazy river, and strong room quality at good value, choose Delta. If you want a livelier resort closer to Puerto Vallarta's town center with a waterpark, swim-up bar, and better-rated beach and dining, choose Marriott PV.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who prefer a calmer, marina-village setting north of Puerto Vallarta, prioritize well-appointed rooms and free Wi-Fi, and don't mind a weaker beach in exchange for a lazy river, adult pool, and the option to bring pets.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a broader activity lineup, including a waterpark for young children, swim-up bar, tennis, and watersports, combined with a better-rated beach and dining, all in a livelier Puerto Vallarta Hotel Zone location close to town.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the same regional dry season, November through April, when rainfall is minimal and temperatures hover in the mid-to-upper 20s Celsius. December and January bring the coolest, most comfortable conditions. The summer and fall shoulder months see higher humidity and Pacific storm activity, though rates drop and crowds thin considerably at both properties.","activities":"Both resorts offer spa treatments, kids clubs, and beach access on Banderas Bay. Marriott PV adds on-site tennis, bicycles, watersports rentals, and a small waterpark. Delta features a lazy river and a dedicated adult pool. Off-site, both are within reach of whale-watching tours (December to March), sport fishing, the Sayulita surf village, Old Town Puerto Vallarta's Malecon, and jungle zip-line excursions."},"marriott-miches-beach-vs-marriott-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Marriott Miches Beach is a secluded Dominican Republic family all-inclusive on an undeveloped stretch of coastline with a strong beach rating (8.3) and exceptional cleanliness (9.4), room (9.0), and sleep quality (9.1) scores, but a lean amenity set limited to a gym, buffet, swim-up bar, and free Wi-Fi. Marriott Puerto Vallarta is a fuller-service Mexican family resort on Banderas Bay with a kids club, spa, tennis, waterpark, babysitting, heated pool, watersports rentals, and bicycles, scoring a higher overall (9.1) and service (9.2), but with a strikingly low beach rating (5.0) and paid Wi-Fi. The core trade-off is beach versus amenities: Miches delivers a genuinely excellent, remote beach experience in a quieter, newer destination with fewer facilities, while Puerto Vallarta compensates for a weak beach with a broad activity and family programming offering in a well-established resort corridor. Both sit at the same price level and share identical food (7.7) and value (8.6) scores, making the choice almost entirely about destination character and amenity priorities.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who prioritize a pristine, uncrowded Dominican beach and exceptional room quality in an off-the-beaten-path destination, and are comfortable with a minimalist amenity set. Ideal for those who want seclusion and natural beauty over organized programming.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a structured, activity-rich Mexican resort experience with a kids club, babysitting, spa, tennis, waterpark, and watersports, and are happy to trade a weak beach for a full suite of on-property programming in the well-connected Puerto Vallarta corridor.","whenToVisit":"Miches benefits from the Dominican Republic's dry season, roughly November through April, avoiding Atlantic hurricane exposure that peaks September to October. Puerto Vallarta's dry season runs November through May, with the Pacific rainy season peaking July through September. Both resorts offer their most reliable weather in the winter and early spring months, making December through March the safest overlap window for either destination.","activities":"At Miches, guests are largely confined to the beach, swim-up bar, and gym, with the surrounding Miches region offering lagoon tours, whale watching seasonally, and access to undeveloped Los Haitises National Park nearby. Puerto Vallarta guests can use on-site tennis, watersports rentals, a waterpark, and bicycles, while the surrounding area offers zip-lining, jungle ATV tours, sport fishing, Vallarta's historic Malecón boardwalk, and a vibrant restaurant and nightlife scene."},"club-med-columbus-vs-club-med-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Club Med Columbus Isle sits on San Salvador in the Bahamas, a remote outer island rated 9.3 for both beach and location — the highest marks in this comparison — reflecting its uncrowded, pristine setting far from mass tourism. Club Med Punta Cana is on the Dominican Republic's well-traveled east coast, rated 7.3 for beach and 8.9 for location, scores that reflect a more developed, busier environment. Columbus Isle edges out on overall atmosphere (7.4 vs 7.3) and service (8.7 vs 8.5), while Punta Cana leads overall (9.0 vs 8.8) and adds amenities Columbus Isle lacks: babysitting, a waterpark for young children, mini golf, an adult pool, and a water feature. Columbus Isle counters with bicycles and a stronger diving reputation anchored by San Salvador's world-class walls. Both are priced at $$$$, but Columbus Isle's remoteness means a longer, more complex journey. If you want a secluded Bahamian outer-island all-inclusive with exceptional beaches and diving and fewer families, choose Columbus Isle. If you want a fuller amenity set including a waterpark, babysitting, and adult pool in a classic Dominican resort setting, choose Punta Cana.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples and families with older children who prioritize a remote, uncrowded Bahamian beach and world-class wall diving over breadth of amenities. Guests who rate pristine natural setting and service above entertainment variety will find Columbus Isle's 9.3 beach and location scores hard to beat.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with toddlers and younger children who need babysitting, a waterpark, and a dedicated adult pool alongside the standard kids and teen clubs. Guests who want a comprehensive amenity list in a well-connected Dominican Republic location and are willing to trade beach quality for convenience.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in the Caribbean's peak dry season from mid-December through April, when rainfall is lowest and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Columbus Isle's remote Bahamian location makes it more weather-sensitive, with hurricane season (June–November) posing a higher disruption risk given limited flight alternatives. Punta Cana's better-served airport makes rebooking easier if storms threaten. Shoulder months of May and early December offer lower rates at both.","activities":"Columbus Isle centers on some of the Caribbean's finest scuba diving along San Salvador's dramatic underwater walls, plus snorkeling, tennis, cycling, and evening entertainment in a quiet, nature-forward setting. Punta Cana matches diving and tennis with mini golf, a kids' waterpark, a nightclub, and evening shows, and sits close to Punta Cana's wider strip of excursions, zip lines, dune buggy tours, and day trips to Saona Island."},"club-med-les-boucaniers-vs-club-med-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Club Med Les Boucaniers and Club Med Punta Cana are both premium family all-inclusives in the same brand family, but they differ meaningfully in setting, amenities, and overall guest satisfaction. Punta Cana scores higher overall (9.0 vs 8.6) and on value (8.1 vs 7.8), despite identical food ratings (7.4) and near-identical service scores. Les Boucaniers holds a clear edge on beach (8.0 vs 7.3) and location (9.0 vs 8.9), reflecting its stunning Martinique peninsula setting. Punta Cana counters with babysitting, a dedicated adult pool, mini golf, and a waterpark for small children, making it the more comprehensively equipped family resort. Les Boucaniers distinguishes itself with windsurfing, a lazy river, yoga classes, and diving in a more exotic, less resort-dense French Caribbean environment. Pool scores are low at both properties (6.2 and 6.9), so neither should be chosen for pool culture. If you want a more adventurous, watersports-rich setting with a superior beach, go to Les Boucaniers. If you want broader family infrastructure and better overall guest satisfaction scores in a classic Dominican setting, go to Punta Cana.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and active couples who want a premium Club Med experience on a genuinely exceptional Martinique beach, with windsurfing, diving, and yoga in a more exotic French Caribbean atmosphere that feels removed from the typical high-volume resort strip.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who want the most comprehensive Club Med setup, including babysitting, a waterpark for small kids, mini golf, and a dedicated adult pool, in a well-run Dominican Republic resort that consistently earns strong overall guest satisfaction scores.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations offer year-round warmth. Martinique's peak season runs December through April, when trade winds keep Les Boucaniers ideal for windsurfing and the beach at its best. Punta Cana is reliably sunny from December to April as well, with hurricane season (June through November) carrying more risk in both locations, though the Dominican Republic tends to see more rainfall during those months.","activities":"At Les Boucaniers, windsurfing, diving, and watersports rentals dominate, with tennis, yoga, and evening entertainment rounding out the program. Excursions into Martinique's lush interior, historic St-Pierre, and distilleries add cultural depth. At Punta Cana, on-site mini golf, the kids waterpark, tennis, and diving keep families busy, with easy access to dune buggy tours, zip-lining, and Bavaro's extensive excursion market nearby."},"club-med-punta-cana-vs-club-med-turkoise":{"keyDifferences":"Club Med Punta Cana is a large family all-inclusive in the Dominican Republic's Punta Cana area with a kids club for under-4s, teen club, waterpark, mini golf, babysitting, adult pool, and a full evening entertainment and nightclub program. Club Med Turkoise is an adults-only all-inclusive on Grace Bay in Turks and Caicos, one of the Caribbean's finest beaches, with diving, snorkelling, tennis, and a simpler amenity set oriented around beach and water. Punta Cana scores higher overall (9 vs 8.6) and on rooms (8 vs 7.4), while Turkoise leads sharply on beach (9.8 vs 7.3) and location (9.4 vs 8.9), reflecting the world-class Grace Bay setting. Both carry the same price tier, but Turkoise's pool rating is notably weaker (6.2 vs 6.9), suggesting guests go there for the ocean, not the pool. Punta Cana is the better-rounded resort for families; Turkoise is a specialist beach destination for couples and adults who want little more than exceptional water and watersports.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a feature-rich Club Med in the Dominican Republic with a kids club from infancy, teen programming, a waterpark, mini golf, nightclub, and babysitting — and who prioritize a high overall resort rating over a world-class beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or solo travelers who want to anchor their holiday to one of the Caribbean's best beaches on Grace Bay, with diving and snorkelling as the main draws, and who have no need for a kids club, waterpark, or elaborate pool setup.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April in their dry seasons. Punta Cana's hurricane season runs June through November, with September the riskiest month. Turks and Caicos shares a similar risk window but benefits from slightly lower humidity year-round. For either resort, January through March delivers the most reliable weather and calm seas for diving and snorkelling at Turkoise.","activities":"At Punta Cana, guests can explore the broader resort strip, take excursions to Saona Island, go zip-lining, or visit local cenotes. At Turkoise, Grace Bay's reef system is the headline attraction for diving and snorkelling, with whale watching available in season and boat charters to nearby cays. Both resorts offer on-site tennis, spa, and evening entertainment without leaving the property."},"club-med-fortaleza-vs-club-med-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Club Med Fortaleza is a family all-inclusive on Brazil's northeastern coast, a less conventional Club Med destination that earns standout scores for cleanliness (8.8), service (8.8), room quality (8.3), and location (8.7), though its pool rating (6.4) is notably weak and its atmosphere score (6.8) is the lowest of any comparable metric. Club Med Punta Cana is a large family all-inclusive in the Dominican Republic's Punta Cana corridor with a waterpark, teen club, nightclub, spa, diving, mini golf, and babysitting, posting a stronger pool score (6.9), atmosphere (7.3), and a slight value edge (8.1 vs 8.0). The gap in atmosphere is meaningful — 0.5 points — and Punta Cana's fuller amenity list gives it more to do on-property. Fortaleza counters with superior cleanliness (8.8 vs 8.6), service (8.8 vs 8.5), and room quality (8.3 vs 8.0). Both resorts share identical food (7.4) and beach (7.3) scores. Fortaleza suits guests who prize quality of execution; Punta Cana suits those who want more programming and a livelier atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who prioritize immaculate rooms, attentive service, and a less-trafficked Club Med destination on Brazil's northeast coast. Those willing to trade a thinner amenity list for a quieter, more polished on-property experience will feel well looked after here.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a full-spectrum Club Med in the Dominican Republic, with a waterpark for little kids, a teen club, nightclub, spa, diving, and babysitting all under one roof. The livelier atmosphere and broader programming make it the stronger pick for families who want variety and entertainment throughout their stay.","whenToVisit":"Club Med Fortaleza benefits from Brazil's dry season between August and January, when Fortaleza's consistent trade winds also make it a draw for kitesurfers. Club Med Punta Cana sits in the Dominican Republic's peak season from December through April; hurricane season runs June through November, with September and October carrying the highest risk. Both resorts command premium pricing over Christmas and New Year.","activities":"Club Med Punta Cana has the deeper on-property list — diving, mini golf, waterpark, tennis, spa, and a nightclub. Fortaleza's location on Brazil's northeast coast puts world-class kitesurfing beaches and the dunes and lagoons of Jericoacoara within reach for excursions. Both resorts offer beach access, kids clubs, evening entertainment, and gym facilities, with tennis and aquatic programming available at each property."},"club-med-gramado-vs-club-med-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Club Med Gramado is a family all-inclusive in Brazil's southern highlands, set in a lush mountain landscape rather than on any beach — reflected in its low beach rating of 4.6 versus Club Med Punta Cana's 7.3. Gramado compensates with strong location (8.8), room (8.3), cleanliness (8.7), and service (8.7) scores, appealing as a nature and cultural retreat rather than a sun-and-sand holiday. Club Med Punta Cana sits on a Caribbean beach in the Dominican Republic and offers a significantly broader amenity set: diving, a waterpark for little kids, teen club, nightclub, adult pool, mini golf, babysitting, and a spa — most of which Gramado does not list. Punta Cana's pool rating (6.9) edges Gramado's (6.2), and its atmosphere (7.3) narrowly beats Gramado's (7.1). Both sit at the same price tier and score similarly on food (7.2 vs 7.4) and value (8.0 vs 8.1). The defining choice is terrain: a forested Brazilian mountain town versus a Dominican Republic beach resort with full Caribbean amenity coverage.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who want a Club Med experience grounded in scenery and culture rather than beach life — ideally those based in or visiting Brazil who want a polished mountain retreat with strong service and cleanliness scores in a characterful southern Brazilian setting.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who want a full-featured Caribbean beach all-inclusive with diving, a waterpark, teen club, babysitting, nightclub, and spa on a well-rated Dominican Republic beach — particularly those prioritising breadth of activities and a classic sun-and-sand holiday.","whenToVisit":"Gramado sits in Brazil's temperate south and is pleasant year-round, though June through August brings the cooler, drier winter that suits the highland atmosphere; July hosts the famous Gramado Film Festival. Punta Cana's peak season runs December through April, when rainfall is lowest and trade winds keep heat manageable; the Atlantic hurricane season (June–November) brings higher humidity and some storm risk, though prices drop considerably.","activities":"At Gramado, guests are close to the Serra Gaúcha wine country, Canela's Caracol Falls, and the town's well-known chocolate shops and European-influenced streetscape. At Punta Cana, on-site options include diving, tennis, mini golf, and a waterpark, while excursions to Saona Island, Hoyo Azul cenote, and Altos de Chavón are all within reach. Both resorts offer evening entertainment programs consistent with the broader Club Med format."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-iberostar-selection-playa-mita":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a Cuban family all-inclusive on the Holguin coast with a beach rated 8.0 versus Playa Mita's 6.3, and a notably higher atmosphere score (6.4 vs 6.9 is close, but Holguin's overall rating edges ahead at 9.0 vs 8.8). Holguin offers archery, yoga, snorkelling, and a waterpark for little kids, while Playa Mita adds a teen club, diving, golf, rooms for 5+ guests, and free Wi-Fi — Holguin charges for Wi-Fi. Food is a meaningful gap: Playa Mita scores 7.1 versus Holguin's 6.1, and service is stronger at Playa Mita (9.0 vs 8.7). Holguin wins on beach quality and overall score in an off-the-beaten-path Cuban setting; Playa Mita wins on dining, service, golf access, and flexibility for larger families in Mexico's Riviera Nayarit. Both share identical value scores of 8.7 and sleep quality of 8.1, making the decision hinge on destination, beach quality versus dining quality, and whether golf or diving matters.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who prioritise a high-quality Cuban beach experience with strong overall ratings, yoga, snorkelling, archery, and solid value in an authentic Holguin coastal setting, and who can live with paid Wi-Fi and lower food scores.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with teenagers or groups of five or more who want better dining, free Wi-Fi, golf, diving, and a teen club on Mexico's Riviera Nayarit coast, and are willing to accept a less impressive beach in exchange for stronger service and food.","whenToVisit":"Holguin, Cuba is best visited November through April when humidity drops and rainfall is minimal; avoid hurricane season from June through October. Punta de Mita, Mexico also peaks from November through April with dry, sunny conditions; the summer months bring humidity and occasional Pacific storm activity. Both resorts share a similar optimal winter travel window.","activities":"At Holguin, guests can snorkel the clear Cuban coastline, take archery and yoga classes, and explore the broader Holguin region including Guardalavaca beach and local colonial towns. At Playa Mita, guests access world-class surfing at Punta de Mita, diving in the Marietas Islands, whale watching seasonally, and the Four Seasons golf course nearby, with Sayulita village a short drive away for markets and restaurants."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-iberostar-selection-rose-hall-suites":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a Cuban family all-inclusive on the Holguin coast with a waterpark for little kids, archery, yoga, snorkelling, and a nightclub, posting standout scores in rooms (9.0), cleanliness (9.0), and value (8.7), but dragged down by notably weak food (6.1), pool (6.7), and atmosphere (6.4) ratings. Iberostar Selection Rose Hall Suites is a premium Jamaican family all-inclusive in Montego Bay with a lazy river, casino, diving, fishing, and rooms for 5+ guests, scoring better on food (7.1), pool (7.3), atmosphere (7.3), and sleep quality (8.6), while falling short on beach (6.0 vs 8.0). Holguin wins decisively on beach quality and overall value in a more isolated Cuban setting, while Rose Hall Suites delivers stronger dining, a livelier atmosphere, and a broader aquatic offering including a lazy river and diving at a higher price point. If you want a high-value Cuban beach resort with excellent rooms and a quieter atmosphere, choose Holguin. If you want a premium Jamaican suite-only resort near Montego Bay with stronger food, a lazy river, and casino, choose Rose Hall Suites.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and value-seekers who want an excellent Cuban beach experience with standout rooms, strong service, and a solid activity lineup including archery and snorkelling, and who can accept weaker food and pool ratings in exchange for one of the Caribbean's better-value packages.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families needing larger suite accommodations, including rooms for five or more guests, who want a premium Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a lazy river, casino, diving, fishing, and noticeably better dining than the Cuban alternative, and are willing to pay a higher price for it.","whenToVisit":"Cuba's Holguin coast peaks November through April when humidity drops and rain is minimal; the summer months bring heat and occasional hurricanes. Rose Hall Suites in Montego Bay follows a similar Caribbean pattern, with December through April offering the driest, most reliable weather. Both resorts sit in the Atlantic hurricane belt, so July through October carries weather risk at either property.","activities":"At Holguin, guests can snorkel the nearby reefs, take archery and yoga classes, use the tennis courts, and explore Cuban culture through excursions to Holguin city or Guardalavaca. At Rose Hall Suites, guests can dive, fish, ride the lazy river, try the casino, and access Montego Bay's wider attractions including the Rose Hall Great House, Dunn's River Falls day trips, and the city's restaurants and nightlife."},"iberostar-selection-coral-bavaro-vs-iberostar-selection-holguin":{"keyDifferences":"Both Iberostar Selection properties share identical overall (9.0), beach (8.0), and location (8.8) ratings, making the differences subtle but meaningful. Coral Bávaro edges ahead on food (7.6 vs 6.1, a notable 1.5-point gap), pool (7.4 vs 6.7), and atmosphere (7.4 vs 6.4), while Holguin counters with a marginally better room score (9.0 vs 8.8) and sleep quality (8.1 vs 8.7 favoring Bávaro). Coral Bávaro sits in the Dominican Republic's Bavaro strip and adds a casino, rooms for 5+ guests, and free Wi-Fi, making it the more practical family resort. Holguin is in Cuba's quieter Guardalavaca coast and adds archery, yoga, and a swim-up bar, but charges for Wi-Fi and scores considerably lower on food. If you want a Dominican family all-inclusive with a casino, free Wi-Fi, stronger dining ratings, and large-group rooms on a lively beach strip, choose Coral Bávaro. If you want a Cuban beach escape with a swim-up bar, yoga, and archery in a more remote, low-key setting at a similar price, choose Holguin.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and groups of five or more who want a Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a casino, free Wi-Fi, stronger food ratings, and a full entertainment program on Bavaro's well-connected, amenity-rich beach strip.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and couples drawn to Cuba's quieter Holguin coast who value a swim-up bar, yoga, and archery over dining variety, and who don't mind paid Wi-Fi in exchange for a more off-the-beaten-path Caribbean experience.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations shine from December through April when rainfall is lowest and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Bavaro's peak season runs December to March, with shoulder months of May and November offering better rates. Holguin similarly peaks in winter; Cuba's hurricane season runs June through November, overlapping with the Dominican Republic's, so both resorts are best avoided in September and October.","activities":"At Coral Bávaro, guests can snorkel the reef, play tennis, use the casino, visit the waterpark, and tap into Bavaro's broader strip of excursions including Saona Island catamaran trips and quad-bike tours. At Holguin, the focus shifts to on-site archery, yoga, and snorkelling along a less-trafficked Cuban coastline, with excursions to nearby Guardalavaca, the Bahía de Naranjo natural aquarium, and cultural day trips to Holguin city."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-iberostar-waves-paraiso-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a Cuban family all-inclusive on the Holguin coast with a waterpark for little kids, snorkelling, archery, yoga, tennis, a nightclub, and spa, posting standout scores in rooms (9.0), cleanliness (9.0), and beach (8.0) while food (6.1) and pool (6.7) lag behind. Iberostar Waves Paraíso Beach is a larger Mexican family all-inclusive in Playa Paraiso on the Riviera Maya with a lazy river, diving, golf course, bicycles, free Wi-Fi, and rooms that sleep five or more, but its beach rating (6.5) and pool rating (6.5) trail Holguin's beach score by half a point. Holguin wins clearly on rooms, beach, cleanliness, and overall score (9.0 vs 8.9), while Paraíso Beach edges it on food (6.8 vs 6.1), atmosphere (6.7 vs 6.4), and amenity breadth. Cuba's remoteness and paid Wi-Fi are real trade-offs against Mexico's accessibility and connectivity. If you want a Cuban family all-inclusive with superior rooms, a strong beach, and excellent value at a lower price point, go to Iberostar Selection Holguin. If you want a Mexican Riviera Maya family resort with a lazy river, diving, golf, free Wi-Fi, and rooms that fit larger families, go to Iberostar Waves Paraíso Beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want an excellent-value Cuban all-inclusive with high-quality rooms, a solid beach, a waterpark for little kids, and strong cleanliness and service scores, and who can live without free Wi-Fi and golf.","whoShouldChooseB":"Larger families or those who prioritize amenity variety — a lazy river, diving, golf, free Wi-Fi, and rooms sleeping five or more — and prefer the easier international access of Mexico's Riviera Maya over a Cuban destination.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak in winter. Holguin's dry season runs November through April, with hurricane risk from June to October. Playa Paraiso follows the same Caribbean hurricane calendar, with the driest and calmest conditions from December through April. Both resorts are best avoided in September and October, the peak of hurricane season for the western Caribbean and Cuba alike.","activities":"At Holguin, guests can snorkel the local reef, take archery and yoga classes, use the tennis courts, and visit nearby Guardalavaca beach or the indigenous archaeological site at Chorro de Maíta. At Paraíso Beach, guests can dive the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, ride the lazy river, golf, cycle, and day-trip to Tulum ruins, Cobá, or the cenotes of the Riviera Maya just inland from the resort."},"iberostar-selection-cancun-vs-iberostar-selection-holguin":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Cancun and Iberostar Selection Holguin are both family-oriented Iberostar properties with beach access, kids clubs, babysitting, and waterparks for little kids, but they diverge sharply on food, atmosphere, and amenities. Cancun scores food at 7.5 versus Holguin's 6.1, a significant 1.4-point gap that reflects Cuba's well-documented supply constraints. Holguin edges ahead overall (9.0 vs 8.8) and on rooms (9.0 vs 8.4), suggesting a newer or better-maintained physical product. Cancun pulls ahead on atmosphere (7.4 vs 6.4) and pool (7.3 vs 6.7), and offers a considerably richer amenity set: a lazy river, waterpark, diving, golf course, teen club, and rooms accommodating five or more guests. Holguin counters with archery, yoga, snorkelling, and a nightclub, plus Wi-Fi (paid). Cancun sits on the Yucatan hotel zone with easy international access; Holguin is a more remote Cuban destination where the trade-off for outstanding room quality and cleanliness (9.0) is noticeably lower dining standards and a quieter, less polished atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want maximum amenity coverage in a high-energy Cancun setting, including a lazy river, golf, diving, teen club, and large-group rooms. The stronger food scores and easy international flights make it the right pick for those who will not compromise on dining variety or convenience.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples drawn to an off-the-beaten-path Cuban beach experience who prioritize immaculate rooms and cleanliness (both rated 9.0) over dining options, and who are comfortable with paid Wi-Fi and Cuba's characteristic supply limitations in exchange for a quieter, more authentic Caribbean atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Cancun's peak season runs December through April when humidity is low and hurricane risk is minimal; summer months are hot and humid with occasional tropical storms. Holguin, on Cuba's north-eastern coast, shares a similar seasonal pattern, with the driest and coolest conditions from November to April. Both destinations are best avoided during the August to October Atlantic hurricane window.","activities":"Cancun guests can explore the Mayan ruins at Chichen Itza and Tulum, snorkel the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, or play the on-site golf course. At Holguin, snorkelling, archery, and yoga are on-property options, while nearby Guardalavaca beach and the indigenous Taino village museum at Chorro de Maita offer excursions. Both resorts offer evening entertainment and tennis on site."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-iberostar-waves-paraiso-del-mar":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a Cuban family all-inclusive on the Holguin coast with a waterpark for little kids, tennis, archery, yoga, a nightclub, and a spa, posting an impressive overall rating of 9.0 driven by standout room (9.0), cleanliness (9.0), and location (8.8) scores. Iberostar Waves Paraíso del Mar is a premium-priced Mexican family all-inclusive in Playa Paraiso with a teen club, diving, mini golf, bicycles, a golf course, and rooms accommodating five or more guests, with a solid overall of 8.8 but a noticeably weaker beach score (6.5 vs 8.0) and lower room rating (8.2 vs 9.0). Holguin edges ahead on rooms, cleanliness, beach, and overall value (8.7 vs 8.5), while Paraíso del Mar counters with free Wi-Fi, a teen club, diving, mini golf, and larger room configurations. Food is mediocre at both but slightly better in Mexico (6.8 vs 6.1). If you want a higher-rated Cuban beach resort with a strong rooms-and-cleanliness record and a waterpark for young children, go to Iberostar Selection Holguin. If you want a premium Mexican Riviera Maya all-inclusive with teen programming, diving, golf, and family rooms sleeping five or more, go to Iberostar Waves Paraíso del Mar.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who prioritise immaculate rooms and a strong beach experience in Cuba, want a waterpark for little ones, and value excellent cleanliness and service scores without paying premium Mexican Riviera Maya prices.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with teenagers or larger groups needing rooms for five or more who want a premium Riviera Maya all-inclusive with diving, mini golf, a golf course, a dedicated teen club, and the convenience of free Wi-Fi throughout.","whenToVisit":"Holguin's dry season runs November through April, making those months ideal for avoiding rain and humidity. Playa Paraiso shares a similar winter peak season from December through April, when the Riviera Maya sees minimal rainfall and comfortable temperatures. Both resorts get hot and humid from June through October, with hurricane risk elevated across the Caribbean and Gulf of Mexico during that period.","activities":"At Holguin, guests can snorkel the nearby reefs, take archery and yoga sessions, and explore Cuba's Guardalavaca area with its colonial heritage and natural reserves. At Paraíso del Mar, the Riviera Maya offers world-class cenote diving, Tulum ruins, Xcaret eco-parks, and jungle zip-lining a short drive away, while on-site guests can add mini golf, bicycles, and golf to their resort day."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-iberostar-selection-riviera-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a Cuban family all-inclusive on the Holguin coast with a strong overall rating of 9.0, outstanding room scores (9.0), and a notable beach rating of 8.0, making it one of the better-rated beach resorts in Cuba. Iberostar Selection Riviera Cancun sits in Puerto Morelos, Mexico, rated 8.7 overall, with superior service (9.0 vs 8.7) and sleep quality (8.6 vs 8.1), but a significantly weaker beach score of just 5.5 compared to Holguin's 8.0. Food is a meaningful gap too: Riviera Cancun scores 7.1 versus Holguin's 6.1. Riviera Cancun adds diving, fishing, an adults-only pool, and rooms accommodating five or more guests, and includes free Wi-Fi, while Holguin charges for it. Holguin offers a snorkelling program and a waterpark for little kids, but its atmosphere rating of 6.4 trails Riviera Cancun's 6.8. If you want a top-rated Cuban beach resort with excellent rooms and strong value in an off-the-beaten-path destination, choose Holguin. If you want better food, service, and room variety near Cancun with diving and fishing, choose Riviera Cancun.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and travellers drawn to Cuba's culture and relative seclusion who want excellent rooms and a genuine beach experience at strong value. Best for those willing to accept lower food scores and paid Wi-Fi in exchange for one of Cuba's highest-rated all-inclusive experiences on a solid stretch of beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families needing large rooms for five or more guests, or those who prioritise better food, attentive service, diving, and fishing in a well-established Mexican resort corridor. Suited to guests who want free Wi-Fi, an adults-only pool escape, and the accessibility of Puerto Morelos near Cancun airport, even with a modest beach.","whenToVisit":"Holguin's dry season runs November through April, avoiding Cuba's hurricane season peak of August to October. Riviera Cancun shares a similar weather window, with November through April offering the driest, most pleasant conditions on Mexico's Caribbean coast. Both resorts see higher prices and occupancy over the Christmas and spring break periods, so late January through early March offers the best balance of good weather and manageable crowds.","activities":"Holguin guests can snorkel the nearby reef, take yoga and archery sessions, and visit the colonial city of Holguin or Guardalavaca's natural reserves. Riviera Cancun guests can dive the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, fish offshore, and access Puerto Morelos town, the Crococun Zoo, and day trips to Tulum or Chichen Itza. Both resorts offer tennis, kids clubs, waterparks for little ones, swim-up bars, and evening entertainment programs."},"iberostar-origin-daiquiri-vs-iberostar-selection-holguin":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Daiquiri is a family all-inclusive on Cayo Guillermo, one of Cuba's most celebrated offshore cays, with an outstanding beach rating of 8.5 and a strong location score of 8.2 reflecting its remote, reef-fringed setting. Iberostar Selection Holguin sits on Cuba's northeastern coast near Holguin city, scoring significantly higher overall at 9.0 versus 8.4, with a notably better room rating of 9.0 versus 7.3, cleanliness of 9.0 versus 8.0, and sleep quality of 8.1 versus 7.4. Daiquiri counters with a superior beach score (8.5 vs 8.0) and adds diving, horseback riding, and watersports rentals that Holguin lacks, making it the more activity-rich pick for beach and water enthusiasts. Holguin adds a waterpark for little kids, archery, and yoga, and its value rating of 8.7 versus 8.1 suggests guests feel they get more for their money. If you prioritize an exceptional beach, diving, and a remote cay setting, choose Daiquiri. If you want better rooms, cleaner facilities, and stronger overall quality near Holguin, choose Selection Holguin.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who want Cuba's best beach experience on a remote offshore cay, with diving, horseback riding, watersports, and snorkelling as priorities. Best for those willing to trade room quality for an outstanding natural beach and water-activity lineup.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want the highest overall quality within Cuba's all-inclusive market, with superior rooms, cleanliness, and service ratings, plus a waterpark for young children, archery, and yoga. A strong value score makes it especially appealing for those wanting comfort and reliability over a standout beach.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Cuba's dry season, running November through April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity manageable. Cayo Guillermo can feel more exposed to trade winds in winter months, which may affect watersports and diving conditions. Holguin's sheltered coastal position tends to be calmer year-round. Both resorts are best avoided during hurricane season, particularly August through October.","activities":"At Daiquiri, guests can dive, snorkel the reefs off Cayo Guillermo, ride horses along the beach, and rent watersports equipment, with tennis and a nightclub rounding out the evenings. Holguin guests can try archery and yoga alongside tennis, snorkelling, and evening entertainment, with a small waterpark for younger children on-site. Both properties offer spa services, swim-up bars, and kids clubs for daytime programming."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-iberostar-waves-dominicana":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a Cuban family all-inclusive on Holguin's coast with a notably high overall rating of 9.0, standout room score of 9.0, and strong cleanliness at 9.0, but food lags at just 6.1 and pool scores only 6.7. It offers archery, yoga, snorkelling, a swim-up bar, and a small waterpark, with paid Wi-Fi reflecting Cuba's connectivity constraints. Iberostar Waves Dominicana sits in Bavaro on a well-established Dominican beach strip, rated 8.6 overall with marginally better food at 6.8 and a teen club, casino, golf course, and rooms for 5 or more people that Holguin lacks. Beach scores favour Holguin (8.0 vs 7.8), while atmosphere and sleep quality are roughly comparable. Holguin is the stronger pick on rooms, cleanliness, and value, while Dominicana edges it on food and amenity breadth. Cuba's limited Wi-Fi and relative isolation contrast sharply with Bavaro's resort-strip convenience and infrastructure. Both sit at a similar value rating, but Dominicana carries a higher price tag.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who prioritise immaculate rooms and a beach-focused Cuban experience with archery, yoga, snorkelling, and a swim-up bar, and who are comfortable trading off weaker food scores and paid Wi-Fi for Holguin's quieter, more secluded atmosphere at strong value.","whoShouldChooseB":"Larger families needing rooms for five or more, families with teenagers wanting a dedicated teen club, or those who want casino access, golf, and the fuller infrastructure of Bavaro's resort strip in the Dominican Republic, and are willing to pay a premium for it.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations suit a November-to-April visit when Caribbean rainfall is lowest. Cuba's Holguin coast is drier and less hurricane-prone than eastern Hispaniola, making it marginally more reliable outside peak season. Bavaro's Punta Cana area sees the heaviest rain from August through October, so Dominicana is best avoided then. Both resorts are busiest and priciest over Christmas and New Year.","activities":"At Holguin guests can snorkel the nearby reefs, take archery and yoga classes, and use a swim-up bar and tennis courts, with excursions to colonial Gibara or the Guadalavaca beach area available. At Dominicana, Bavaro's wider resort strip opens up golf, casino evenings, and easy access to Punta Cana's zip-lines, dune-buggy tours, and Saona Island day trips, giving the Dominican property a broader off-resort activity market."},"iberostar-origin-tainos-vs-iberostar-selection-holguin":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Tainos sits on Varadero's famous peninsula beach, earning a standout beach score of 9.0 versus Iberostar Selection Holguin's 8.0, and its location rating of 8.3 reflects that well-known stretch of Cuban coastline. However, Holguin pulls ahead in nearly every other metric: overall 9.0 vs 8.5, rooms 9.0 vs 7.5, cleanliness 9.0 vs 8.1, value 8.7 vs 8.1, pool 6.7 vs 5.6, and sleep quality 8.1 vs 7.5. Food scores are similarly low at both properties, 6.1 at Holguin and 5.8 at Tainos, typical of Cuban all-inclusives. Holguin adds meaningful amenities Tainos lacks: a spa, waterpark for little kids, swim-up bar, snorkelling, and archery. Tainos counters with windsurfing and fishing. Varadero is Cuba's most developed resort corridor while Holguin's Guardalavaca coast is quieter and less touristed. If you want Varadero's iconic beach at a solid price, Tainos delivers. If you want better rooms, cleaner facilities, more amenities, and stronger overall value in a less crowded Cuban setting, Holguin wins convincingly.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who prioritise Cuba's best-known beach destination and want watersports like windsurfing and fishing alongside a lively Varadero strip atmosphere. A good fit if Varadero's iconic shoreline is non-negotiable and the slightly lower room and pool quality is an acceptable trade-off.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want the best-rated rooms, cleanliness, and value in this comparison, with a spa, waterpark for small children, swim-up bar, snorkelling, and archery rounding out the offering. Ideal for those happy to trade Varadero's famous beach strip for a quieter, better-appointed resort on Holguin's Guardalavaca coast.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Cuba's dry season, November through April, when rainfall is low and temperatures sit in the mid-to-high 20s Celsius. July and August bring higher humidity and occasional tropical storms but also peak family travel. Shoulder months of May and November offer a balance of decent weather and lower rates at both Varadero and Holguin.","activities":"At Tainos, watersports take centre stage with windsurfing and fishing complementing the beach, plus tennis, yoga, and a nightclub. At Holguin, snorkelling off Guardalavaca's reef, archery, the small waterpark, and a spa broaden the programme. Both offer kids clubs, evening entertainment, babysitting, and tennis. The Holguin area also allows day trips to nearby Banes and indigenous Taíno archaeological sites."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-iberostar-waves-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a Cuban family all-inclusive on the Holguin coast with standout ratings for overall experience (9.0), rooms (9.0), and cleanliness (9.0), alongside a notably strong location score (8.8) and value (8.7). Its beach scores higher than Punta Cana's (8.0 vs 7.8), and it offers swim-up bar, archery, yoga, snorkelling, and a small waterpark. Iberostar Waves Punta Cana is a Dominican Republic family all-inclusive with a teen club, casino, diving, golf course, and rooms accommodating five or more guests — amenities Holguin lacks entirely. Punta Cana edges Holguin on food (6.8 vs 6.1) and sleep quality (8.3 vs 8.1), though Holguin leads on overall score, rooms, cleanliness, and beach. Both share similarly modest pool and atmosphere ratings. The core trade-off is Cuba's higher-rated resort experience and beach against the Dominican Republic's broader amenity set, including golf, diving, a casino, and teen programming, at a higher price point.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples prioritising a high-quality Cuban resort experience with excellent rooms, a beautiful beach, strong service, and genuine value — and who are comfortable with paid Wi-Fi and a more limited activity roster in exchange for a noticeably higher overall satisfaction rating.","whoShouldChooseB":"Larger families or those with teenagers who want a Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a teen club, casino, golf course, diving, and rooms that sleep five or more — and who are willing to pay a premium for that broader amenity coverage despite slightly lower overall and room ratings.","whenToVisit":"Holguin's dry season runs November through April, making those months ideal for beach conditions and minimal rain. Punta Cana is also best November through April, avoiding the Atlantic hurricane season that peaks August through October. Both destinations share the same Caribbean high season, so booking well in advance is advisable for either resort during the winter months.","activities":"At Holguin, guests can snorkel directly from the resort, practise archery, take yoga classes, and enjoy a swim-up bar, with nearby excursions to Guardalavaca beach and indigenous Taino archaeological sites. At Punta Cana, diving, golf, and a casino add on-site options, while excursions to Saona Island, zip-lining, and buggy tours through the Dominican countryside are popular nearby additions for active families."},"iberostar-selection-bavaro-suites-vs-iberostar-selection-holguin":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Bávaro Suites is a premium Dominican Republic family all-inclusive in Bavaro with suites sized for large groups, diving, a waterpark, pets allowed, and access to one of the Caribbean's liveliest resort strips. Iberostar Selection Holguin is a Cuban family all-inclusive on a quieter Holguin beach with archery, snorkelling, and notably higher overall (9.0 vs 8.6) and room (9.0 vs 8.5) ratings, though food lags significantly at 6.1 versus Bávaro's 7.5. The atmosphere gap is stark: Bávaro scores 7.4 against Holguin's 6.4, reflecting Cuba's more low-key resort scene compared to the Dominican Republic's energetic Bavaro strip. Holguin leads on cleanliness (9.0 vs 8.9) and value (8.7 vs 8.6), while Bávaro offers diving, a gym, and rooms accommodating five or more guests that Holguin cannot match. If you want a large, amenity-rich Dominican all-inclusive with diving, pets, and a lively atmosphere, choose Bávaro Suites. If you want quieter Cuban surroundings, exceptional rooms, and strong cleanliness scores at a slightly better value, choose Holguin.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children or large groups wanting a premium Dominican all-inclusive with diving, a waterpark, babysitting, and access to the busy, entertainment-driven Bavaro resort strip. Also suited to pet owners and those who need rooms sleeping five or more.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who prioritise immaculate rooms and a clean, quiet beach environment over buzzing nightlife and a broad activity menu. Guests drawn to Cuba's distinct cultural setting and comfortable with slower-paced resort life and more limited food options will find Holguin well-suited.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Caribbean's dry season, roughly mid-December through April, when rainfall is low and humidity manageable. The Dominican Republic's Bavaro coast can see tropical weather year-round but peaks June through October. Cuba's Holguin region similarly sees its wettest months in summer and autumn. Either resort is at its best November through April, with shoulder months May and November offering fewer crowds and reasonable conditions at both.","activities":"At Bávaro Suites, guests can dive directly from the resort, play tennis, join yoga classes, and access a waterpark and nightclub without leaving the property, with Punta Cana's shops and excursions nearby. Holguin guests can snorkel, try archery, attend evening entertainment, and visit one of Cuba's less-touristed provincial cities. Both resorts offer kids clubs, babysitting, swim-up bars, tennis, and spa facilities for a well-rounded family stay."},"iberostar-origin-playa-alameda-vs-iberostar-selection-holguin":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Playa Alameda is an adults-only all-inclusive on Varadero's well-known beach strip, rated 8.3 overall, with a strong beach score of 8.8 but notably weak food and pool ratings of 5.6 each and a subdued atmosphere score of 6.1. Iberostar Selection Holguin is a family all-inclusive on Cuba's less-visited Holguin coast, rated 9.0 overall, with standout scores for rooms (9.0), cleanliness (9.0), service (8.7), value (8.7), and sleep quality (8.1) that consistently outpace Playa Alameda across nearly every category. Holguin's beach scores slightly lower at 8.0 versus 8.8, and its food rating of 6.1 edges Alameda's 5.6 only marginally. The gap in atmosphere is small (6.4 vs 6.1), but Holguin's family amenity set is considerably broader, adding a kids club, babysitting, swim-up bar, archery, snorkelling, and a waterpark. Playa Alameda trades on Varadero's famous beach and an adults-only quiet, while Holguin delivers a more polished, better-value all-around experience in a less crowded Cuban destination.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who want Cuba's iconic Varadero beach as their primary draw and prefer a quieter, adults-only environment with yoga, tennis, spa, and watersports. Best suited to those willing to accept modest food and pool ratings in exchange for one of Cuba's most celebrated stretches of sand.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families seeking a high-performing Cuban all-inclusive with excellent rooms, cleanliness, and service scores, a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, and snorkelling in a less touristy Holguin setting. Also suits couples who prioritise overall resort quality and value over the name recognition of Varadero.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Cuba's dry season running November through April, when rainfall is lowest and humidity is manageable. December through March offers the most reliably sunny weather at both Varadero and Holguin. The shoulder months of November and April provide good conditions with smaller crowds. Avoid June through October when hurricane season brings higher rainfall risk across the island.","activities":"At Playa Alameda guests can enjoy watersports rentals, tennis, yoga, spa treatments, and evening entertainment along the Varadero strip, with access to Varadero town and day trips to Havana. At Holguin guests can snorkel, practice archery, use the waterpark, attend yoga classes, and visit the nightclub, with nearby excursions to Guardalavaca beach, Banes, and the Bahía de Naranjo nature reserve offering additional variety beyond the resort grounds."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-iberostar-waves-rose-hall-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a large Cuban family all-inclusive on the beaches of Holguin, with standout ratings for overall experience (9.0), rooms (9.0), cleanliness (9.0), and location (8.8), plus a notably strong value score of 8.7. It adds archery, yoga, snorkelling, a waterpark for little kids, and paid Wi-Fi to a solid amenity lineup. Iberostar Waves Rose Hall Beach is a Jamaican family all-inclusive near Montego Bay with diving on offer but weaker scores across the board, including a beach rating of just 5.5 versus Holguin's 8.0, a pool score of 6.4 versus 6.7, and an overall rating 0.5 points lower at 8.5. Holguin's rooms score a full point higher (9.0 vs 8.0) and its value rating edges ahead (8.7 vs 8.3). Rose Hall adds scuba diving, which Holguin lacks, and sits at a higher price point. If you want a higher-rated, better-value Cuban family resort with superior rooms and a strong beach, go to Iberostar Selection Holguin. If you want a Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with diving access and a familiar international setting, go to Iberostar Waves Rose Hall Beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who want a high-scoring, excellent-value Cuban all-inclusive with superior rooms, a strong beach, snorkelling, archery, yoga, and a waterpark for little kids, and who are comfortable with the paid Wi-Fi and the experience of visiting Cuba.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who prioritise scuba diving access and want a Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay's conveniences and airport, and who are less focused on beach quality or squeezing maximum value from their budget.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak between December and April, when Caribbean weather is driest and most reliable. Cuba's Holguin coast can see rain from May through October, with September and October carrying the highest hurricane risk. Jamaica's Montego Bay shares a similar pattern, with its own hurricane exposure peaking August through October. For either resort, booking the November-to-April window secures the best conditions.","activities":"At Iberostar Selection Holguin, guests can snorkel the nearby reef, take archery and yoga classes, use the waterpark, and explore the culturally rich Holguin region including Guardalavaca beach area. At Iberostar Waves Rose Hall Beach, guests can dive with the on-site dive operation, explore Montego Bay's Hip Strip and duty-free shopping, visit the nearby Rose Hall Great House, or arrange excursions to Dunn's River Falls and the Blue Mountains."},"iberostar-origin-playa-pilar-vs-iberostar-selection-holguin":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Playa Pilar and Iberostar Selection Holguin are both Cuban family all-inclusives from the same chain, but they diverge sharply on what they do best. Playa Pilar's beach rating of 9.8 is the standout number here — one of the highest in the Caribbean — reflecting its position on Cayo Guillermo's famous white-sand shores, but its pool (5.9) and atmosphere (6.5) ratings lag noticeably. Holguin scores higher overall (9.0 vs 8.5), with stronger room quality (9.0 vs 8.1), cleanliness (9.0 vs 8.3), value (8.7 vs 8.0), and sleep quality (8.1 vs 7.7), and it adds amenities Playa Pilar lacks: a kids club, archery, waterpark for little kids, babysitting, nightclub, and spa. Food ratings are identical at 6.1. Playa Pilar is a beach-first resort where the setting carries the experience; Holguin is a more complete, better-run family resort where the infrastructure and service quality are consistently higher across every measured dimension except the beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Beach-obsessed families and couples who consider the sand and sea their entire holiday and are happy to overlook weaker pool, atmosphere, and amenity ratings in exchange for access to one of Cuba's most spectacular beaches on Cayo Guillermo.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who want a well-rounded Cuban all-inclusive with stronger rooms, cleanliness, service, and a full amenity set including a kids club, babysitting, waterpark, spa, and nightclub, and are willing to trade a top-tier beach for a more reliably polished resort experience.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Cuba's dry season, running November through April, when humidity is lower and rainfall minimal. Peak months of December through March bring the best weather but higher prices. Holguin on Cuba's eastern coast can see slightly different rainfall patterns than Cayo Guillermo, but both follow the same broad Caribbean seasonal rhythm. Avoid hurricane season's peak from August through October if possible.","activities":"Playa Pilar guests have the beach itself as the primary draw, with snorkelling in clear shallow waters around Cayo Guillermo and access to the surrounding cays. Holguin guests can pursue archery, yoga, tennis, snorkelling, and evening entertainment on site, with a waterpark and kids club adding structure for families. Both resorts sit within reach of Cuban cultural excursions, and Holguin's proximity to the city offers additional off-resort sightseeing options."},"iberostar-selection-holguin-vs-iberostar-waves-costa-dorada":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Selection Holguin is a large Cuban family all-inclusive on the Holguin coast with a notably strong overall rating of 9.0 versus Costa Dorada's 8.5, and it pulls ahead in room quality (9.0 vs 8.0), beach (8.0 vs 6.3), pool (6.7 vs 6.0), and cleanliness (9.0 vs 8.6). Holguin also carries a substantially broader amenity set: kids club, waterpark for little kids, babysitting, archery, snorkelling, yoga, tennis, swim-up bar, nightclub, spa, gym, and evening entertainment. Iberostar Waves Costa Dorada is a Dominican Republic family all-inclusive in Puerto Plata with a beach and little else listed by way of amenities, though food ratings are marginally closer (6.3 vs 6.1). Holguin's location score of 8.8 outpaces Costa Dorada's 8.1. Both share identical service and sleep quality scores. If you want a well-rounded Cuban family all-inclusive with strong rooms, a real beach, and a full activity program, go to Iberostar Selection Holguin. If you want a more stripped-back Dominican Republic family option in Puerto Plata at a comparable price, go to Iberostar Waves Costa Dorada.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a highly rated, amenity-rich Cuban all-inclusive with a kids club, waterpark for little ones, babysitting, archery, snorkelling, spa, and nightclub on a strong beach in Holguin, and who prioritise room quality and cleanliness above all.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who prefer the Dominican Republic over Cuba and are happy with a more pared-back resort in Puerto Plata, where value remains solid and service matches Holguin, but expectations around beach quality and on-site activities should be set lower.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations suit a November-to-April dry season visit when rainfall is lowest and temperatures are most comfortable. Cuba's Holguin coast can see hurricane-season humidity from June through October, and Puerto Plata in the Dominican Republic follows a similar weather pattern. Shoulder months of May and November offer quieter resorts and competitive pricing at both properties.","activities":"At Iberostar Selection Holguin, guests can snorkel directly off the beach, take yoga and archery sessions, use the tennis courts, and explore Cuba's second-largest city, Holguin, with its colonial plazas and nearby Guardalavaca bay. At Iberostar Waves Costa Dorada, Puerto Plata's cable car up Mount Isabel de Torres, 27 Waterfalls of Damajagua, and amber museum give guests strong off-resort excursion options beyond the property's beach."},"iberostar-origin-laguna-azul-vs-iberostar-selection-holguin":{"keyDifferences":"Iberostar Origin Laguna Azul and Iberostar Selection Holguin are both Cuban family all-inclusives within the same hotel group, but their ratings tell meaningfully different stories. Selection Holguin outscores Laguna Azul across nearly every category: overall (9 vs 8), rooms (9 vs 7.3), cleanliness (9 vs 7.7), service (8.7 vs 7.6), value (8.7 vs 7.5), and sleep quality (8.1 vs 7.4). Laguna Azul's one clear advantage is beach (9 vs 8), and its location score is competitive (8 vs 8.8). Holguin carries a stronger amenity package — archery, waterpark for little kids, nightclub, spa, babysitting, and snorkelling — making it a more complete family resort on paper. Laguna Azul's atmosphere (6.1) and pool (5.8) ratings are noticeably weak, suggesting a property that underdelivers beyond its excellent beach. If you want a superior room product, cleaner facilities, and better service in a well-rounded Cuban family resort, Holguin is the stronger choice. If the beach is your single priority, Laguna Azul's 9-rated shoreline is hard to argue with.","whoShouldChooseA":"Beach-obsessed families and couples who are willing to accept weaker food, pool, and atmosphere scores in exchange for one of Cuba's best-rated stretches of sand. Best suited to guests who will spend most of their day on the beach and have modest expectations of everything else.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a well-rounded Cuban all-inclusive with strong room quality, cleanliness, and service scores. The kids club, babysitting, archery, waterpark, and nightclub make Holguin a particularly good fit for families with children of varying ages who want more than just a beach.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Cuba's dry season, running November through April, when rainfall is low and temperatures sit in the mid-to-high 20s Celsius. The summer months bring higher humidity and hurricane-season risk, peaking August through October. December through February is the most reliably pleasant window, though it also attracts the highest demand and prices across both properties.","activities":"Both resorts offer beach access, snorkelling, tennis, yoga, swim-up bars, evening entertainment, and buffet dining. Holguin adds archery, a small waterpark for young children, a nightclub, spa, gym, and babysitting to its roster. Off-resort, the Holguin region offers excursions to Guardalavaca, the Bahía de Naranjo natural park, and local cultural sites in Holguin city, accessible from either property."},"hard-rock-hotel-vallarta-vs-heaven-at-the-hard-rock-hotel-riviera-maya":{"keyDifferences":"Hard Rock Hotel Vallarta is a large family all-inclusive on Banderas Bay in Nuevo Vallarta with a kids club, teen club, pool slides, arcade, babysitting, heated pool, and rooms for groups of five or more, scoring a notably stronger beach rating of 6.8 versus Heaven's 4.8. Heaven at the Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya is an adults-only section of the Hard Rock Riviera Maya property in Puerto Aventuras, offering a quieter, couples-focused experience with diving and tennis added to the mix, but a weaker beach and a slightly lower atmosphere score of 7.1 versus Vallarta's 7.4. Both resorts match exactly on overall score (9.1), food (7.3), and pool (7.3), and sit at the same price tier, so the decision is almost entirely about who is traveling. Vallarta clearly wins on family infrastructure and beach quality; Heaven wins on adult exclusivity and access to diving. If you want a Pacific-coast family Hard Rock with strong service, a real beach, and full kids programming, choose Vallarta. If you want an adults-only Caribbean Hard Rock experience with diving, choose Heaven.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and mixed groups who want a full-service Pacific-coast Hard Rock with kids and teen clubs, babysitting, pool slides, arcade, and large-group room configurations on a beach that scores meaningfully better than the Riviera Maya alternative.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want the Hard Rock brand in an adults-only setting on the Riviera Maya, with diving, tennis, and a quieter atmosphere, and who are not prioritizing beach quality as a deciding factor.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season between November and April, when rainfall is minimal and humidity drops. Vallarta's Pacific shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates before peak crowds arrive. Heaven on the Riviera Maya shares the Caribbean coast's hurricane season risk from June through October, so late spring or early winter visits are the safest bets for calm weather at both properties.","activities":"Hard Rock Vallarta guests can fish Banderas Bay, explore the Marietas Islands by boat, and access the resort's arcade and pool slides on-site, with Puerto Vallarta's historic Malecón a short drive away. Heaven guests can dive the Riviera Maya's reef system directly through the resort, play tennis, fish offshore, and reach Tulum ruins or Xel-Há ecological park within a 30-to-45-minute drive of Puerto Aventuras."},"hard-rock-hotel-cancun-vs-heaven-at-the-hard-rock-hotel-riviera-maya":{"keyDifferences":"Hard Rock Hotel Cancun is a large family all-inclusive on Cancun's Hotel Zone with a waterpark for little kids, kids club, rooms for 5+ guests, and pets allowed, sitting on a strong beach rated 8.0 and earning an overall 8.8. Heaven at the Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya is an adults-only all-inclusive in Puerto Aventuras on the Riviera Maya, rated slightly higher overall at 9.1, but with a notably weak beach score of just 4.8 compared to Cancun's 8.0 — a meaningful gap for beach-focused travelers. Heaven adds a nightclub, diving, and fishing that Cancun lacks, and edges Cancun on value (8.6 vs 8.4), but its atmosphere rating of 7.1 trails Cancun's 7.3. Food scores are similarly modest at both (7.5 vs 7.3). Cancun wins on location (8.8 vs 8.3) and beach quality. If you want a family Hard Rock experience with a strong beach and kids facilities in Cancun, choose Resort A. If you want an adults-only Hard Rock with a nightclub, diving, and fishing in the Riviera Maya and can accept a weaker beach, choose Resort B.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want a well-located Cancun all-inclusive with a strong beach, waterpark for little kids, a kids club, swim-up bar, and rooms large enough for 5 or more guests, including pet-friendly accommodations.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want an adults-only Hard Rock experience in the Riviera Maya with a nightclub, diving, and fishing, and prioritize a lively evening atmosphere and slightly better value over beach quality.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season between December and April, when rainfall is minimal and temperatures are warm without being extreme. Cancun and the Riviera Maya share similar climate patterns. July and August are busiest and most humid. Hurricane season runs June through November, with September being the highest-risk month for both locations.","activities":"Hard Rock Cancun guests can explore the Hotel Zone's bars, restaurants, and shopping, or take day trips to Isla Mujeres and Chichen Itza. Heaven at the Hard Rock Riviera Maya sits near Puerto Aventuras marina, giving guests easy access to diving the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, sportfishing charters, Xel-Ha eco-park, Tulum ruins, and cenote swimming — a richer menu of off-property adventure for active travelers."},"hard-rock-hotel-and-casino-punta-cana-vs-heaven-at-the-hard-rock-hotel-riviera-maya":{"keyDifferences":"Hard Rock Punta Cana is a large family all-inclusive in the Dominican Republic's Bavaro area rated 8.6 overall, with a waterpark, kids club, teen club, lazy river, mini golf, casino, and babysitting at a mid-market price point. Heaven at the Hard Rock Riviera Maya is an adults-only section of the Hard Rock Puerto Aventuras property in Mexico, rated higher overall at 9.1 and priced at premium level, with diving, tennis, fishing, and a notably cleaner, quieter experience reflected in its 9.0 cleanliness and 9.0 service scores. The beach gap is significant: Punta Cana scores 7.3 versus a low 4.8 at Heaven, making the Dominican property the clear winner for beach holidays. Heaven compensates with stronger room scores (8.7 vs 8.5), superior service, and a more refined adults-only atmosphere, though its atmosphere rating (7.1) actually trails Punta Cana (7.4). Food ratings are nearly identical at 7.3 and 7.4. Punta Cana offers broader family infrastructure; Heaven delivers a more polished, quieter, adults-only experience at a considerably higher price.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a high-energy Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a waterpark, kids and teen clubs, casino, mini golf, and lazy river at a competitive mid-market price on a solid beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups seeking a premium, quieter Mexico all-inclusive with exceptional service and cleanliness scores, diving, tennis, and fishing in a more refined atmosphere, and who are not prioritising beach quality.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations offer warm weather year-round. Punta Cana's peak season runs December through April when rainfall is lowest. The Riviera Maya similarly peaks December to April, with summer bringing heat and humidity to both. Hurricane season affects both regions June through November, with September and October carrying the highest risk.","activities":"Hard Rock Punta Cana guests can access the resort's casino, waterpark, mini golf, and golf course, with nearby Bavaro beach excursions and cenote day trips available. Heaven Riviera Maya guests can dive the Mesoamerican Reef, fish offshore, and explore the nearby town of Puerto Aventuras, with Tulum ruins, cenotes, and Cozumel ferry trips all within easy reach."},"hard-rock-hotel-los-cabos-vs-heaven-at-the-hard-rock-hotel-riviera-maya":{"keyDifferences":"Hard Rock Hotel Los Cabos is a large family all-inclusive on the Pacific side of Cabo San Lucas with a waterpark, kids club, teen club, babysitting, heated pools, and a pets policy, scoring a strong 9.3 on rooms and cleanliness. Heaven at the Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya is an adults-only section of the Hard Rock Riviera Maya property in Puerto Aventuras on the Caribbean coast, with diving, fishing, and a more stripped-back amenity set. Los Cabos edges ahead overall at 8.9 vs 9.1 for Heaven, though Heaven scores marginally higher overall despite lower food (7.3 vs 7.7) and pool ratings (7.3 vs 7.6). The beach gap is notable: Los Cabos scores just 3.5 vs Heaven's 4.8, reflecting the rougher Pacific surf typical of Cabo. Los Cabos wins on rooms (9.3 vs 8.7) and service (9.1 vs 9.0). Heaven adds diving and fishing that Los Cabos lacks, while Los Cabos counters with a waterpark and full family infrastructure. Both sit at the same price tier.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a polished Pacific-coast Hard Rock experience with a waterpark, kids and teen clubs, babysitting, heated pools, and top-rated rooms and service. Also suits pet owners, given the rare pets-allowed policy at an all-inclusive property.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults and couples who want a quieter, Caribbean-facing Hard Rock all-inclusive with access to diving and fishing, without the energy of a family resort. Suits those who prioritise a more serene atmosphere over an expansive amenity list and prefer the calmer Caribbean beach over Pacific surf.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos is best November through May, avoiding summer hurricane season and heat peaks. Heaven at Riviera Maya on the Caribbean side also peaks December through April, sidestepping the June to October hurricane window. Both properties are busiest during US and Canadian school holidays in winter and spring, so travelling in November or early December offers the best balance of weather and lower crowds.","activities":"At Los Cabos, guests can arrange excursions to the iconic El Arco rock formation, ATV desert tours, whale watching from January to March, snorkelling at Cabo Pulmo, and deep-sea fishing. At Heaven in Puerto Aventuras, guests can explore the nearby Riviera Maya cenotes, visit Tulum ruins, take day trips to Coba, snorkel at Akumal with sea turtles, and access the resort's own dive operation directly from the property."},"hard-rock-hotel-riviera-maya-vs-heaven-at-the-hard-rock-hotel-riviera-maya":{"keyDifferences":"Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya and Heaven at the Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya share the same Puerto Aventuras location, price tier, and core ratings — identical scores for pool (7.3), atmosphere (7.1), location (8.3), room (8.7), cleanliness (9.0), and nearly identical beach ratings (4.5 vs 4.8). The meaningful differences are in who each property is built for and what infrastructure supports them. Hard Rock Riviera Maya is a full family resort with a waterpark for little and big kids, lazy river, arcade, kids club, and babysitting — amenities entirely absent from Heaven. Heaven, the adults-only wing, edges ahead on overall rating (9.1 vs 8.8), service (9.0 vs 8.9), and value (8.6 vs 8.5), suggesting a quieter, more attentive experience without the operational complexity of managing families. The beach score at both resorts is notably low (under 5), so neither should be chosen primarily for beach quality. The resorts share dining infrastructure, which may explain why food scores are similarly modest at 7.5 and 7.3 respectively.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of any age who want a large Mexican all-inclusive with waterparks, a lazy river, arcade, kids club, and babysitting in Puerto Aventuras. The broad entertainment infrastructure and strong service score make it a reliable choice for parents who want to keep all ages busy.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or adults-only travelers who want the Hard Rock experience in Puerto Aventuras without children present. The marginally higher overall and service scores suggest a more refined atmosphere, and the streamlined amenity list reflects a property focused on adult comfort rather than family programming.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Aventuras sits in the Riviera Maya, where peak season runs December through April with lower humidity, minimal rain, and reliable sunshine. Hurricane season peaks August through October, though the area sits slightly south of the busiest storm tracks. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower prices with mostly good weather. Both resorts share the same seasonal conditions given their co-located setting.","activities":"Both resorts offer diving, tennis, fishing, spa, and evening entertainment including a nightclub. The Riviera Maya location puts guests near Xcaret and Xel-Há eco-parks, cenote diving, the ruins at Tulum and Cobá, and snorkeling along the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef. Puerto Aventuras itself has a marina and dolphin facility. Hard Rock Riviera Maya adds onsite waterparks, a lazy river, and an arcade for families seeking activity without leaving the property."},"hard-rock-hotel-montego-bay-vs-heaven-at-the-hard-rock-hotel-riviera-maya":{"keyDifferences":"Hard Rock Hotel Montego Bay is a family-oriented Jamaican all-inclusive rated exceptionally high on rooms (9.5), cleanliness (9.5), service (9.4), and location (9.1), sitting on a lively stretch near Montego Bay. Heaven at the Hard Rock Hotel Riviera Maya is the adults-only tower of a larger Mexican resort complex in Puerto Aventuras, with strong cleanliness (9.0) and service (9.0) scores but a notably weak beach rating (4.8) versus Montego Bay's 6.7, and a lower atmosphere score (7.1 vs. 7.2). Montego Bay edges ahead on food (7.9 vs. 7.3) and pool (6.9 vs. 7.3 goes to Heaven), while both sit at the same price tier. The Montego Bay property is built around families and a prime Jamaican coastal location, while Heaven trades beach quality for an adults-only environment with diving, fishing, a nightclub, and spa access. If you want a family-friendly Jamaican Hard Rock with outstanding rooms and service near Montego Bay, choose Resort A. If you want an adults-only Mexican escape with a spa, diving, and nightclub despite a weaker beach, choose Resort B.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who want an exceptionally well-appointed Jamaican all-inclusive with top-rated rooms, spotless facilities, and attentive service in a prime Montego Bay location. Guests who prioritize room quality, cleanliness, and a strong beach setting will find Montego Bay consistently delivers.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults-only travelers seeking a quieter, amenity-rich Mexican resort experience with diving, spa, fishing, and nightclub access in Puerto Aventuras. Best suited to couples or groups who value a relaxed, adult atmosphere over beach quality and don't mind a less impressive shoreline.","whenToVisit":"Montego Bay is best visited December through April when Jamaica's dry season delivers reliable sunshine and lower humidity. Heaven at the Hard Rock Riviera Maya benefits from the same Caribbean dry season window, roughly November through April, avoiding the late-summer Atlantic hurricane season that affects both destinations. Both resorts sit within the hurricane belt, so late August through October carries elevated weather risk regardless of choice.","activities":"Hard Rock Montego Bay puts guests within easy reach of Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls excursions, and ATV tours inland. Heaven at the Hard Rock Riviera Maya offers on-site diving, tennis, fishing, and a spa, with Tulum ruins, cenote swimming, and Xcaret eco-parks reachable from Puerto Aventuras. Both properties deliver evening entertainment and nightclub access, giving active guests structured programming alongside broader regional excursion options."},"hard-rock-hotel-cancun-vs-hard-rock-hotel-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Hard Rock Hotel Cancun and Hard Rock Hotel Vallarta are both premium Mexican family all-inclusives sharing the same brand DNA, identical location scores (8.8), and similar pool ratings (7.3 each), but meaningful differences emerge across service, beach, and amenities. Vallarta pulls ahead on overall score (9.1 vs 8.8), service (9.2 vs 9.0), cleanliness (9.1 vs 9.0), and value (8.8 vs 8.4), while Cancun holds the edge on beach (8.0 vs 6.8) and food (7.5 vs 7.3). Cancun's beach advantage is significant — a 1.2-point gap is hard to ignore. Cancun also offers a waterpark for little kids and accepts pets, while Vallarta counters with a teen club, nightclub, pool slide, arcade, heated pool, babysitting, and a no-reservations restaurant policy. Vallarta suits families who want deeper on-property programming and better service scores; Cancun suits those who prioritize a superior beach experience and traveling with very young children or pets.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with toddlers or young children who want a strong Cancun beachfront experience, a waterpark for little kids, and pet-friendly accommodation. Also ideal for travelers who place a premium on beach quality and don't need a nightclub or teen-focused programming.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with a wider age range — particularly those with teenagers — who want a nightclub, teen club, arcade, heated pool, and babysitting in Nuevo Vallarta. Those who prioritize service ratings and value for money will also find Vallarta the stronger overall performer.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season, roughly December through April, when rain is minimal and humidity manageable. Cancun's peak runs November to April, with hurricane season (June–October) carrying more risk. Vallarta's dry season similarly peaks December to April, with summer months bringing afternoon showers but fewer crowds and lower rates. Shoulder months like May or November offer a balance of good weather and better pricing at both properties.","activities":"Both resorts keep guests well occupied on-property with swim-up bars, evening entertainment, spas, gyms, and buffet dining. Vallarta adds fishing excursions, an arcade, and a nightclub, while Cancun offers tennis. Off-property, Cancun guests have easy access to Isla Mujeres, Chichen Itza day trips, and the Nichupte Lagoon. Vallarta guests can explore Puerto Vallarta's old town, whale-watching tours (winter), zip-lining in Sierra Madre, and boat trips to secluded coves along Banderas Bay."},"hard-rock-hotel-los-cabos-vs-hard-rock-hotel-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Hard Rock Hotel Los Cabos and Hard Rock Hotel Vallarta are both premium Mexican family all-inclusives sharing the same brand DNA, but they diverge meaningfully on beach, rooms, and on-site amenities. Vallarta edges out Los Cabos overall (9.1 vs 8.9) and on service (9.2 vs 9.1), and its beach rating is substantially higher (6.8 vs 3.5), reflecting the calmer Banderas Bay waters of Nuevo Vallarta versus the rougher, swim-unfriendly Pacific surf at Cabo. Los Cabos counters with superior rooms (9.3 vs 8.8), better sleep quality (8.8 vs 8.1), and exclusive amenities including a waterpark for older kids, tennis courts, and a pets-allowed policy. Vallarta offers practical advantages like restaurants without reservation requirements, rooms accommodating five or more guests, a pool slide, arcade, and fishing. Both carry the same price tier, but Los Cabos trades a usable beach for a stronger room product and more entertainment infrastructure, while Vallarta delivers a genuinely swimmable beach alongside solid family-activity coverage.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who prioritize exceptional room quality, a waterpark, and tennis, and who are unbothered by a beach too rough for swimming. Also the clear choice for guests traveling with pets or those who want Los Cabos's dramatic desert-meets-ocean scenery over a conventional beach holiday.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a swimmable beach as the centerpiece of their vacation, with added conveniences like no-reservation restaurants, large rooms for groups of five or more, an arcade, and fishing excursions in the calmer, lush surroundings of Nuevo Vallarta.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos is best October through June, before summer hurricane season and peak heat arrive; December through April offers near-perfect dry weather. Vallarta's high season runs November through April when Banderas Bay is calm and rain-free. Both destinations share a similar seasonal rhythm, but Vallarta's summer shoulder season can bring afternoon showers while remaining warm and green.","activities":"Los Cabos guests can explore El Arco rock formation by boat, go sport fishing, visit the famous Lover's Beach, and ATV through the desert. Vallarta guests can take whale-watching tours from November through March, explore the cobblestoned Sayulita surf village, zip-line through jungle canopy, and arrange sport fishing. Both resorts offer on-site spa, nightclub, and evening entertainment programs to keep families occupied without leaving the property."},"hard-rock-hotel-and-casino-punta-cana-vs-hard-rock-hotel-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Hard Rock Hotel & Casino Punta Cana is a massive Dominican Republic family resort in Bavaro with a full waterpark, lazy river, casino, golf course, adult pool, and mini golf at a mid-market price point. Hard Rock Hotel Vallarta is a smaller Mexican Pacific family resort in Nuevo Vallarta, priced significantly higher at $$$$, with a heated pool, arcade, and fishing access but no waterpark or casino. The Dominican property scores higher on beach (7.3 vs 6.8) and pool (7.6 vs 7.3), while Vallarta leads on overall score (9.1 vs 8.6), cleanliness (9.1 vs 8.7), service (9.2 vs 8.6), room quality (8.8 vs 8.5), and location (8.8 vs 7.9). Notably, Vallarta commands a premium price yet delivers better service and cleanliness scores, while Punta Cana offers far more amenity volume — waterslides, lazy river, casino, golf — at a lower price. If you want maximum amenities and waterpark infrastructure at a better price in the Dominican Republic, go to Punta Cana. If you want sharper service, a cleaner property, and a stronger Pacific Mexico location at a premium, go to Vallarta.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a large, amenity-packed Dominican Republic all-inclusive with a full waterpark, lazy river, casino, golf course, and adult pool at a mid-market price. Best for those who prioritize activity volume and value over top-tier service polish.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families and couples willing to pay a premium for noticeably better service (9.2), cleanliness (9.1), and a strong Nuevo Vallarta location. Ideal for those who want a refined Pacific Mexico Hard Rock experience without needing a waterpark or casino on-site.","whenToVisit":"Punta Cana enjoys warm, dry weather from December through April, with hurricane season running June through November — shoulder months like May and early June offer lower prices. Nuevo Vallarta is best visited November through April during Mexico's dry season; summer months bring humidity and rain from the Pacific but rates drop meaningfully, making it a reasonable value trade-off for budget-conscious families.","activities":"Punta Cana guests can explore the Bavaro beach strip, take excursions to Saona Island, go deep-sea fishing, or visit nearby golf courses beyond the resort's own. Vallarta guests benefit from proximity to Puerto Vallarta's old town, whale-watching tours (in season), zip-lining in the Sierra Madre, and sportfishing charters — the location score of 8.8 reflects genuine off-resort excursion richness compared to Punta Cana's more resort-contained experience."},"hard-rock-hotel-riviera-maya-vs-hard-rock-hotel-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Both are large family Hard Rock all-inclusives in Mexico at the same price level, but they differ meaningfully in beach quality, water amenities, and service ratings. Hard Rock Riviera Maya scores a striking 4.5 on beach versus Vallarta's 6.8, a significant gap that matters if beach time is central to your trip. Riviera Maya compensates with an extensive waterpark offering for both little and big kids, plus a lazy river and diving — a more comprehensive water-activity lineup than Vallarta. Vallarta counters with a notably higher service rating (9.2 vs 8.9), a teen club Riviera Maya lacks, and rooms that accommodate five or more guests. Vallarta also rates higher overall (9.1 vs 8.8) and on value (8.8 vs 8.5). Riviera Maya's location in Puerto Aventuras gives access to cenotes and Mayan ruins; Vallarta's Nuevo Vallarta location is closer to a genuine Mexican town. Food ratings are similarly modest at both — 7.5 at Riviera Maya, 7.3 at Vallarta — so neither resort stands out for dining.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with younger and older kids who want maximum water-based entertainment — a full waterpark for all ages, a lazy river, diving, and a swim-up bar — and don't mind a weaker beach in exchange for strong overall amenities and proximity to cenotes and Mayan ruins.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with teens or large groups needing rooms for five or more who prioritize exceptional service, a better beach, and a location close to the culture and energy of Puerto Vallarta and Nuevo Vallarta's town life.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season, roughly December through April, when rain is minimal and humidity manageable. Riviera Maya's Caribbean side can see hurricane activity from June through November, with September the riskiest month. Vallarta on the Pacific also has a rainy season peaking July through September but tends to receive shorter, sharper showers rather than prolonged storms. Shoulder months of November and May offer value at both.","activities":"At Riviera Maya, guests can explore nearby cenotes, visit Tulum's clifftop ruins, and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef — the world's second largest. Puerto Aventuras marina offers deep-sea fishing and dolphin encounters. At Vallarta, the Sierra Madre mountains provide zip-lining and jungle tours, while Banderas Bay offers whale watching from December through March, sailing, and sport fishing. Both resorts have on-site arcades, spas, evening entertainment, and nightclubs."},"hard-rock-hotel-montego-bay-vs-hard-rock-hotel-vallarta":{"keyDifferences":"Hard Rock Hotel Montego Bay and Hard Rock Hotel Vallarta are both upscale family all-inclusives under the same brand at the same price tier, but they differ meaningfully in location quality, room performance, and sleep experience. Montego Bay scores a standout 9.1 for location and 9.5 for both rooms and cleanliness, with a sleep quality of 8.7, suggesting a quieter, more polished in-room experience. Vallarta sits in Nuevo Vallarta on Mexico's Pacific coast and scores 8.8 for rooms and 8.1 for sleep quality, a notable 0.6-point gap that may reflect noise or room insulation issues. Vallarta edges ahead on atmosphere (7.4 vs 7.2) and pool (7.3 vs 6.9), and its amenity list is extensive — teen club, arcade, pool slide, heated pool, babysitting, and fishing. Montego Bay's food rating is marginally stronger (7.9 vs 7.3). Both score identically on value (8.8) and similarly on beach (6.7 vs 6.8). Montego Bay feels like the stronger choice for room quality and location prestige; Vallarta wins on breadth of family-specific amenities.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who prioritize exceptional rooms, cleanliness, and a high-scoring location close to Montego Bay's airport and attractions. A strong pick if sleep quality and a polished in-room experience matter as much as the pool deck.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with kids of all ages who want the widest possible range of on-site activities — pool slides, an arcade, a teen club, babysitting, fishing, and a heated pool — in a large Nuevo Vallarta resort with solid service and easy Pacific Mexico access.","whenToVisit":"Montego Bay is best November through mid-December and January through April, avoiding the June–November hurricane season peak. Nuevo Vallarta enjoys a dry season from November through April with low humidity and reliable sun; summer months bring heat and occasional Pacific storms. Both properties sit in their respective sweet spots during the northern winter, making December through March the overlap window for ideal conditions at either resort.","activities":"Montego Bay guests are minutes from Doctor's Cave Beach, Dunn's River Falls, ATV tours, and the Hip Strip's bars and craft markets. Vallarta guests have Nuevo Vallarta's marina, whale-watching excursions from November to March, zip-lining in the Sierra Madre foothills, and the boutiques and restaurants of Puerto Vallarta's Zona Romántica a short drive south. On-site, Vallarta's arcade, pool slide, and fishing add variety beyond the standard beach-and-pool routine."},"marriott-cancun-vs-marriott-miches-beach":{"keyDifferences":"Marriott Cancun and Marriott Miches Beach are both upscale family all-inclusives at the same price level with identical cleanliness (9.4), service (9.1), and value (8.6) scores, but they diverge meaningfully on beach, pool, and amenity depth. Cancun scores higher on beach (9.0 vs 8.3), pool (7.3 vs 7.1), and overall (9.0 vs 8.8), while Miches edges ahead on sleep quality (9.1 vs 8.6) and room score (9.0 vs 8.9). The amenity gap is significant: Cancun offers a kids club, pool slide, arcade, heated pool, diving, fishing, spa, babysitting, watersports rentals, swim-up bar, and a waterpark for little kids, while Miches provides only a gym, buffet, swim-up bar, and free Wi-Fi. Cancun sits on the well-established Hotel Zone strip with easy airport access (location 8.8), while Miches is a remote, undeveloped stretch of the Dominican Republic's northeast coast, offering seclusion over convenience. Cancun charges for Wi-Fi; Miches includes it free.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want a full-service Cancun all-inclusive with a kids club, waterpark, arcade, babysitting, diving, spa, and a top-rated beach on a well-connected resort strip. The depth of on-site amenities makes it the stronger choice for guests who want everything in one place.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples who prioritize seclusion, quiet, and exceptional sleep quality over amenity breadth. Miches is a remote, largely undeveloped corner of the Dominican Republic best suited to guests who want a peaceful, off-the-beaten-path Caribbean escape rather than a programmed resort experience.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April during the dry season. Cancun's Hotel Zone is reliably calm through spring; seaweed (sargassum) can affect Cancun beaches May through October. Miches, on the Dominican Republic's northeast coast, faces Atlantic swells and higher rainfall June through November. For either resort, January through March offers the most settled conditions.","activities":"Cancun guests can dive, fish, rent watersports equipment on-site, and access the Hotel Zone's restaurants, shopping, and Isla Mujeres day trips nearby. Miches is adjacent to Los Haitises National Park, one of the Dominican Republic's most dramatic natural reserves, offering mangrove boat tours and cave exploration. On-site, both resorts offer swim-up bar access; broader activity programming is far stronger at Cancun."},"delta-hotels-by-marriott-riviera-nayarit-vs-marriott-cancun":{"keyDifferences":"Delta Hotels Riviera Nayarit sits in La Cruz de Huanacaxtle on Mexico's Pacific coast, a quieter, less-developed setting than Cancun, with standout room (9.0), cleanliness (9.1), and value (8.7) scores, but a notably weak beach rating of 3.0 versus Marriott Cancun's 9.0 — the single most important gap between these two properties. Marriott Cancun counters with a superior food score (7.8 vs 7.1), a heated pool, pool slide, waterpark for little kids, arcade, babysitting, watersports rentals, diving, swim-up bar, and a fishing program, making it the more activity-rich option for families. Delta Nayarit offers a lazy river, adult pool, and a pet-friendly policy Cancun lacks, and its atmosphere and location suit guests seeking a low-key Pacific escape over a polished Cancun hotel zone experience. Both sit at the same price tier and carry nearly identical overall scores (8.9 vs 9.0), but the beach differential and Cancun's broader family amenity set make Marriott Cancun the stronger choice for beach-focused families, while Delta Nayarit suits those prioritizing rooms, tranquility, and value on the Pacific side.","whoShouldChooseA":"Travelers prioritizing an exceptionally clean, well-appointed room and a quieter Pacific Mexico atmosphere in a less-touristed area. Ideal for couples, remote workers, or families with pets who value tranquility, a lazy river, and strong value over a premier beach or an extensive activity roster.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a classic Cancun hotel zone all-inclusive with a world-class beach, babysitting, a waterpark for little kids, pool slide, arcade, diving, watersports rentals, and a swim-up bar. Best for those whose holiday centers on beach time and keeping children entertained with a wide menu of on-site activities.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season, roughly November through April, when rain is minimal and humidity manageable. Cancun's Caribbean side sees its peak beach conditions and calmest seas in winter and spring; Riviera Nayarit on the Pacific is driest and sunniest from December through March. Both locations carry elevated hurricane risk from August through October.","activities":"At Delta Nayarit, guests can explore the charming marina village of La Cruz de Huanacaxtle, take whale-watching tours in season, and visit nearby Sayulita or Punta Mita. At Marriott Cancun, guests can dive the Mesoamerican Reef, rent watersports equipment on-site, visit Isla Mujeres by ferry, or explore the Mayan ruins at Tulum and Chichen Itza on day trips from the hotel zone."}}
